WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-IN

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:04.280
Today is for any young Indian boy or girl,
under the age of 25,

00:00:04.360 --> 00:00:07.400
who wants to start
a consumer electronic brand.

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:30.400
Start? Okay, ready?

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:32.840
All right.

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:45.040
Hi, guys, thank you for coming home
and doing this.

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:50.160
I think Carl had to travel
from further, further away.

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:54.480
-Mm-hmm.
-Amit and Rahul live closer in Delhi.

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:59.240
So maybe we start
by speaking about ourselves,

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:04.360
giving my audience an intro of who we are,

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:07.600
how we got to be where we are.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:11.120
Rahul is already a friend of mine,
so I know a lot about him.

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:13.280
But maybe we start with Carl.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.200
Sure. I'm happy to be here.

00:01:16.280 --> 00:01:21.160
It took a while for us to schedule it
back and forth, but we're finally here.

00:01:21.920 --> 00:01:23.000
So I'm Carl.

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:25.960
I'm one of the co-founders of a company
called Nothing.

00:01:26.960 --> 00:01:29.880
But ever since I can remember,
I was always a tech fan.

00:01:30.720 --> 00:01:32.360
I grew up in Stockholm, in Sweden.

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:35.800
I remember, my parents got me
the first iPod.

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:38.880
And I was only like 12 at the time.

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:41.920
And the first-generation iPod
was very complicated,

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:43.840
because, I don't know
if you guys remember,

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:46.440
-it had the FireWire connection.
-[Rahul] Right.

00:01:46.520 --> 00:01:49.840
I had a PC.
It didn't have the FireWire connection.

00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:52.320
So I had to buy...
First, I got the iPod, I didn't know.

00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:55.960
-I couldn't connect it to the PC.
-Right.

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:58.720
Then I had to buy a PCI card for FireWire,

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:02.800
install that, to even be able
to connect the iPod.

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:04.120
And back then, there was no iTunes,

00:02:04.200 --> 00:02:08.160
so it was RealPlayer to manage the music.

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:11.600
Well, anyway, that product
got me really hooked on technology.

00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:16.240
The scroll wheel was really cool,
and managing the music library,

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:22.080
fixing all the ID3 tags for each song,
getting the album arts perfect.

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:25.840
And a couple of years later,
I was probably...

00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:28.880
So I think I was the first to get the iPod
in my entire school.

00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:33.640
So I was a cool kid among the nerds
in the beginning.

00:02:33.720 --> 00:02:35.440
Where was the school, Carl?

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:36.640
That was in Stockholm.

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:39.440
What year are we talking about?

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:41.400
iPod. When was the iPod?

00:02:41.480 --> 00:02:42.880
2001?

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:44.560
Yeah. You're 36 today, right?

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:47.400
Yeah, I'm 35... turning 36.

00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:49.640
So when I was 12, I got the iPod.

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:51.120
Really excited about that product.

00:02:51.920 --> 00:02:56.200
Then I got the first iPhone
through a friend in the US,

00:02:56.280 --> 00:03:00.000
because the iPhone
was only exclusive with AT&amp;T.

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:02.280
So I had a friend buy it for me,

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:07.680
and then we had to pay
a $450 cancellation fee on the contract,

00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:10.160
and then got it shipped,
and then jailbroke it,

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:11.480
and installed my own SIM card.

00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:13.720
So I was the first among all my friends
to get the iPhone.

00:03:14.480 --> 00:03:17.760
But I think those two products
were super formative for me.

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:19.640
I guess the third thing
that happened was...

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:22.560
Then I got the iPad.

00:03:22.640 --> 00:03:25.200
I forgot which year,
but the first year the iPad came out.

00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:29.800
And I don't know if you guys remember,
it used to have a skeuomorphic UI.

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:33.400
So, basically, the UI tried to mimic
how things look like in real life.

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:38.680
And when you swipe from the bottom,
there was a control panel.

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:40.040
And it was like metallic.

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:43.280
So you had like a volume knob
that was brushed metal.

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:45.360
But when you tilted the iPad,

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:49.520
the light source of the graphic
also changed.

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:51.120
So, I'm like, "Oh, my God,

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:54.520
like, if Apple thinks about
every little detail like this...

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:59.440
I can trust them on like...
They've figured everything out."

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:04.880
So those three moments made me a big fan
of this industry and of Apple.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:07.360
Do you still feel that way about Apple?

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:09.560
No, it's a very different company now.

00:04:09.640 --> 00:04:11.240
When did it change?

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:13.240
I think the change has been gradual.

00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:17.720
I think the two CEOs have had
a very different approach

00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:18.960
to running the company.

00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:22.560
I mean, the stock price doesn't lie.

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:28.000
I think Tim Cook has done a great job
on the shareholder value creation side.

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:32.120
But when it just comes to inspiring
a young guy or a young person

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:36.880
to take a career in tech, I think
the old Apple was way better at that.

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:40.040
So really inspired by those products.

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:43.440
And then, I was chronically online
as a kid.

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:44.880
My parents were busy.

00:04:44.960 --> 00:04:48.360
They were always at work,
but I got a laptop computer,

00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:50.880
and I got fibre Internet
at a very young age

00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:53.960
because the infrastructure
was pretty well developed in Sweden.

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:57.840
-At 12, you had...
-Fibre.

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:02.240
-And phone, access to phone.
-I had a Nokia 3210.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:03.760
-At 12 years old.
-Yeah.

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:07.760
So then fast forward to later,
so I had the Internet.

00:05:07.840 --> 00:05:12.760
Started making friends online
'cause I felt like the friends around me,

00:05:12.840 --> 00:05:14.960
they only saw a very small part
of the world.

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:18.560
Whereas online,
you can connect with anybody.

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:20.240
So I made a very good friend.

00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:23.640
We were chatting on MSN Messenger
every single day

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:26.200
about how to make money online.

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:29.640
We were both writing blogs
and making websites and all that stuff.

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:34.000
And then, he then became
the youngest founder

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:35.920
to get into Y Combinator.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:37.920
And he's, like, two years younger than me.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
-Wow.
-I was very jealous when he got in.

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:42.720
He was probably 17 or something.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:45.080
And so that was also my plan.

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:47.440
So after uni,
I'm going to apply for Y Combinator.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
So it was a different time,
when consumer Internet

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:53.440
was still very, like, booming
with Facebook and all that.

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:55.800
What's really working for Y Combinator?

00:05:56.400 --> 00:05:59.240
We're trying to start something like that
called WTFund,

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:04.840
which is a non-dilutive grant programme
where we don't take equities.

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:10.120
It's not too much like Y Combinator,
but a different version of it.

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:12.120
Why have they been so successful?

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:14.160
I don't know. I haven't thought about it.

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:16.480
When I was young,
I just wanted to go there,

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:19.400
because I thought that was the place
you had to go

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:22.680
if you wanted to become
a Silicon Valley founder.

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:28.320
They made a lot of... They've been
a kingmaker in the industry, I think.

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:32.280
I'm sure they have some
unique way of figuring out

00:06:32.360 --> 00:06:34.920
who's a good fit in terms of founders.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:36.800
And then they have their brand.

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:39.440
And then they prepare
the founders for, like...

00:06:40.280 --> 00:06:43.480
the subsequent funding rounds
in a pretty smart way.

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:45.720
Like, even when I'm raising money,

00:06:45.800 --> 00:06:49.360
sometimes, I reference
the Y Combinator docs,

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:51.280
like, the guides for how to raise money.

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:55.080
Do you think it's network
or access to capital?

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:57.240
The capital is very little, actually.

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:00.160
-Half a million.
-Yeah. It was even less before.

00:07:00.240 --> 00:07:02.400
And they take a lot of stake
for that money.

00:07:03.960 --> 00:07:05.240
But I think it's a branding thing.

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:08.600
Like, once you have that brand
on your resume,

00:07:08.680 --> 00:07:10.280
your next round will be a lot easier.

00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:12.680
And your next, next round
will be a lot easier.

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:14.840
And they do have good content to teach.

00:07:14.920 --> 00:07:17.680
Maybe that's their user acquisition.
Right?

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:22.200
Having good content to teach young people
why you should start a company,

00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:23.520
how you should start a company.

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:27.680
And then once they're ready,
they inbound to YC.

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:29.280
Okay. And then?

00:07:29.360 --> 00:07:34.800
So I was planning to go to YC,
and then I was playing a lot of games.

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:37.360
A lot of League of Legends at that time.

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:40.760
-It wasn't very...
-Games as in, like, video games?

00:07:40.840 --> 00:07:43.360
-Yeah, like online computer games.
-Online games.

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:47.800
So I was a bit lazy,
so I didn't write my application.

00:07:47.880 --> 00:07:53.200
But then I got a phone call from the CEO
of Meizu back then.

00:07:53.840 --> 00:07:56.920
He's like, "Hey,
we want to become more international.

00:07:57.720 --> 00:07:59.200
Do you want to help?"

00:07:59.280 --> 00:08:00.320
So I had like two options.

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:02.760
Either I have to write
my application for YC,

00:08:02.840 --> 00:08:05.400
or I can go to China to join Meizu.

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:11.880
I took the path of least resistance
and didn't finish my university.

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:15.280
I moved to Hong Kong in 2011.

00:08:15.960 --> 00:08:17.280
-For Meizu?
-For Meizu.

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:23.520
Just for the...
Meizu was the Apple of China at that time.

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:26.120
They were the first one
to come up with a phone. Yeah.

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:28.800
-The first Chinese smartphone.
-Yes, it was Meizu.

00:08:29.480 --> 00:08:34.520
They made really great MP3 players before.
That's when I got to know the company.

00:08:37.560 --> 00:08:40.680
And then, yeah, to be a part
of the beginning of something interesting,

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:41.760
that's why I moved.

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:44.320
And also out of laziness,

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:46.760
to not have to write the thesis
for university

00:08:46.840 --> 00:08:48.960
and the application for YC.

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:51.920
And the reason why he reached out to me
was because,

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.720
after I discovered their products in 2006,

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:58.880
I made an online fan community
about that company.

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:00.520
And it got quite big.

00:09:00.600 --> 00:09:03.960
We got to like 70,000 users, members.

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:05.520
We were updating, like, people

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:10.200
on the new firmware updates
and customisation, and all that stuff.

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:14.120
And then I think he saw something in that
and decided to call.

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:16.400
So the founder of Meizu
called you himself?

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:18.120
-The CEO.
-Yeah?

00:09:18.200 --> 00:09:20.120
-The professional CEO.
-Wow.

00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:23.240
Okay. And you were in Nokia
for three months?

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:26.480
Yeah, that was before that.
Just for like a summer internship.

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:28.720
Right. And after Meizu?

00:09:29.600 --> 00:09:30.920
So I didn't stay that long.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:33.680
I think I stayed, like, a year.

00:09:34.800 --> 00:09:37.960
I left because I quickly realised
that it was a family business.

00:09:38.560 --> 00:09:40.720
So the key positions
were all family members.

00:09:40.800 --> 00:09:44.960
And it's hard to build a very big company
like that, I think.

00:09:45.640 --> 00:09:48.440
Was the professional CEO a family member?

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:49.840
He wasn't.

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:53.200
But imagine how hard it was for him
to do his work.

00:09:53.800 --> 00:09:56.440
But head of finance,
head of international.

00:09:57.520 --> 00:09:58.520
It's probably not gonna work.

00:09:58.600 --> 00:10:00.760
So I started applying for jobs.

00:10:01.360 --> 00:10:02.560
I applied for Xiaomi.

00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:06.680
I applied for OPPO.

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:10.200
I applied for another company
that's no longer here, called Smartisan.

00:10:11.240 --> 00:10:12.240
Yeah, yeah.

00:10:13.680 --> 00:10:15.160
Smartisan had that... They had that...

00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:16.600
This is a Bangalore-based startup, right?

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:21.240
No, no, no. This is based out of Beijing.

00:10:21.320 --> 00:10:23.000
Yeah, back in the day.

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:25.560
With their Hammer UI and all that.

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:26.760
-Is it?
-Mm-hmm.

00:10:26.840 --> 00:10:27.840
Yeah.

00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:30.080
-Yeah, they did some good design.
-[Rahul] Yeah.

00:10:30.160 --> 00:10:32.360
The Smartisan guy never responded to me.

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:35.160
I interviewed at Xiaomi and OPPO.

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:41.320
And to be honest, I think back then,
Xiaomi was a rocket ship.

00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:42.680
Like, venture-backed.

00:10:42.760 --> 00:10:47.960
I think Sequoia and a bunch of
really well-known VCs were backing them.

00:10:48.040 --> 00:10:49.920
-DST and all of them. Yeah.
-DST.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:54.240
So I was actually quite intimidated
by the people I met there.

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:58.360
Like, everybody that interviewed with me
at Xiaomi felt very aggressive,

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:00.760
like, results-oriented, very smart.

00:11:01.480 --> 00:11:03.360
Whereas when I interviewed with OPPO,

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:07.040
I felt more like a traditional
manufacturing culture.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.120
So selfishly,
I thought that if I joined this

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:13.760
less aggressive culture, I can shine more.

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:16.120
Did you get a job at Xiaomi as well?

00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:18.360
I dropped out of the interview process

00:11:18.440 --> 00:11:22.160
after we made an agreement
with OPPO at that time.

00:11:22.240 --> 00:11:27.000
Yeah, so then OPPO also saw
the rise of Xiaomi.

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:29.200
Because Xiaomi was selling phones online,

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:31.080
they were the first
to do that in the world.

00:11:31.160 --> 00:11:33.560
And they could undercut other people

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:35.480
because the distribution cost
was a lot lower.

00:11:36.160 --> 00:11:42.560
So OPPO was also trying to find a strategy
to hedge against the rise of Xiaomi.

00:11:43.520 --> 00:11:45.560
So they created a new brand
called OnePlus.

00:11:46.640 --> 00:11:48.560
It was supposed to be online,

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:51.160
by leveraging the supply chain
that OPPO had built.

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:53.000
Because Xiaomi was
still building their supply chain,

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:54.240
they didn't have those advantages.

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:56.320
Is OnePlus still a part of OPPO?

00:11:56.400 --> 00:11:58.880
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:01.680
So then, I had just joined.

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:07.760
And I was like, "Hey, I can't just join
and then you start a new company.

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:10.120
Like, I want to be a part
of the new company."

00:12:10.200 --> 00:12:13.240
But then I was told that the new company
is not for international,

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:15.800
it's just for China.

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:17.240
To fight Xiaomi in China.

00:12:17.840 --> 00:12:20.880
But I kind of made the case
that it doesn't hurt, right?

00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:24.760
Like, if I can run international,
it's all free money.

00:12:25.320 --> 00:12:28.240
Like, you guys can still focus on China,

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:30.640
and everything else is just extra
on top of that.

00:12:30.720 --> 00:12:34.520
So that's how I, in the beginning,
got the opportunity.

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:38.800
I was only 24 to run international.

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:41.320
Were you more a marketing person
at this point

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:43.680
or were you more
the technical person at this point?

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:46.440
I was more marketing, I think.

00:12:46.520 --> 00:12:48.240
I was kind of like a...

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:50.200
'Cause ever since I was 12
when I got that computer,

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:51.520
I started making websites.

00:12:51.600 --> 00:12:54.000
And then I built traffic,
sold advertising.

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:55.760
So like just...

00:12:55.840 --> 00:12:58.080
I had a deep desire to make money
when I was young.

00:12:58.160 --> 00:13:03.200
So more like business/marketing,
just trying to make it work, hustling.

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:05.080
So that's kind of what we did.

00:13:05.880 --> 00:13:10.480
After one year,
after launching the product at OnePlus,

00:13:10.560 --> 00:13:12.400
China did $100 million in revenue.

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:14.480
International did $200 million.

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:16.840
China lost money,
international made money.

00:13:16.920 --> 00:13:18.800
And then we decided to pivot
the entire company

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:21.320
to be more focused on international.

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:23.800
'Cause the competition in China
was too high.

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:27.400
-Yeah.
-So that was the OnePlus journey.

00:13:27.480 --> 00:13:30.440
Spent seven years at OnePlus.

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:34.280
Very grateful because I was just a kid.

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:39.160
Like, being able to participate
in such a high CapEx industry

00:13:39.240 --> 00:13:42.040
without needing to use my own money.

00:13:42.120 --> 00:13:43.200
I didn't have money.

00:13:44.240 --> 00:13:46.200
So, very grateful
for all those opportunities.

00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:48.360
Allowing me to fail
with a lot of crazy ideas

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:49.480
and learning from those.

00:13:50.800 --> 00:13:53.560
Ultimately, it's kind
of like a CPG strategy

00:13:53.640 --> 00:13:56.760
where we buy components
from different suppliers,

00:13:56.840 --> 00:13:58.680
we package the components,

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:01.160
and we have a unique position
in the market,

00:14:01.240 --> 00:14:04.280
design, brand, and sell the product.

00:14:05.040 --> 00:14:06.280
I had done that for seven years.

00:14:06.360 --> 00:14:09.520
I didn't feel like
that's what I wanted to do my entire life.

00:14:11.560 --> 00:14:15.640
I want to not only implement
other people's technology,

00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:21.880
I also want the opportunity to eventually
impact how people use technology.

00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:23.880
So I knew I had to go independent.

00:14:26.040 --> 00:14:28.760
So I left in 2020, in September.

00:14:29.440 --> 00:14:33.440
And on my birthday,
that was like a birthday gift for myself.

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:38.240
And started this new company
called Nothing.

00:14:38.320 --> 00:14:39.600
It's been four and a half years.

00:14:40.320 --> 00:14:45.560
We underestimated the difficulty
in building this, but we're still around.

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:49.920
So, very grateful to still have
opportunities to build a company.

00:14:51.760 --> 00:14:54.200
But it was a bit tougher than we expected.

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:57.640
Are you branding your phone
by keeping it there?

00:14:57.720 --> 00:15:01.480
Yeah, it's free exposure. [chuckles]

00:15:01.560 --> 00:15:03.520
It has a very distinctive back, right?

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:05.760
Yeah, so that's our entire thing.

00:15:05.840 --> 00:15:07.200
We...

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:10.040
It's a very mature industry,

00:15:10.120 --> 00:15:14.400
and it's very hard to compete
because everybody is at very high scale.

00:15:14.480 --> 00:15:16.080
So they have a lot of advantages.

00:15:17.560 --> 00:15:19.560
We're not reinventing the category.

00:15:19.640 --> 00:15:21.920
It was invented a long time ago
by somebody else.

00:15:22.680 --> 00:15:27.080
So, for us, it's all about carving out
a small position in the market first.

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:29.840
We don't have to have everybody love us.

00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:34.400
It's okay if 90% of people don't care
about us or hate us

00:15:34.480 --> 00:15:39.040
as long as we get a niche group
of consumers who really love us.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.920
That works in our industry
because it's so big.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.000
Maybe it doesn't work
for smaller categories.

00:15:45.600 --> 00:15:49.040
So, for us, we chose to differentiate
through design

00:15:49.120 --> 00:15:51.920
because it was the fastest way
to differentiate.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:55.880
If we picked technology,
it would take years to play out.

00:15:55.960 --> 00:15:58.000
It's a lot of investment, a lot of years.

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:02.280
We also didn't want to reinvent
the product category.

00:16:02.360 --> 00:16:06.480
Like, if we have crazy ideas
on a new gadget,

00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:08.840
we might spend years
on trying to build it.

00:16:08.920 --> 00:16:11.680
And then if we launch it,
you only have one chance.

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:13.800
If people don't like it, you're screwed.

00:16:13.880 --> 00:16:17.200
Yeah, so we start with hardware design,
then we move to software design.

00:16:18.040 --> 00:16:22.120
Now we're investing more and more
into the OS itself, into AI.

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:27.240
So I think, for us, it's about building
differentiation and modes over time.

00:16:27.320 --> 00:16:28.560
But in a gradual way.

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:32.280
Don't move too fast because then
you might, kind of, fall off the horse.

00:16:32.360 --> 00:16:36.560
So, for a company
headquartered in Sweden...

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:37.720
-UK.
-UK.

00:16:39.320 --> 00:16:41.160
The trade war will affect you how?

00:16:41.240 --> 00:16:42.400
Tariffs?

00:16:42.480 --> 00:16:45.120
So, now, the most direct way is...

00:16:46.760 --> 00:16:50.240
Trump had new tariffs
for manufacturing from China.

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:52.760
So we manufacture the earbuds in China.

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:57.800
And that's like a 20% hit on our...

00:16:57.880 --> 00:17:00.280
-[Amit] Import.
-...business plans for the US market.

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:04.280
So now we need to look
at alternative sources of manufacturing

00:17:04.360 --> 00:17:05.760
like India, like Vietnam,

00:17:05.840 --> 00:17:07.320
where it makes the most sense.

00:17:08.280 --> 00:17:13.000
It's the first time where, you know,
every night, 10pm, I go on CNN.com.

00:17:13.080 --> 00:17:15.360
See. He must have woken up.

00:17:15.440 --> 00:17:16.680
What is the new news?

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:18.200
And then go to sleep.

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:21.320
But it won't affect you as much
if you're getting stuff from China

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:23.200
and selling in India, right?

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:25.560
No, it's not about that getting from...

00:17:25.640 --> 00:17:28.520
See, because the supply chain right now
is there in China.

00:17:28.600 --> 00:17:31.080
And then all the manufacturing now
is coming to India.

00:17:32.480 --> 00:17:34.800
But it's not about China,
it's about India also.

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:39.200
Because, you know, reciprocal tariffs
and all those sort of things.

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:43.040
But I would assume it would hurt you most
if you're selling something in the US.

00:17:43.960 --> 00:17:45.520
Certainly, yes.

00:17:45.600 --> 00:17:48.120
But now we're talking about
the whole industry, you know, per se.

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:51.520
So, you know,
if you see the reciprocal tariff,

00:17:51.600 --> 00:17:52.760
even on mobile phones.

00:17:53.800 --> 00:17:58.680
It's, you know, it's 16.5%.

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:00.640
Right?

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:05.200
So if anything coming into India,
there is a duty of 16.5%.

00:18:05.280 --> 00:18:07.600
Going to US as of now is 0%.

00:18:08.200 --> 00:18:10.040
So reciprocal means...

00:18:10.120 --> 00:18:12.200
At some level, doesn't it sound fair?

00:18:12.760 --> 00:18:17.000
Like, I'm just...
I have no affinity to America.

00:18:17.080 --> 00:18:20.560
And I'm the biggest proponent
of India built for India,

00:18:20.640 --> 00:18:22.280
supporting Indian product.

00:18:23.120 --> 00:18:28.240
But, if tomorrow
I was selling to country X, Y, Z.

00:18:28.320 --> 00:18:32.320
And I was selling them something
and they were charging me 30% duty on it,

00:18:33.960 --> 00:18:36.600
if I was buying something from them,

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:40.120
I would assume the same duty should apply.

00:18:40.200 --> 00:18:41.880
Yeah, I think so.

00:18:41.960 --> 00:18:43.840
Like, inherently, it's logical, no?

00:18:43.920 --> 00:18:45.760
-Yeah, but I have a different view.
-Yeah.

00:18:45.840 --> 00:18:49.400
See, it's not binary.
It's not, you know-- It depends:

00:18:49.480 --> 00:18:53.280
How do you want to bring up your country?
What are your policies, for example?

00:18:53.360 --> 00:18:55.360
We've been discussing about China a lot.

00:18:56.320 --> 00:18:58.360
In China, way back, they decided

00:18:58.440 --> 00:19:00.400
that they are not going to allow
the foreign companies.

00:19:00.480 --> 00:19:02.320
Foreign companies can only come with JVs

00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:04.880
because they want to build
their champions.

00:19:06.560 --> 00:19:09.080
But then, how can they do that,

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:13.840
+but sell to other countries
at the scale that they are selling

00:19:13.920 --> 00:19:15.280
and creating these deficits?

00:19:15.360 --> 00:19:17.760
No, but they created that scale, right?

00:19:17.840 --> 00:19:23.240
So, see, if you see examples
how great countries are built.

00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:27.720
It's all about the companies
that, you know...

00:19:28.520 --> 00:19:31.480
If you have great companies,
the country will prosper.

00:19:31.560 --> 00:19:33.520
And the United States
is the biggest example.

00:19:35.440 --> 00:19:38.000
Same thing, you know,
China worked on that way back.

00:19:38.720 --> 00:19:43.720
And so, if Mercedes-Benz
have to, you know...

00:19:44.480 --> 00:19:48.000
they want to sell and they say,
"Do a joint venture with our company."

00:19:48.080 --> 00:19:51.320
Everyone, Hyundai, or...
all of them in the automobile.

00:19:52.040 --> 00:19:56.480
Softwares... Never allowed Google,
Microsoft, you know, all those players.

00:19:56.560 --> 00:19:59.200
They build their own companies,
and they...

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:01.000
We all know about that.

00:20:02.400 --> 00:20:04.840
So, if it was like what we are discussing

00:20:04.920 --> 00:20:07.720
that yes, sitting across the table,
okay, if you do this, I do this.

00:20:07.800 --> 00:20:10.560
Then all these things-- Then Google
would have been there probably...

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:12.120
Or Amazon would have been there.

00:20:12.200 --> 00:20:14.600
I don't think so whether
they will be having an Alibaba or not

00:20:14.680 --> 00:20:16.720
or whether there was this Baidu,

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:18.800
you know, all those players
would have been existing or not.

00:20:19.480 --> 00:20:26.000
But I'm making the presumption
that classical economic theory suggests

00:20:26.080 --> 00:20:29.720
that free markets are the fastest way

00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:33.240
to improve quality and get competitive.

00:20:33.320 --> 00:20:34.880
Like, I do see your point.

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:37.200
I remember reading somewhere in history

00:20:38.200 --> 00:20:41.120
that back in the day
when UK was not doing well,

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:43.240
they shut off from the world,

00:20:43.320 --> 00:20:47.240
isolated their domestic industry
pre-industrial revolution

00:20:47.320 --> 00:20:50.040
and they didn't allow foreign products
for a while

00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:55.520
to help their internal industry to grow
to a point where it can be competitive.

00:20:55.600 --> 00:20:56.920
So maybe there's a point to that.

00:20:57.880 --> 00:21:00.400
But when I look at it very simplistically,

00:21:00.480 --> 00:21:05.120
if Nikhil is selling something
and Rahul is selling something,

00:21:05.800 --> 00:21:08.520
if each time Rahul is selling something,

00:21:08.600 --> 00:21:10.600
there is a certain additional tax

00:21:10.680 --> 00:21:14.400
outside of the cost of growth produced
in Rahul's margin,

00:21:14.480 --> 00:21:16.120
the same should apply to Nikhil as well.

00:21:16.200 --> 00:21:20.720
Certainly. So as I said, likewise,
it sounds very, it's simple, it's logical.

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:24.400
But, you know,
when you're building your countries,

00:21:24.480 --> 00:21:26.240
you know, the whole narrative
changes in that.

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:29.640
And that's how all these FTA treaties
are being worked out.

00:21:29.720 --> 00:21:30.760
-[Nikhil] Yeah.
-Yeah.

00:21:30.840 --> 00:21:33.600
They've supported the ecosystem also
in a big way,

00:21:33.680 --> 00:21:35.560
if you look at all Chinese companies.

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:38.760
I mean, all, like-- You're talking about
Internet companies,

00:21:38.840 --> 00:21:41.600
they never allowed US companies
to come in.

00:21:41.680 --> 00:21:43.800
In fact, there is no Uber also there.

00:21:43.880 --> 00:21:45.920
Amazon also had to sell out
their business there.

00:21:46.480 --> 00:21:48.640
I mean, somehow
they're protected for the Indian--

00:21:48.720 --> 00:21:50.960
their Chinese companies to grow, actually.

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:53.360
That's how, I mean,
that's how their whole strategy,

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:54.840
you know, has been worked out.

00:21:54.920 --> 00:21:57.080
So, today, we talk
about semiconductors here.

00:21:57.160 --> 00:21:59.160
They started working
on semiconductors 20 years back.

00:21:59.240 --> 00:22:01.440
-[Carl] Yeah.
-And now the results are coming.

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:05.480
They're like 3,200 companies
working on semiconductors.

00:22:05.560 --> 00:22:09.040
Most patents are being filed there. So...

00:22:09.840 --> 00:22:11.880
Carl, can I ask you another question?

00:22:11.960 --> 00:22:13.800
Mm-hmm.

00:22:13.880 --> 00:22:17.280
For a kid who moved from China to the US

00:22:17.360 --> 00:22:20.240
with two PhD parents,

00:22:20.320 --> 00:22:22.920
and a deep desire to make money
while young,

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:24.200
where does that come from?

00:22:24.920 --> 00:22:27.480
I'm sure there's some childhood trauma,

00:22:27.560 --> 00:22:29.920
but I've never explored that path
to understand more.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:31.720
What do you suspect it could be?

00:22:32.520 --> 00:22:35.520
I think just being... not fitting in,

00:22:35.600 --> 00:22:37.720
the feeling of not fitting in,
you know, like...

00:22:37.800 --> 00:22:40.120
But you're a young, good-looking guy.
Why not fitting in?

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:44.400
'Cause I grew up in white societies
as a minority.

00:22:44.480 --> 00:22:46.160
Racist? Back then?

00:22:46.240 --> 00:22:49.240
I think it's not, like, explicitly racist,

00:22:50.920 --> 00:22:54.280
but it's like, you're just
not the same, right?

00:22:54.360 --> 00:22:56.480
Like, I could tell.

00:22:56.560 --> 00:22:58.600
I think there's something to do with that.

00:22:58.680 --> 00:23:00.880
US more so or Sweden?

00:23:01.720 --> 00:23:04.360
-I think both.
-Is that all?

00:23:05.520 --> 00:23:06.520
Childhood?

00:23:06.600 --> 00:23:08.720
I think childhood trauma
is a big part of it,

00:23:08.800 --> 00:23:12.680
but I haven't gone to a therapist
to unpack all of that.

00:23:13.480 --> 00:23:17.440
There's also, I think, a fear of death.

00:23:17.520 --> 00:23:20.280
You know, I remember
when I was very young,

00:23:21.080 --> 00:23:25.400
I was very angry at my parents
for giving birth to me.

00:23:25.480 --> 00:23:27.880
Because now I have to die,
and that's terrible.

00:23:27.960 --> 00:23:29.240
"Why did you do this?"

00:23:29.320 --> 00:23:31.800
-This is at what age?
-Eight, I think.

00:23:31.880 --> 00:23:33.960
So there's like this fear.

00:23:34.040 --> 00:23:39.080
And my best answer is, like,
this is going to be a journey.

00:23:39.160 --> 00:23:40.160
Life is a journey.

00:23:40.920 --> 00:23:43.600
I got the conclusion
from the movie Life of Pi.

00:23:43.680 --> 00:23:44.880
[Rahul] Mm-hmm.

00:23:44.960 --> 00:23:47.800
The kid is on a boat,
meets a lot of animals,

00:23:47.880 --> 00:23:50.080
but actually it didn't happen.

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:53.920
Just made it up
to make the journey more pleasant.

00:23:55.560 --> 00:23:59.000
So it's all about the journey,
and I think by doing something ambitious,

00:23:59.080 --> 00:24:01.280
doing something different,
the journey will be a lot more fun.

00:24:02.080 --> 00:24:04.360
So that's also a driver, I think.

00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:06.240
Do you feel like nothing has meaning?

00:24:06.320 --> 00:24:08.360
Are you nihilistic,
stoic in your thinking?

00:24:09.200 --> 00:24:11.120
I think the journey has meaning,

00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:16.040
but I don't think
there's much beyond death.

00:24:16.120 --> 00:24:17.200
Well, thank you.

00:24:18.240 --> 00:24:20.160
Rahul, would you like to go next?

00:24:22.080 --> 00:24:23.440
Tell us about your life.

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:26.160
Start from the beginning, from Delhi.

00:24:26.240 --> 00:24:29.280
-You know...
-I know, but they don't know.

00:24:32.520 --> 00:24:35.080
So, yeah, I grew up in Delhi.

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:39.120
Born in a middle class family,

00:24:39.200 --> 00:24:41.040
father was a school teacher,

00:24:41.880 --> 00:24:43.200
mother was a housewife.

00:24:44.360 --> 00:24:46.800
Youngest kid in the family.

00:24:48.600 --> 00:24:53.280
Growing up, just wanted to do something.

00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:54.680
Nobody was doing business in my family.

00:24:54.760 --> 00:24:56.320
Because, you know, all...

00:24:56.400 --> 00:24:58.600
But I don't know how I picked up that,

00:24:58.680 --> 00:25:01.400
but that I will always do something
of my own.

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:04.400
This was probably when I was...

00:25:05.920 --> 00:25:10.160
maybe, if I remember,
around 10 years or 12 years,

00:25:10.240 --> 00:25:12.200
I just wanted to do something of my own.

00:25:13.080 --> 00:25:15.640
And I was pretty clear
that I will not work for anybody else.

00:25:16.720 --> 00:25:18.560
Despite knowing that there is no capital.

00:25:18.640 --> 00:25:20.040
Why?

00:25:20.120 --> 00:25:23.520
No... A school teacher,
how much capital will you have?

00:25:23.600 --> 00:25:25.720
No, why will you not work for anyone else?

00:25:27.200 --> 00:25:32.720
Because I just thought that
I want to do something different in life,

00:25:32.800 --> 00:25:35.920
in terms of something meaningful.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:37.200
I am not saying impact,

00:25:37.280 --> 00:25:39.440
because, at that time,
it was not about impact,

00:25:39.520 --> 00:25:40.960
it was about survival.

00:25:42.720 --> 00:25:46.520
You said this to me personally
at different points.

00:25:46.600 --> 00:25:48.840
Even when I sat with you

00:25:48.920 --> 00:25:52.680
and had the fund raise,
dilution conversation.

00:25:53.320 --> 00:25:57.400
You always said, we won't raise X,

00:25:58.680 --> 00:26:01.240
because control will go away.

00:26:01.320 --> 00:26:04.320
Or we will have somebody else
we are answerable to.

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:08.000
Why did you never want to work
for anyone else?

00:26:08.080 --> 00:26:10.920
And why do you never
want to give up control

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:12.880
or your position in that ecosystem?

00:26:12.960 --> 00:26:16.120
Yeah, so I think we will break up
in these two parts.

00:26:17.080 --> 00:26:18.600
First, not work for anyone,

00:26:18.680 --> 00:26:22.520
because I wanted, as I said,
to do something different,

00:26:22.600 --> 00:26:26.360
something big, something meaningful.

00:26:27.120 --> 00:26:28.280
And I...

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:31.160
-Jai, get me some coffee, please.
-Yes, sir.

00:26:31.240 --> 00:26:33.560
I remember this conversation
with my friends at that time,

00:26:33.640 --> 00:26:38.440
and we used to go and play in parks,
that I will do something of my own.

00:26:41.480 --> 00:26:43.360
And they would also ask the same question.

00:26:43.440 --> 00:26:48.640
But I think there was a deep desire
in terms of wanted to...

00:26:50.920 --> 00:26:54.200
wanted to be known for something.

00:26:54.280 --> 00:26:55.440
Why?

00:26:57.360 --> 00:26:58.960
This is the problem with him.

00:27:01.600 --> 00:27:02.760
No, but...

00:27:02.840 --> 00:27:04.120
So why?

00:27:04.200 --> 00:27:06.480
Maybe because when I was growing up,

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:11.320
I saw, you know...

00:27:13.320 --> 00:27:20.080
how people were and how things were
going on in terms of whatever access.

00:27:20.160 --> 00:27:23.440
So because we were having
very limited access to things.

00:27:23.520 --> 00:27:24.920
So you are 50 now.

00:27:25.680 --> 00:27:29.560
Your formative years were '90s?

00:27:30.680 --> 00:27:33.040
-When India was opening up?
-Yeah.

00:27:33.120 --> 00:27:37.080
Yeah. You know, end of, let's say...
you can say...

00:27:37.160 --> 00:27:40.040
When I started working, it was 2000, yeah.

00:27:40.120 --> 00:27:43.880
Right. What did you see then
which made you want to do these things?

00:27:43.960 --> 00:27:49.200
So first, you know, I just told my dad...
he said, "What do you want to do?"

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:50.800
I said, "I just want to do
something of my own."

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:52.480
-He said, "What?"
-I said, "I have no idea.

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:55.480
But buy me a computer."

00:27:55.560 --> 00:28:00.640
Because all my friends, whether they were
doing civil or mechanical or electronics,

00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:01.760
everybody was going in software.

00:28:01.840 --> 00:28:03.520
So I said I want to do
something in software.

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:04.760
[Nikhil] Mm-hmm.

00:28:05.320 --> 00:28:07.680
And bought that computer.

00:28:10.160 --> 00:28:12.080
And I clearly remember
when I bought that computer,

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:13.840
I had no idea about computers
at that time.

00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:16.120
Windows came,
and Windows was there at that time.

00:28:17.040 --> 00:28:19.120
So I went to the guy
who was selling the computer.

00:28:19.800 --> 00:28:21.520
He said, "What computer do you want?"

00:28:21.600 --> 00:28:25.680
I said, "It should have lot of icons
on the screen."

00:28:26.720 --> 00:28:28.600
It used to have shortcuts, actually.

00:28:28.680 --> 00:28:29.680
I never knew about that.

00:28:29.760 --> 00:28:33.240
I said, "It should have lot of icons
on the screen."

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:35.080
And that's how...

00:28:35.920 --> 00:28:37.120
So he laughed at me.

00:28:38.560 --> 00:28:39.640
"He has no idea."

00:28:40.800 --> 00:28:42.040
He gave me.

00:28:42.120 --> 00:28:43.560
And then I bought a book.

00:28:47.320 --> 00:28:49.400
"Learn VB in 21 days."

00:28:49.480 --> 00:28:51.600
-Visual Basic.
-Visual Basic, yeah.

00:28:52.280 --> 00:28:54.560
I wrote a program in three days.

00:28:54.640 --> 00:28:57.400
Hello world, this, that.
I thought, "Okay, I know programming now."

00:28:57.960 --> 00:29:00.640
My friend came, he saw the book.
He said, "You've done this?"

00:29:00.720 --> 00:29:02.400
I said, "Yeah, I made a program."
He said, "Can I take this?"

00:29:02.480 --> 00:29:03.480
I said, "Yeah, take it."

00:29:04.080 --> 00:29:05.480
So he took that book away.

00:29:05.560 --> 00:29:08.760
That guy later became my partner.
So the story...

00:29:08.840 --> 00:29:10.600
And he is a core techie guy.

00:29:10.680 --> 00:29:11.680
Coding only.

00:29:12.520 --> 00:29:14.320
So I tell him
you become a coder because of me.

00:29:15.640 --> 00:29:18.840
So, by virtue of buying that computer,
that decision,

00:29:18.920 --> 00:29:20.600
we started working on...

00:29:20.680 --> 00:29:22.720
So I started looking for opportunities
in software.

00:29:22.800 --> 00:29:24.440
That, what can I do in software.

00:29:25.200 --> 00:29:28.080
2000 was like the software bust time, no?

00:29:28.160 --> 00:29:29.320
Yeah, the dot-com.

00:29:29.400 --> 00:29:31.520
So, this is like '99 or so.

00:29:31.600 --> 00:29:33.480
You started Micromax in 2000.

00:29:33.560 --> 00:29:36.280
No, actually 1998.

00:29:36.360 --> 00:29:38.400
1998, with the three friends.

00:29:39.200 --> 00:29:41.040
-Four friends.
-[Nikhil] Four friends.

00:29:41.120 --> 00:29:43.520
Started with three, fourth came
from US and then joined here.

00:29:44.720 --> 00:29:46.280
Then started, you know,
working on software,

00:29:46.360 --> 00:29:48.320
just worked on a lot of SAP.

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:50.840
That went down.

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:53.400
Then started working on e-commerce,

00:29:53.480 --> 00:29:56.720
that Y2K problems and all that.
So, at that time, I was in US.

00:29:57.440 --> 00:30:00.560
So I was the BD guy,
doing marketing and sales,

00:30:00.640 --> 00:30:03.280
and rest of the other guys were
doing the coding and everything.

00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:06.200
So, at that time,
we wrote a lot of B2B engines

00:30:06.280 --> 00:30:10.280
for e-commerce and doing all that.

00:30:13.200 --> 00:30:15.960
So, you know, that was the time
when Sun Microsystems was there,

00:30:16.040 --> 00:30:18.080
and it was like we had the dot in dot-com.

00:30:20.400 --> 00:30:23.760
And then that market went down,
and then we realised

00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:25.200
that it is a very fast-moving market,

00:30:25.280 --> 00:30:27.280
and you have to, you know,
constantly change yourself

00:30:27.360 --> 00:30:29.880
very quickly to be relevant.

00:30:29.960 --> 00:30:31.440
We moved on to embedded technology,

00:30:31.520 --> 00:30:34.280
started working
with University of Irvine, California.

00:30:34.360 --> 00:30:36.000
They had an R&amp;D centre on embedded.

00:30:36.800 --> 00:30:38.240
We started working together.

00:30:39.240 --> 00:30:41.600
And, at that time, Nokia, in India,

00:30:41.680 --> 00:30:45.320
was looking
for a machine-to-machine partner, M2M.

00:30:46.360 --> 00:30:49.360
HCL was their partner
for their mobile phones,

00:30:50.040 --> 00:30:52.160
and they were looking for someone
for a machine-to-machine.

00:30:52.240 --> 00:30:54.320
And we got introduced.

00:30:55.360 --> 00:30:57.280
And they said,
"Would you like to do something?"

00:30:57.360 --> 00:31:01.240
You know, we used to write device drivers,

00:31:01.320 --> 00:31:07.320
doing, you know, work on
a lot of different architectures.

00:31:07.400 --> 00:31:09.280
ARM, PowerPC and all that.

00:31:09.360 --> 00:31:11.200
Said okay, started doing that.

00:31:13.480 --> 00:31:15.840
And then, one fine day,

00:31:18.040 --> 00:31:21.560
I was just sitting with one of the guys
from Nokia, Finland.

00:31:21.640 --> 00:31:24.360
And he showed me a product.

00:31:24.440 --> 00:31:25.440
I said, "What is this?"

00:31:25.520 --> 00:31:28.720
He said, "This is one of the products
wherein if you put a SIM card in this,

00:31:28.800 --> 00:31:33.000
you can connect a telephone
along with this,

00:31:33.080 --> 00:31:35.160
and it will replace the landline."

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:38.720
So I said, "Good.
So why did you make this product?"

00:31:38.800 --> 00:31:39.920
He said, "In Finland, you know,

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:42.080
because there are a lot of snow
and everything,

00:31:42.160 --> 00:31:45.720
you can't lay the copper wire...
the telephone.

00:31:45.800 --> 00:31:48.120
So you can put a SIM card in this
and connect a phone

00:31:48.200 --> 00:31:49.240
and then you have a landline,

00:31:49.320 --> 00:31:51.760
because this phone is going to be fixed,
nobody's going to take it."

00:31:53.320 --> 00:31:55.160
He said, "Can you do something with this?"

00:31:57.360 --> 00:31:59.320
I said, "India, how much would this...

00:31:59.400 --> 00:32:01.280
we don't have market
for something like this."

00:32:04.200 --> 00:32:07.480
So I took that product from him.
I said, "Okay, let me just play."

00:32:10.320 --> 00:32:13.440
And we found an opportunity and I went
back to him the next day and said,

00:32:14.440 --> 00:32:17.760
we would like to power
the payphone machines.

00:32:17.840 --> 00:32:19.280
Yes.

00:32:19.360 --> 00:32:23.720
So we went to Airtel and all those guys...

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:27.640
and all the GSM players,

00:32:27.720 --> 00:32:30.840
said, we can power payphones
with one SIM card.

00:32:31.800 --> 00:32:34.200
At that time, payphone in India
was only MTNL and BSNL,

00:32:34.280 --> 00:32:37.000
government companies laying down the wire.

00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:38.880
You mean the STD centre?

00:32:38.960 --> 00:32:41.400
STD centre, STD meets.

00:32:42.680 --> 00:32:44.480
So they said, "Okay, how can you do that?"

00:32:44.560 --> 00:32:46.120
We said, "This is, you know,
with that phone,"

00:32:46.200 --> 00:32:48.040
because we were writing device drivers
and everything,

00:32:48.120 --> 00:32:51.360
we took that machine,
change the code and everything,

00:32:51.960 --> 00:32:54.640
put our software, attach the landline,

00:32:54.720 --> 00:32:56.880
and say, you put a SIM card,
and you can work.

00:32:58.800 --> 00:32:59.880
They said, good.

00:33:00.600 --> 00:33:03.320
And then it was also a solution,
good solution for corporates,

00:33:03.400 --> 00:33:06.000
because corporates, if they want to have
a connection straight away,

00:33:06.080 --> 00:33:10.000
you can just, you know, integrate it
with the EPABX systems and all.

00:33:10.080 --> 00:33:11.920
So it worked for them.

00:33:13.080 --> 00:33:16.960
And from a small Delhi-based company,

00:33:17.040 --> 00:33:20.760
we started growing to all the states
and started supporting all the carriers.

00:33:20.840 --> 00:33:25.560
Airtel, that time, it was Hutch
and Idea and all.

00:33:25.640 --> 00:33:27.000
We started supplying to them.

00:33:27.680 --> 00:33:30.080
The business was started doing
reasonably okay.

00:33:30.160 --> 00:33:34.520
From three, four crore rupees annually,

00:33:34.600 --> 00:33:36.560
we started doing around 100 crore rupees.

00:33:37.760 --> 00:33:41.520
-And, you know, very quickly we scaled up.
-What year was this?

00:33:42.480 --> 00:33:44.080
This, I think 2003.

00:33:44.800 --> 00:33:46.880
Hundred crore then
is like thousand crore now.

00:33:47.880 --> 00:33:49.000
More.

00:33:50.040 --> 00:33:51.400
A lot more.

00:33:51.480 --> 00:33:52.480
So we were happy.

00:33:52.560 --> 00:33:55.000
We thought that okay, we have arrived,
something is happening.

00:33:55.080 --> 00:33:56.640
So that business was doing well.

00:33:56.720 --> 00:33:59.000
So one day I got a call
from this Finnish guy.

00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:01.560
I remember his name, Henry.

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:05.960
So Henry said, "Rahul, can we meet?"
I said, "Absolutely."

00:34:06.040 --> 00:34:07.040
Said, "Why?"

00:34:07.120 --> 00:34:08.920
He said, "I have good news
and bad news for you."

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:12.560
I said, "Tell me what?"
He said, "No, come over to my home."

00:34:13.720 --> 00:34:15.120
Went to his home.

00:34:16.240 --> 00:34:19.520
He said, "What do you like to listen?"
I said, "Tell me the bad news first."

00:34:19.600 --> 00:34:21.480
He said, "Bad news is that

00:34:21.560 --> 00:34:24.800
Nokia, we have sold
the whole machine-to-machine business."

00:34:24.880 --> 00:34:26.560
What year was this?

00:34:26.640 --> 00:34:27.760
It's 2003.

00:34:28.400 --> 00:34:29.760
2003, 2004.

00:34:29.840 --> 00:34:33.720
Back then they were killing it, right?
Nokia was the market leader?

00:34:33.800 --> 00:34:35.400
Number 1 to number 10 was Nokia.

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:37.520
Then started 11, 12, 13. Yeah.

00:34:38.280 --> 00:34:40.800
So I said, "What is the good news?"

00:34:40.880 --> 00:34:42.000
He said, "Good news is that

00:34:42.080 --> 00:34:44.920
as Nokia, now we are coming
into car accessories business.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:47.240
We want you to distribute
our car accessories."

00:34:50.160 --> 00:34:52.120
So those car accessories, you know,
they had speakers.

00:34:52.200 --> 00:34:57.000
You could put in those,
that lighter socket.

00:34:57.080 --> 00:34:58.280
-[Nikhil] Mm-hmm.
-Oh.

00:34:58.360 --> 00:35:02.040
And connect the wire with your Nokia phone
and then while you are driving,

00:35:02.120 --> 00:35:03.520
the speaker, you know, you can talk.

00:35:04.960 --> 00:35:06.160
A pretty interesting solution.

00:35:06.240 --> 00:35:09.120
They had a speaker
you can put in your seat

00:35:09.200 --> 00:35:13.880
and the mic and, you know,
the speakers will come like this.

00:35:13.960 --> 00:35:15.400
So all those sort of...

00:35:16.240 --> 00:35:19.480
So I said, "No, we are not interested
in the accessories business."

00:35:20.200 --> 00:35:23.360
So the technology was there with us
completely because we developed...

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:27.680
So we made our own box,
our fixed wireless terminal.

00:35:27.760 --> 00:35:31.200
Stamped Micromax on top of it
and went back to Airtel.

00:35:31.280 --> 00:35:33.960
We said, "Nokia is no more,
this is Micromax.

00:35:34.640 --> 00:35:35.720
Would you like to use it?"

00:35:36.840 --> 00:35:37.920
Same terminal.

00:35:38.960 --> 00:35:44.120
All of those guys, Airtel and Vodafone,
they used to know me from Nokia.

00:35:44.200 --> 00:35:47.560
In their phone also, my phone number
was saved as "Rahul Nokia".

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:51.600
So they said, "Okay."

00:35:54.240 --> 00:35:58.000
Up north there is a shrine, Vaishno Devi,
they said, "You install it there."

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:03.520
Because it works 24 hours, the pay phone,
you know, it works 24 hours.

00:36:03.600 --> 00:36:05.840
-In "Vaishnav" Devi?
-Vaishno Devi.

00:36:05.920 --> 00:36:09.880
Yeah? I have been there,
that walk where you are climbing the hill

00:36:09.960 --> 00:36:11.760
and there are STD booths
on that path, right?

00:36:11.840 --> 00:36:13.160
Yes, yes.

00:36:14.400 --> 00:36:17.000
So we installed our machines there.

00:36:17.080 --> 00:36:18.640
First machines in Vaishno Devi?

00:36:18.720 --> 00:36:20.520
-Yes.
-How come?

00:36:20.600 --> 00:36:22.600
Because that's what Airtel said,
that, you know, if you install--

00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:26.280
Because the traffic is so high,
that if it works there,

00:36:26.360 --> 00:36:28.680
if it can take the load,
then it will work anywhere.

00:36:29.480 --> 00:36:31.400
We said, "Okay."
We installed it there, 20 days.

00:36:32.160 --> 00:36:33.160
The revenue from...

00:36:33.240 --> 00:36:36.320
Because see, for the operators,
it was a killer product

00:36:36.400 --> 00:36:38.560
because their ARPU from one SIM card,

00:36:38.640 --> 00:36:41.360
multiple people are using one SIM card,
the ARPU is massive.

00:36:41.960 --> 00:36:43.960
Thousands of rupees from one SIM card.

00:36:44.040 --> 00:36:45.840
With an individual, it's...

00:36:45.920 --> 00:36:47.520
Versus what did they have before that?

00:36:47.600 --> 00:36:49.160
Nothing.

00:36:49.240 --> 00:36:50.760
There were STD booths before that, right?

00:36:50.840 --> 00:36:52.960
MTNL... powered by MTNL and BSNL.

00:36:53.040 --> 00:36:54.080
Hmm.

00:36:54.160 --> 00:36:55.360
To run an...

00:36:55.440 --> 00:36:58.120
You know, to install an STD booth
where there was no MTNL, BSNL line,

00:36:58.200 --> 00:36:59.200
where there was only...

00:36:59.280 --> 00:37:01.360
if there was a GSM signal coming in,
you can power that.

00:37:03.720 --> 00:37:06.560
And so then they gave us a contract.

00:37:06.640 --> 00:37:08.560
This is pre
"people having cell phones", right?

00:37:08.640 --> 00:37:09.760
Significantly pre.

00:37:09.840 --> 00:37:11.520
No, cell phones were there at that time.

00:37:11.600 --> 00:37:14.440
In 2005-06, they were pretty much there.

00:37:14.520 --> 00:37:15.640
Yeah, the cell phones were there.

00:37:15.720 --> 00:37:17.800
No smartphones,
all the feature phones were there.

00:37:17.880 --> 00:37:20.000
So, you are saying the difference was
it got cheaper?

00:37:20.080 --> 00:37:22.320
Yeah, it was difficult to get.

00:37:22.400 --> 00:37:26.560
So, you have to apply to MTNL,
get a license and then, you know, install.

00:37:26.640 --> 00:37:28.440
-Painful that time.
-[Rahul] Right.

00:37:28.520 --> 00:37:29.600
The government.

00:37:29.680 --> 00:37:32.560
The government thing and then,
you know, they will come,

00:37:32.640 --> 00:37:34.440
and if there was no line...

00:37:34.520 --> 00:37:37.120
Imagine if there is no...
If it is a village.

00:37:37.800 --> 00:37:40.840
See, they have to lay down the whole line.
It was a costly affair and time-taking.

00:37:41.520 --> 00:37:43.240
And for us, if there is a signal coming,

00:37:43.320 --> 00:37:45.680
we will say, about five minutes,
we will install it.

00:37:45.853 --> 00:37:50.613
So, that business started doing quite well
and then we became a de facto number one

00:37:50.693 --> 00:37:53.613
on GSM fixed wireless terminal phones
in India.

00:37:53.693 --> 00:37:59.093
And started operating offices pan-India,
became a pan-India player,

00:37:59.173 --> 00:38:01.893
service network and everything.
So, we learnt a lot there.

00:38:02.533 --> 00:38:05.573
Applying, you know, sale tax numbers
and everything,

00:38:05.653 --> 00:38:08.573
you know, like the whole...
how the business works.

00:38:08.653 --> 00:38:10.333
This is till 2006.

00:38:10.933 --> 00:38:13.973
2000, yeah. 2006-07.

00:38:14.053 --> 00:38:15.493
Mm.

00:38:15.573 --> 00:38:17.573
One fine day, I got a call
from a senior guy from Airtel.

00:38:17.653 --> 00:38:19.053
He said, "Oh, there is a problem
in a machine.

00:38:19.133 --> 00:38:20.453
Can you go and check it?"

00:38:20.533 --> 00:38:22.373
That, by that time, you know,
our business grew

00:38:22.453 --> 00:38:24.933
to like 400 crores per annum.

00:38:25.013 --> 00:38:28.773
So, we were doing, like...

00:38:28.853 --> 00:38:31.573
Did you have liquidity?
Did you take out money from the business?

00:38:31.653 --> 00:38:33.293
No, we were just keeping the money.

00:38:33.373 --> 00:38:35.973
But I still... I just remember
that time BMW came to India.

00:38:36.053 --> 00:38:39.813
I bought a BMW 3 Series
and thought, "Yes, this is it."

00:38:39.893 --> 00:38:40.933
In 2006.

00:38:41.013 --> 00:38:43.813
So, that time, then my...
That was the first time

00:38:43.893 --> 00:38:46.213
when my parents realised
that our son is doing something.

00:38:46.293 --> 00:38:49.093
Because otherwise, they used to ask me,
"Son, what are you doing?"

00:38:49.173 --> 00:38:51.453
I said, "Fixed wireless terminals
and all that..."

00:38:52.053 --> 00:38:54.813
Yeah, so coming back to the story,
so that guy called me.

00:38:54.893 --> 00:38:58.093
So, I said, he said,
"It's in Bengal somewhere,

00:38:58.173 --> 00:38:59.853
why don't you go and check?"

00:38:59.933 --> 00:39:01.413
I said, "I'll send some engineer."

00:39:01.493 --> 00:39:02.853
He said,
"No, it's a senior-level escalation,

00:39:02.933 --> 00:39:05.653
can you go yourself?" I said, "Okay."

00:39:05.733 --> 00:39:08.173
Took a plane, landed in Kolkata,
took a cab,

00:39:08.253 --> 00:39:11.573
five hours drive near Bangladesh border.

00:39:11.653 --> 00:39:16.173
Saw, this all, Krishnanagar,
Nadia and all...

00:39:16.973 --> 00:39:20.013
Just saw the problem, fixed it
and then in the evening coming back...

00:39:20.613 --> 00:39:23.013
to catch a flight
in late night in Kolkata.

00:39:23.093 --> 00:39:26.493
In mid, I saw, it's a village
where there was no electricity.

00:39:26.573 --> 00:39:30.373
But there was an Airtel ISD PCO booth.

00:39:31.293 --> 00:39:34.533
So, I asked my cab driver, I said,
"Bhaiya, can you stop the car?"

00:39:35.453 --> 00:39:37.093
I went inside the booth.

00:39:38.213 --> 00:39:39.773
And, because I knew
that if it is an Airtel,

00:39:39.853 --> 00:39:41.373
must be using our equipment.

00:39:41.453 --> 00:39:44.933
So, I said, "There is no electricity
in the village,

00:39:45.013 --> 00:39:47.013
how are you running this booth?"

00:39:48.413 --> 00:39:50.293
He showed me a big truck battery there.

00:39:50.373 --> 00:39:53.253
He said, "Sir, you draw power from here."

00:39:54.253 --> 00:39:55.413
I said, "Fine."

00:39:56.733 --> 00:40:00.533
We were not making phones those days,
I was having a Nokia phone.

00:40:00.613 --> 00:40:01.813
There was no signal in my phone.

00:40:01.893 --> 00:40:04.653
I said, "There is no signal in my phone,
how are you drawing the signals?"

00:40:05.213 --> 00:40:09.893
He showed me a big 20 dB gain antenna,
mounted on a pole on his terrace.

00:40:10.893 --> 00:40:12.173
Typical Indian jugaad.

00:40:13.373 --> 00:40:15.053
He said,
"Sir, the signal comes from here."

00:40:16.453 --> 00:40:18.053
I got more intrigued. I said, "Fine,

00:40:18.133 --> 00:40:19.933
there is no electricity,
how do you charge the battery?"

00:40:21.013 --> 00:40:23.973
He said, "Eleven kilometres away
there is a village,

00:40:24.053 --> 00:40:25.373
there is electricity.

00:40:26.453 --> 00:40:28.893
In the night, when I shut down
my shutter, I go there,

00:40:28.973 --> 00:40:30.773
charge in the night
and then come back in the morning."

00:40:31.613 --> 00:40:32.973
I said, "How much money do you make?"

00:40:33.613 --> 00:40:35.493
He said, "Around, let's say,
4,000 rupees a month."

00:40:36.453 --> 00:40:38.333
Now, 4,000 rupees a month in a village,

00:40:38.413 --> 00:40:41.973
there is no electricity,
no entertainment, no TV, is big.

00:40:42.053 --> 00:40:45.653
Then I was travelling
in the interiors of Bihar,

00:40:45.733 --> 00:40:48.013
and I saw people charging,

00:40:48.093 --> 00:40:52.613
you know, asking 25 rupees or 40 rupees
to charge your phone.

00:40:52.693 --> 00:40:55.093
Because at those days there were
different pins for different phones.

00:40:55.173 --> 00:40:56.853
I remember, yeah.

00:40:56.933 --> 00:41:00.013
Different for Motorola
and different for Nokia,

00:41:00.093 --> 00:41:01.733
those round pins and all...

00:41:01.813 --> 00:41:03.133
before everything standardised.

00:41:03.853 --> 00:41:05.253
I said, "Why is this?"

00:41:05.333 --> 00:41:08.333
He said, "Because there is no electricity
at home, people come, pay and charge."

00:41:08.893 --> 00:41:10.053
It's very expensive, right?

00:41:10.933 --> 00:41:13.253
-For a charge.
-Yeah. At that time it is very much.

00:41:13.893 --> 00:41:16.613
But see, those days
mobile phones were not common like this

00:41:16.693 --> 00:41:19.973
because the call was not free.

00:41:20.053 --> 00:41:21.973
Today, probably you are paying for data.

00:41:22.053 --> 00:41:24.133
You know, that time the call
was expensive.

00:41:24.973 --> 00:41:30.053
I went back, sat with our guys,
worked a lot on the GSM technology.

00:41:30.133 --> 00:41:31.773
I said, "Guys,
why don't you make a mobile phone?"

00:41:31.853 --> 00:41:33.013
What year was this?

00:41:33.093 --> 00:41:34.533
This is 2007.

00:41:36.253 --> 00:41:39.853
So, the first reaction from everyone
internally was, "Are you crazy?

00:41:39.933 --> 00:41:44.973
Who is going to fight these Nokias
and Samsungs and Motorolas in the world?"

00:41:47.453 --> 00:41:49.133
And they said,
"Why do you want to do that?

00:41:49.213 --> 00:41:52.933
I mean, we are doing so well.
You are driving a BMW 3 Series,

00:41:53.013 --> 00:41:55.493
so why do you want
to disturb the apple cart?

00:41:55.573 --> 00:41:56.613
Why?

00:41:57.973 --> 00:42:03.573
I said, "No, I think, you know, the food
is being cooked in different countries.

00:42:03.653 --> 00:42:05.373
We need a flavour in India.

00:42:05.453 --> 00:42:11.933
You know, it's somewhere in Finland
or in Korea, but we need Indian flavours."

00:42:13.213 --> 00:42:15.053
Anyway, so fought a lot internally.

00:42:16.093 --> 00:42:17.453
And then they said...

00:42:17.533 --> 00:42:18.893
Fought with your co-founders,
your partners.

00:42:18.973 --> 00:42:20.973
Yes, yes, yes.

00:42:21.053 --> 00:42:22.573
They said, "Okay, 10,000 phones you make.

00:42:23.533 --> 00:42:25.933
If it works, it's fine,
otherwise our business is doing well."

00:42:26.013 --> 00:42:28.013
So, this is like casino money
they gave me.

00:42:28.093 --> 00:42:30.293
They said, "You go and play, if it works,
it's okay. Otherwise you pay."

00:42:30.373 --> 00:42:32.053
How much money was there?

00:42:32.133 --> 00:42:36.413
10,000 phones,
even if a phone was 2,000 rupees,

00:42:36.493 --> 00:42:37.693
you multiply, it was what?

00:42:38.653 --> 00:42:40.933
-Twenty crores?
-Yeah, all that, yeah.

00:42:43.013 --> 00:42:44.173
I said, okay.

00:42:44.973 --> 00:42:46.413
So, we sat with the team and said,

00:42:46.493 --> 00:42:48.773
"Guys, let's make a phone
with long battery life,

00:42:48.853 --> 00:42:51.493
one month of battery backup,
because of all these experiences."

00:42:52.653 --> 00:42:53.853
And...

00:42:54.813 --> 00:42:57.373
And that's how
the first Micromax phone came.

00:42:58.013 --> 00:43:00.653
And the tagline for the phone
was "Mobile ka Baap."

00:43:00.733 --> 00:43:03.013
Because the standby time was 30 days.

00:43:04.093 --> 00:43:05.613
Since we worked a lot.

00:43:05.693 --> 00:43:10.013
Now, herein, my philosophy is that
whatever you are doing in life,

00:43:10.093 --> 00:43:11.293
nothing goes waste.

00:43:11.373 --> 00:43:15.333
Whatever we were, you know, I'm just,
you know, scrambling my whole story here.

00:43:15.413 --> 00:43:17.213
But in between,
we worked a lot on SIM card,

00:43:17.293 --> 00:43:19.173
with Schlumberger and all those guys
for one, two years.

00:43:19.253 --> 00:43:20.813
Nothing came out of it.

00:43:20.893 --> 00:43:22.693
Nothing came out of all those things.

00:43:22.773 --> 00:43:25.253
But all those things we implemented
when we were making phones.

00:43:26.573 --> 00:43:30.293
So, normal phones take
seven to eight milliamperes,

00:43:30.373 --> 00:43:32.613
you know, per second as power.

00:43:32.693 --> 00:43:34.333
We worked on embedded,

00:43:34.413 --> 00:43:36.453
we made it two to three milliamperes
per second.

00:43:36.533 --> 00:43:40.173
And that's how we created
the same form factor.

00:43:40.253 --> 00:43:44.493
At that time,
the battery was 700, 600 mAh.

00:43:44.573 --> 00:43:47.453
We put some 1,800 mAh,
2,000 mAh that time.

00:43:48.493 --> 00:43:49.693
Same form factor.

00:43:49.773 --> 00:43:53.013
Made a phone
and then went to the distributors.

00:43:53.093 --> 00:43:54.773
Now, the real problem started from there.

00:43:56.173 --> 00:43:59.053
Because all the distributors were like,
all big distributors.

00:43:59.133 --> 00:44:03.493
Like, even the Delhi distributor of Nokia
was bigger than us.

00:44:04.413 --> 00:44:07.253
We were doing pan-India business,
fixed wireless and all, but...

00:44:07.333 --> 00:44:09.293
Because Nokia was so successful.

00:44:09.373 --> 00:44:12.093
So, we said, "Now we make mobile phones,
why don't you distribute?"

00:44:13.493 --> 00:44:14.853
And globally, it was only, you know,

00:44:14.933 --> 00:44:17.493
all those four, five
international brand names.

00:44:18.373 --> 00:44:23.093
There was no local brand doing anything
in the world at that time.

00:44:23.173 --> 00:44:26.933
Even if it was there, they were not like
very, very successful brands.

00:44:27.013 --> 00:44:31.253
So, they just offered us a cup of coffee
and said, "Good friends, but sorry."

00:44:32.013 --> 00:44:35.253
We were not able to find a distributor
after making the phone.

00:44:35.333 --> 00:44:36.893
In 2000?

00:44:37.693 --> 00:44:40.573
'07, '08 now. This is '08.

00:44:42.173 --> 00:44:44.613
And so, we went back to...

00:44:44.693 --> 00:44:47.213
After a lot of...
there is no distributor, how do we...

00:44:48.013 --> 00:44:49.733
So, we went back to our fixed wireless.

00:44:49.813 --> 00:44:51.453
-Did you already make the inventory?
-Huh?

00:44:51.533 --> 00:44:54.453
-Did you already make the inventory?
-Yeah, already it was with us.

00:44:55.733 --> 00:44:59.813
And we went back to our distributors
of fixed wireless terminals,

00:44:59.893 --> 00:45:02.533
payphone guys, who were selling payphones.

00:45:03.293 --> 00:45:05.533
We said, "Now, we have this.
Would you like to sell this?"

00:45:06.173 --> 00:45:08.933
He said, "Sir, give it to us, keep it,
if it sells, we will see."

00:45:09.013 --> 00:45:10.733
Because they were not
the mobile phone guys.

00:45:12.333 --> 00:45:14.973
We gave the phones to them.

00:45:16.013 --> 00:45:17.853
Ten days, the phones were sold out.

00:45:19.653 --> 00:45:22.533
Why? Because of the differentiation.
There was nothing like that in the market.

00:45:22.613 --> 00:45:24.093
-Battery was the differentiation.
-Yes.

00:45:25.333 --> 00:45:27.413
Which you learnt from travelling
to remote places.

00:45:27.493 --> 00:45:29.093
Yes.

00:45:29.173 --> 00:45:32.893
And the form factor was nice,
it was not bulky,

00:45:32.973 --> 00:45:36.133
so we didn't try to change much
on the form factor and all.

00:45:38.533 --> 00:45:41.893
The repeat order started coming in.
That's the same--

00:45:41.973 --> 00:45:44.453
And then everything went crazy.
Things blew up, right?

00:45:44.533 --> 00:45:47.053
-Things blew up.
-I remember seeing Micromax everywhere.

00:45:47.133 --> 00:45:49.053
Yeah, then things became crazy.

00:45:49.133 --> 00:45:51.373
And you started marketing like mad
at this point, right?

00:45:52.013 --> 00:45:56.293
No, so then we sat and said,
"Okay, what is it that we want to do?

00:45:56.373 --> 00:45:57.373
And how do we want to do it?"

00:45:58.373 --> 00:46:01.493
Because there could be
a lot of distractions.

00:46:02.053 --> 00:46:05.133
So, and we were still learning
at that stage,

00:46:05.213 --> 00:46:07.413
it's not that we perfected,
we were still learning.

00:46:08.813 --> 00:46:12.533
So, one day I saw my cook
using three SIM cards.

00:46:12.613 --> 00:46:16.053
This is the time
when all the new operators got license,

00:46:16.133 --> 00:46:18.053
and everybody was selling
new schemes every day.

00:46:18.133 --> 00:46:20.413
Uninor and all the new guys came in.

00:46:21.293 --> 00:46:22.893
So, I said,
"Why are you using three SIM cards?"

00:46:22.973 --> 00:46:25.213
He said, "Sir, one for local calling."

00:46:25.293 --> 00:46:27.133
I said, "Fine. Second SIM card?"

00:46:27.213 --> 00:46:29.533
He said, "To call my native village."

00:46:29.613 --> 00:46:31.653
I said, "Third SIM card?"

00:46:31.733 --> 00:46:33.493
He said, "Incoming is free,
so I am not throwing it away."

00:46:35.973 --> 00:46:37.373
I went back to our guys and said,

00:46:37.453 --> 00:46:40.213
"Guys, why don't we make a phone
with a dual SIM card?"

00:46:41.213 --> 00:46:44.493
They said, "No, two phones
only rich people can afford."

00:46:44.573 --> 00:46:46.213
I said, "That's not the consumer truth.

00:46:46.293 --> 00:46:48.373
These are the guys
who are using two phones.

00:46:49.453 --> 00:46:51.773
So, can we make
in a single phone, you know,

00:46:51.853 --> 00:46:55.373
simultaneously talking on the GSM signal?"

00:46:55.453 --> 00:46:59.013
So, with one single baseband,
we created the dual SIM phone that time.

00:46:59.853 --> 00:47:04.453
And I still remember,
I showcased it at one distributor meet,

00:47:04.533 --> 00:47:06.853
and everybody stood
and clapped, and they said, "Sir..."

00:47:08.213 --> 00:47:10.013
That was the time when we realised

00:47:10.093 --> 00:47:14.573
that we have to find the gaps
in the market.

00:47:14.653 --> 00:47:16.573
It's very interesting.
You are finding your gaps

00:47:16.653 --> 00:47:19.973
from your driver, your maid,
from going to villages.

00:47:20.053 --> 00:47:21.293
Everyday life.

00:47:21.373 --> 00:47:23.293
It's like you are learning that,

00:47:23.373 --> 00:47:26.253
you are just observing
and then, you know, finding those gaps.

00:47:26.333 --> 00:47:28.333
Do you see any gaps today?

00:47:28.413 --> 00:47:29.413
Multiple.

00:47:29.493 --> 00:47:31.213
Name one, top of the list.

00:47:34.093 --> 00:47:35.653
I can go on and on,

00:47:35.733 --> 00:47:37.533
but these are all different,
different ideas.

00:47:38.773 --> 00:47:41.173
I went crazy, I will tell you, you know,
in that in terms of finding gaps.

00:47:41.253 --> 00:47:42.653
So, we said, okay, we want to make a...

00:47:42.733 --> 00:47:45.973
So, that's how we made first phone
for girls with Swarovski.

00:47:46.053 --> 00:47:48.093
At that time,
the phones for girls in India

00:47:48.173 --> 00:47:50.453
was only by Dolce &amp; Gabbana, by Motorola.

00:47:50.533 --> 00:47:53.173
Now, how many people can afford
a Dolce &amp; Gabbana in this country?

00:47:54.413 --> 00:47:57.693
So, we made a phone,
you know, with Swarovski.

00:47:57.773 --> 00:48:00.293
Now, again, these very interesting
consumer stories here.

00:48:00.373 --> 00:48:03.213
We launched that phone
because our team insisted,

00:48:03.293 --> 00:48:06.413
"No, this is Swarovski,
it has to be expensive."

00:48:06.493 --> 00:48:09.973
And after a lot of, you know...

00:48:10.053 --> 00:48:14.333
I said, "No, just make it in the reach of,

00:48:14.413 --> 00:48:15.653
let's say, common people."

00:48:15.733 --> 00:48:18.253
We priced at 5,000 rupees at that time.

00:48:18.333 --> 00:48:19.733
Is that the way in India?

00:48:19.813 --> 00:48:24.213
I remember watching an interview of yours
when I was researching for today.

00:48:25.293 --> 00:48:27.853
When you were talking
about the form factor on your phone,

00:48:27.933 --> 00:48:30.533
you said-- What was his name?

00:48:30.613 --> 00:48:32.413
-Jesper?
-[Carl] Yeah.

00:48:32.493 --> 00:48:34.933
He said that whenever
you look a product...

00:48:35.013 --> 00:48:39.253
at a product for two seconds
and look away and you have to draw it,

00:48:39.333 --> 00:48:42.453
you should have
that one distinctive design element.

00:48:43.293 --> 00:48:46.053
That's a very different school of thought

00:48:46.133 --> 00:48:49.133
from the more utilitarian school
of thought here, right?

00:48:49.973 --> 00:48:54.973
Is this what works for India
and that works for the affluent?

00:48:55.053 --> 00:48:57.333
No, see, this is a time
when there were only feature phones,

00:48:57.413 --> 00:48:58.813
-there were no smartphones.
-[Nikhil] Right.

00:48:58.893 --> 00:49:00.333
So, how do you differentiate
feature phones?

00:49:00.413 --> 00:49:01.453
Right.

00:49:01.533 --> 00:49:04.653
I think we're at a stage in the industry
where it's hyper-competitive.

00:49:04.733 --> 00:49:08.213
-Yes.
-Every user need has been fully explored.

00:49:08.293 --> 00:49:12.373
Now, it is all evolved, like in laptops,
it's already at the ceiling.

00:49:12.453 --> 00:49:15.413
-How will you... You can't reinvent.
-Right.

00:49:16.013 --> 00:49:17.893
This was a time
when everything was evolving.

00:49:17.973 --> 00:49:19.013
[Nikhil] Right.

00:49:19.093 --> 00:49:21.413
We're at a different maturity stage
of the industry, I think.

00:49:21.493 --> 00:49:23.213
-[Rahul] Yes, yes.
-Right. Right.

00:49:23.293 --> 00:49:26.733
The phone was also a dream
when you came in.

00:49:26.813 --> 00:49:27.933
Nobody had phones that time.

00:49:28.013 --> 00:49:31.253
2008, by then, a lot of people had phones.

00:49:31.893 --> 00:49:33.293
Yeah, but the penetration was not high

00:49:33.373 --> 00:49:36.693
because the GSM rates
and everything was quite expensive.

00:49:36.773 --> 00:49:39.333
How big did it get in terms of numbers?

00:49:39.413 --> 00:49:43.413
From selling 10,000 phones a month,

00:49:43.493 --> 00:49:45.533
we were selling three million phones
a month.

00:49:47.293 --> 00:49:49.933
How big was the overall market
at that time?

00:49:50.013 --> 00:49:52.293
Total market less than 100 million
in India.

00:49:52.893 --> 00:49:54.573
Put together, less than that.

00:49:54.653 --> 00:49:57.693
So, you were selling
3% of the total market a month.

00:49:58.853 --> 00:50:00.453
-No, no, no.
-[Amit] 20%?

00:50:00.533 --> 00:50:01.933
[Rahul] No, no, no.

00:50:02.013 --> 00:50:04.453
-[Carl] A third?
-No, no, no.

00:50:04.533 --> 00:50:06.853
When we were doing three million,

00:50:06.933 --> 00:50:11.573
at that time, our market share
was around 25%, plus, plus.

00:50:11.653 --> 00:50:12.933
That's crazy.

00:50:13.013 --> 00:50:14.933
You were sponsoring cricket,

00:50:15.013 --> 00:50:17.173
you were sponsoring everything
back then, right?

00:50:17.253 --> 00:50:20.493
Yes, so our big bet
was on cricket and music.

00:50:21.173 --> 00:50:22.613
Because that's what the youth was into.

00:50:22.693 --> 00:50:27.173
And you said, a blanket on whatever is...

00:50:27.253 --> 00:50:29.613
Yeah. And that worked also.

00:50:29.693 --> 00:50:32.413
-And this stayed for a while?
-Yeah.

00:50:32.493 --> 00:50:33.613
For a couple of years?

00:50:34.373 --> 00:50:36.373
-Yeah.
-This crazy growth trajectory?

00:50:36.453 --> 00:50:37.613
Yes.

00:50:37.693 --> 00:50:41.173
Interestingly, we come back
to our tariff questions,

00:50:41.253 --> 00:50:43.413
the tariff conversation
we were having earlier,

00:50:43.493 --> 00:50:46.773
because that kind of
was the problem, right?

00:50:46.853 --> 00:50:49.613
The Chinese competition
which came into India post.

00:50:49.693 --> 00:50:52.853
Yes, so that was a time...

00:50:52.933 --> 00:50:54.813
And again, I will answer a couple
of other questions

00:50:54.893 --> 00:50:57.613
which you were asking about
why you wanted to and all.

00:50:57.693 --> 00:50:59.653
So there were a lot of learnings also
in between.

00:50:59.733 --> 00:51:04.093
So for example, when Meizu
was raising the round with Alibaba,

00:51:04.173 --> 00:51:06.493
we were deep down
with Alibaba at that time.

00:51:06.573 --> 00:51:08.253
Yeah. Raising the round and...

00:51:08.333 --> 00:51:12.053
-So our paths have been intertwined.
-Yes, and a pretty big one.

00:51:12.133 --> 00:51:14.173
At that time, we were raising, what,

00:51:14.253 --> 00:51:16.253
around 800 million dollars
around at that time.

00:51:16.333 --> 00:51:17.413
This is in 2000...

00:51:17.493 --> 00:51:20.853
'14 and secondary, most of it.

00:51:20.933 --> 00:51:23.093
-Wow!
-[laughter]

00:51:24.173 --> 00:51:28.053
So it was because the business
was throwing so much of cash.

00:51:28.133 --> 00:51:30.293
-Right.
-Yeah, so we said we don't need money,

00:51:30.373 --> 00:51:32.973
but, you know, at that time,
everybody wanted to connect.

00:51:33.053 --> 00:51:35.933
-You know, I remember...
-You could buy a few more BMWs.

00:51:37.093 --> 00:51:38.173
Few more than few more.

00:51:38.253 --> 00:51:40.053
[laughter]

00:51:40.133 --> 00:51:43.773
So this was going well.
And then we realised that...

00:51:43.853 --> 00:51:45.053
So we didn't take that money.

00:51:45.133 --> 00:51:46.573
We said, "Okay, no,
we are doing quite well."

00:51:46.653 --> 00:51:48.493
We said, "We already have so much of..."

00:51:49.973 --> 00:51:51.573
Bad decision in hindsight?

00:51:51.653 --> 00:51:53.693
So we thought that, you know,

00:51:53.773 --> 00:51:58.813
if we have taken care of the Finnish
and the Koreans at that time--

00:51:58.893 --> 00:52:00.573
Later on, because that time we never knew,

00:52:00.653 --> 00:52:05.053
but in 2016-17, you know,
that was the time

00:52:05.133 --> 00:52:08.373
when the, you know, the Chinese brands
started coming in.

00:52:09.213 --> 00:52:11.533
So we thought, you know,
we have taken care of them.

00:52:11.613 --> 00:52:14.333
So we can, you know,
we'll take care of this also.

00:52:14.413 --> 00:52:17.213
It's okay. We'll go head on.

00:52:17.853 --> 00:52:22.013
But, you know, that was
a very, very different game.

00:52:22.093 --> 00:52:26.773
Because, you know, when the Chinese came,
they came up with so much of gunpowder.

00:52:26.853 --> 00:52:29.453
And you never know that
where the gunpowder is coming from.

00:52:29.533 --> 00:52:31.213
And whether there is an end to it or not.

00:52:32.653 --> 00:52:35.213
Do you think the government
subsidised them to come in that manner?

00:52:35.813 --> 00:52:37.413
-Their government?
-[Rahul] So... Yes.

00:52:37.493 --> 00:52:39.373
So there, as I said,
you never know, because, you know,

00:52:39.453 --> 00:52:41.973
there were so many schemes
which were running there.

00:52:42.053 --> 00:52:44.693
And not only the central level scheme,
but also the state level scheme.

00:52:44.773 --> 00:52:46.533
The companies were funded
by the states also.

00:52:47.893 --> 00:52:49.093
So...

00:52:49.773 --> 00:52:51.853
So we said, okay, we'll see.

00:52:51.933 --> 00:52:53.413
And then we started fighting.

00:52:53.493 --> 00:52:57.493
It was a price, you know,
price battle started going on.

00:52:57.573 --> 00:53:00.493
You know, when the Xiaomis of the world
started coming in and then the...

00:53:00.573 --> 00:53:03.533
So before that, we were fighting,
let's say, with the Samsungs

00:53:03.613 --> 00:53:07.413
and the Motos
or the Sony Ericssons of the world.

00:53:09.093 --> 00:53:10.773
Doing pretty well.

00:53:10.853 --> 00:53:13.413
And then you start...
suddenly you start having a competition

00:53:13.493 --> 00:53:17.693
wherein if you are selling, let's say,
at 100 rupees,

00:53:17.773 --> 00:53:20.013
somebody comes and says,
hey, I'm 90 rupees.

00:53:21.333 --> 00:53:23.013
[Nikhil] And if you say 80,
they'll say 70.

00:53:23.093 --> 00:53:25.413
[Rahul] They'll say 70.
So that's how it's a race to the bottom.

00:53:25.493 --> 00:53:29.453
And then suddenly
they were burning a lot of money.

00:53:29.533 --> 00:53:31.853
-But can I ask a structural question?
-Yes. Yes.

00:53:32.733 --> 00:53:36.093
While it seems like a race to the bottom,

00:53:36.173 --> 00:53:39.813
because of the scale of manufacturing
they have,

00:53:39.893 --> 00:53:45.133
is the cost of production in China
inherently so much lower

00:53:45.213 --> 00:53:48.613
that at 80 rupees you can't make money,
but at 70 rupees they can?

00:53:49.213 --> 00:53:53.493
So that's, yeah, that's true,
because it's the whole supply chain

00:53:53.573 --> 00:53:55.613
which is, you know,
which is established there.

00:53:56.333 --> 00:53:58.213
So probably what we were discussing.

00:53:58.293 --> 00:54:03.093
That if their BOM is 100, your BOM is 120.

00:54:03.173 --> 00:54:06.013
But you would also be importing
that time or manufacturing?

00:54:06.813 --> 00:54:11.133
No. So, see, we established
our first plant in India in 2010.

00:54:11.213 --> 00:54:14.373
-So you started early.
-Way before Make In India started.

00:54:14.453 --> 00:54:17.413
So, but the components
was coming from there, right?

00:54:18.053 --> 00:54:21.413
And at that time, all these brands
what we see right now,

00:54:21.493 --> 00:54:22.653
they were not there.

00:54:22.733 --> 00:54:27.613
So they started coming in, for example,
all the brands were there in DVD players

00:54:27.693 --> 00:54:29.933
or MP3 players, and then they started
coming on that.

00:54:31.933 --> 00:54:33.693
And then the price war started.

00:54:33.773 --> 00:54:38.053
And so, and we also went into it.

00:54:39.293 --> 00:54:42.733
But somehow with the whole supply chain
and everything, then you slowly,

00:54:42.813 --> 00:54:46.013
you know, access to all these things
started getting restricted.

00:54:46.933 --> 00:54:49.373
So, for example,
why Micromax became successful?

00:54:49.453 --> 00:54:52.293
Because in this...
in the industry where we are in,

00:54:52.373 --> 00:54:54.213
you are already, you know,
you're looking for a differentiation.

00:54:54.293 --> 00:54:56.893
For example, if I was designing a phone,
my question to myself was:

00:54:56.973 --> 00:54:59.053
Why will I buy,
or somebody will buy this phone?

00:54:59.133 --> 00:55:01.253
What is different in this one? Why?

00:55:01.333 --> 00:55:02.613
Why...

00:55:02.693 --> 00:55:04.413
Why somebody will not buy another phone?

00:55:04.493 --> 00:55:07.373
So, you know, that's how
the differentiators were coming in.

00:55:08.093 --> 00:55:10.133
And differentiator
was not only on the feature,

00:55:10.213 --> 00:55:13.653
but also on who's going to come up
with the latest chipset first.

00:55:13.733 --> 00:55:15.653
Who's going to come up with--
If there is a 50 megapixel camera,

00:55:15.733 --> 00:55:18.773
who's the first guy coming up
with a 50 megapixel camera?

00:55:18.853 --> 00:55:20.693
If there was a fast charging coming,

00:55:20.773 --> 00:55:22.373
who's the first guy
to come up with fast charging?

00:55:22.453 --> 00:55:25.373
And the distributors used to look at,
you know, look at us that,

00:55:25.453 --> 00:55:28.333
okay, they will come up
with something new every quarter and...

00:55:29.933 --> 00:55:31.933
So when that access
started getting stopped?

00:55:32.013 --> 00:55:33.733
Government stopped the access?

00:55:33.813 --> 00:55:37.373
No, no, it's not the government, you know,
because the scale shifted somewhere else.

00:55:38.133 --> 00:55:39.133
Right.

00:55:39.213 --> 00:55:42.893
And they preferred supplying
to their own companies than to you?

00:55:42.973 --> 00:55:48.173
Right. And so the numbers and everything,

00:55:48.253 --> 00:55:49.973
because their numbers
started growing up in...

00:55:50.053 --> 00:55:51.933
Because China itself
became a very big market

00:55:52.013 --> 00:55:53.893
and the scale was, you know, became big.

00:55:53.973 --> 00:55:56.093
Because, you know,
there are a lot of theories about...

00:55:56.173 --> 00:55:57.733
about Micromax in the market.

00:55:57.813 --> 00:56:00.693
This happened, that happened.
Everybody can come up with their own.

00:56:00.773 --> 00:56:02.853
Yeah. What is the theory...
the most popular one?

00:56:02.933 --> 00:56:04.413
No, I keep on hearing different one.

00:56:04.493 --> 00:56:07.773
Oh, they went, you know,
into luxury segment

00:56:07.853 --> 00:56:11.493
or there was no R&amp;D. You know, all this.

00:56:11.573 --> 00:56:13.213
But I don't know
how many people know, we...

00:56:13.293 --> 00:56:15.573
When Nokia got sold, we had the...

00:56:15.653 --> 00:56:20.133
You know, we took all the top Nokia,
they had the gold, you know, division.

00:56:20.213 --> 00:56:23.133
We got all gold guys from Nokia
and doing the R&amp;D at that time.

00:56:23.213 --> 00:56:26.613
But whatever this was happening,
all this, you know, coming from China,

00:56:27.333 --> 00:56:28.533
it was a global phenomenon.

00:56:28.613 --> 00:56:30.653
So it was not only that we were affected.

00:56:30.733 --> 00:56:32.653
All the other, let's say,
there were other brands

00:56:32.733 --> 00:56:37.653
in Turkey or in Malaysia,

00:56:37.733 --> 00:56:40.093
other places,
you know, everybody got affected.

00:56:40.813 --> 00:56:47.413
And I think in 2019 odd or so,
we realised that, you know,

00:56:47.493 --> 00:56:49.933
you can burn money,
but you know, you can burn money

00:56:50.013 --> 00:56:52.213
till the point you know
that I'm going to win the game.

00:56:52.293 --> 00:56:53.293
Right.

00:56:53.373 --> 00:56:57.413
But if the other person is having
an unlimited supplies,

00:56:57.493 --> 00:56:59.093
like a bottomless pit.

00:56:59.173 --> 00:57:02.613
A bit like today, no?
All the loss-making startups in India,

00:57:03.533 --> 00:57:05.373
all competing downwards.

00:57:05.453 --> 00:57:07.253
Yeah.

00:57:07.333 --> 00:57:11.773
And see, and we build Micromax,
let's say, from day one, making money

00:57:11.853 --> 00:57:15.213
and doing that, you know,
never raised any capital.

00:57:15.893 --> 00:57:19.413
Slowly, slowly, you know, build it
and whatever, you know, we raised.

00:57:19.493 --> 00:57:22.733
Said no to $800 million in 2014.

00:57:22.813 --> 00:57:26.493
-So if you ask me in hindsight that.
-You should have taken it.

00:57:26.573 --> 00:57:29.333
Yeah, because see, that time we never knew
that you had to create a war chest.

00:57:29.413 --> 00:57:31.333
[Nikhil] Yeah.

00:57:31.413 --> 00:57:33.933
You create a war chest
and say, "Okay, now let's, you know--"

00:57:34.013 --> 00:57:37.013
Biggest bull run in Indian equity markets.
Imagine you put that in equity.

00:57:38.013 --> 00:57:39.493
2014 to today.

00:57:39.573 --> 00:57:41.173
Yeah. So, you know, with $800 million,

00:57:41.253 --> 00:57:43.053
you sit on the casino table
and say, okay, now play.

00:57:43.133 --> 00:57:44.333
-Yeah.
-[Carl] Yeah.

00:57:45.933 --> 00:57:47.333
Yeah, so, and then after...

00:57:48.533 --> 00:57:50.733
Yeah, in 2009,
then we realised that, you know,

00:57:50.813 --> 00:57:52.933
either we'll, you know,
if we keep on burning with this space,

00:57:53.693 --> 00:57:55.013
we will get finished.

00:57:55.093 --> 00:57:56.453
We'll get completely burned out.

00:57:56.533 --> 00:57:58.573
We will not have any capital left.

00:57:59.253 --> 00:58:00.733
So we said,
"Okay, let's stop burning money.

00:58:01.973 --> 00:58:04.253
And wait for your turn.

00:58:04.933 --> 00:58:07.133
And start focusing on manufacturing."

00:58:07.693 --> 00:58:11.133
And that's how
we started building more factories

00:58:11.813 --> 00:58:15.573
in 19, 20, 21, and now.

00:58:17.493 --> 00:58:22.133
And that's how we, you know,
pivoted on the manufacturing game.

00:58:22.213 --> 00:58:26.533
And the whole idea is that unless
and until you have access to supply chain.

00:58:26.613 --> 00:58:31.413
For example, if today I have to make
a triple screen fold...

00:58:33.573 --> 00:58:34.693
I don't have access to the screen.

00:58:36.013 --> 00:58:37.173
So how do you come up with the latest?

00:58:37.253 --> 00:58:39.653
-When you say access to supply chain...
-Yes.

00:58:39.733 --> 00:58:42.373
...you're talking about
the company in China that gives--

00:58:42.453 --> 00:58:43.853
That makes the screen. Okay?

00:58:43.933 --> 00:58:45.093
That makes the display.

00:58:45.173 --> 00:58:46.973
But the other bigger company there,

00:58:47.053 --> 00:58:48.933
for example, let's say Huawei,
has a triple screen.

00:58:49.013 --> 00:58:50.013
Huawei has already blocked that

00:58:50.093 --> 00:58:52.533
and said, "Okay, for one year
you can't give to anybody else.

00:58:52.613 --> 00:58:54.933
Because I am promising you
this much of volume."

00:58:55.013 --> 00:58:58.893
So, Nikhil,
how it happens is all partners,

00:58:58.973 --> 00:59:02.453
like supply chain partners,
screen, battery, or processor,

00:59:02.533 --> 00:59:03.933
they work with bigger brands,

00:59:04.013 --> 00:59:06.213
and everybody has an alpha customer
on their list.

00:59:06.293 --> 00:59:09.053
Let's say Huawei would be
the alpha customer on the list.

00:59:09.133 --> 00:59:11.453
So every first technology
would go to Huawei.

00:59:12.213 --> 00:59:15.733
He will block the capacity,
and when it is over, it will come to us.

00:59:15.813 --> 00:59:18.933
New technology means all resources
they will depute to Huawei.

00:59:19.013 --> 00:59:20.333
And then it will come to the market,

00:59:20.413 --> 00:59:24.173
and Huawei will take the first leg
of new product, which is launching,

00:59:24.253 --> 00:59:27.933
which goes for chipsets,
screens, sensor, across.

00:59:28.013 --> 00:59:30.653
But we will never be able to make that
on our own.

00:59:30.733 --> 00:59:34.773
For anybody wanting to start
a consumer electronic company,

00:59:35.493 --> 00:59:37.653
you can't make that triple-fold screen

00:59:37.733 --> 00:59:40.853
that this supply chain vendor
is making for Huawei.

00:59:41.573 --> 00:59:44.333
No, if you are, like, a "startup" startup,
it is too hard to make.

00:59:45.533 --> 00:59:47.093
It requires a lot of money and probably--

00:59:47.173 --> 00:59:48.733
[Amit] He might be making it.

00:59:48.813 --> 00:59:49.893
-It's at a later stage.
-He can answer.

00:59:49.973 --> 00:59:51.733
-Yes, later stage.
-It's at a later stage.

00:59:51.813 --> 00:59:53.853
So if you look at Apple's strategy now,

00:59:53.933 --> 00:59:56.933
they feel like they're bleeding
too much margin to their suppliers.

00:59:57.013 --> 00:59:58.773
-[Amit] Yeah.
-So they're doing vertical integration.

00:59:58.853 --> 01:00:00.773
So they are developing
their own technology,

01:00:00.853 --> 01:00:02.693
their own screen,
their own whatever processor.

01:00:02.773 --> 01:00:05.613
I thought they're outsourcing more
to Foxconn and--

01:00:05.693 --> 01:00:07.493
-For manufacturing.
-It's only for EMS.

01:00:07.573 --> 01:00:09.333
-What is EMS?
-Assembling.

01:00:09.413 --> 01:00:11.133
-You would attempt better.
-Just for assembling?

01:00:12.213 --> 01:00:13.373
-Really?
-[Rahul] Yes.

01:00:13.453 --> 01:00:16.173
So Apple used to be
a consumer-focused company, right?

01:00:16.253 --> 01:00:18.293
So in the start, they were very small.

01:00:18.373 --> 01:00:21.373
They were competing against IBM,
and, like, big PC companies.

01:00:21.893 --> 01:00:24.853
So they targeted a niche consumer,
the creative consumer.

01:00:25.613 --> 01:00:28.573
And they positioned the personal computer
as a bicycle for the mind.

01:00:28.653 --> 01:00:29.653
So if you have an idea,

01:00:29.733 --> 01:00:32.893
you can use your Apple computer
to manifest that idea.

01:00:32.973 --> 01:00:35.573
In the '90s,
they started acquiring software companies

01:00:36.133 --> 01:00:38.613
to then create their own suite
of content creation tools

01:00:38.693 --> 01:00:40.653
like iMovie, GarageBand.

01:00:41.373 --> 01:00:42.893
It's all to cater to the creative, right?

01:00:42.973 --> 01:00:44.413
Beautiful industrial design,

01:00:44.493 --> 01:00:48.053
great software that helps you
take your ideas into reality.

01:00:48.653 --> 01:00:51.053
After some time,
they really captured the creatives.

01:00:51.573 --> 01:00:54.653
-Like, they had a partnership with Adobe.
-Yeah.

01:00:54.733 --> 01:00:56.573
Adobe worked better on Apple computers.

01:00:57.413 --> 01:00:59.973
So once they got the creatives,
the brand became really cool.

01:01:00.573 --> 01:01:03.573
So normal people,
they also wanted to feel creative.

01:01:03.653 --> 01:01:05.613
So therefore,
"I buy Apples 'cause I'm a creative."

01:01:06.933 --> 01:01:08.173
But then...

01:01:08.253 --> 01:01:09.613
So they won the consumer battle.

01:01:09.693 --> 01:01:12.573
And then to keep growing the share price,

01:01:12.653 --> 01:01:14.853
they needed to take the value
back from their suppliers

01:01:14.933 --> 01:01:17.333
'cause they had outsourced
a lot of the components.

01:01:18.013 --> 01:01:20.853
So in the recent ten years,
it's been a vertical integration strategy.

01:01:21.813 --> 01:01:23.093
Now they do their own processors.

01:01:23.173 --> 01:01:26.893
Actually, what we talked about before,
they get the TSMC latest...

01:01:27.573 --> 01:01:28.813
There you need allocation.

01:01:28.893 --> 01:01:31.653
Yeah, they get the first batch
before everybody else.

01:01:31.733 --> 01:01:34.773
They get the latest technology from TSMC
for Apple silicon.

01:01:35.293 --> 01:01:38.413
Now they're doing a mini...
Is it mini-LED or micro-LED?

01:01:38.493 --> 01:01:40.613
They have their own display technology.

01:01:41.253 --> 01:01:42.813
It's deployed on the Apple Watch already.

01:01:42.893 --> 01:01:44.333
The mini-LED.

01:01:44.413 --> 01:01:45.413
[Carl] Mini-LED.

01:01:45.493 --> 01:01:47.573
So it's very hard
for anyone to compete, right?

01:01:47.653 --> 01:01:48.853
It's a very tough industry.

01:01:50.133 --> 01:01:56.213
And everybody who is an incumbent today
has been around for 30, 40, 50, 100 years?

01:01:57.213 --> 01:02:00.053
Apple is, like, 50, I think. 50-ish.

01:02:00.133 --> 01:02:02.453
-Samsung is older.
-Yeah.

01:02:02.533 --> 01:02:06.933
But Samsung's smartphone business
should be similar, maybe 25 years.

01:02:07.453 --> 01:02:09.053
The Chinese brand, maybe 15 years.

01:02:10.053 --> 01:02:14.653
So every ten years, the cards will flip.

01:02:14.733 --> 01:02:17.413
[Rahul] Yeah, so I think
this is a very interesting thing...

01:02:18.493 --> 01:02:22.413
if you're talking about competing,
or nobody can come up.

01:02:22.493 --> 01:02:24.093
-We came up at that time.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

01:02:24.173 --> 01:02:25.333
Defying the odds, you know.

01:02:25.413 --> 01:02:30.973
Globally there was, you know, no brand,
like a local brand who came and became...

01:02:31.053 --> 01:02:33.293
Like, we were top ten in the world,
and that's how it was going.

01:02:35.413 --> 01:02:37.733
I still feel that can happen. Right?

01:02:39.013 --> 01:02:44.893
But we never realised that governments
have to, you know, play a role in it.

01:02:44.973 --> 01:02:47.573
Because at that time we never thought
about the governments and the countries.

01:02:47.653 --> 01:02:50.413
Now we realise about countries,
governments, and everything.

01:02:50.493 --> 01:02:51.893
-What should the government do?
-Yeah.

01:02:52.893 --> 01:02:56.173
For example,
you take our automobile industry in India.

01:02:57.613 --> 01:02:58.853
I think we have done a great job there.

01:02:59.693 --> 01:03:02.813
All the Hondas and Suzukis came initially,

01:03:02.893 --> 01:03:05.293
did joint ventures
with the Indian companies.

01:03:06.493 --> 01:03:09.293
Created a lot of ecosystem
of supply chain.

01:03:09.373 --> 01:03:11.293
-You see all the component players.
-Yeah.

01:03:12.013 --> 01:03:13.013
Right?

01:03:13.093 --> 01:03:15.213
And now if you see
our automobile industry,

01:03:15.293 --> 01:03:16.413
we are supplying to the world now.

01:03:17.773 --> 01:03:19.613
We are a very mature industry
in automobile.

01:03:19.693 --> 01:03:21.813
And if the same thing were true
for mobile phones,

01:03:21.893 --> 01:03:23.693
what happened to Micromax
would not have happened.

01:03:24.653 --> 01:03:27.573
Maybe, you know,
the world order would have been different

01:03:27.653 --> 01:03:28.813
in terms of the brands.

01:03:28.893 --> 01:03:29.973
-Right.
-Yeah.

01:03:30.053 --> 01:03:33.613
So, any industry, you need to see
that you want to make local champions.

01:03:33.693 --> 01:03:36.453
So for example,
today in the worldly order,

01:03:36.533 --> 01:03:41.173
imagine if there are two, three
local champions coming out of India

01:03:41.733 --> 01:03:43.573
who can make a global impact.

01:03:43.653 --> 01:03:44.933
I think it would be great for the country.

01:03:45.013 --> 01:03:46.253
[Nikhil] But if we...

01:03:46.333 --> 01:03:47.573
There's a flip side to that argument

01:03:47.653 --> 01:03:50.373
that if we become protectionist
of local industry...

01:03:51.333 --> 01:03:54.933
do we continue to get foreign money
into the country?

01:03:55.933 --> 01:03:57.933
So I'm not saying that you stop.

01:03:58.013 --> 01:04:00.133
I'm saying you allow collaborations.

01:04:01.613 --> 01:04:03.213
Collaborations where you need to learn.

01:04:03.933 --> 01:04:05.973
-Collaborations with technology transfer.
-[Rahul] Absolutely.

01:04:06.053 --> 01:04:07.453
-IP transfer.
-Yes.

01:04:07.533 --> 01:04:09.533
Work on IP transfer, and then you learn.

01:04:09.613 --> 01:04:11.413
So in four, five years, you will learn.

01:04:12.973 --> 01:04:15.453
Right? See, I said,
"Auto happened, you know, at that time."

01:04:15.533 --> 01:04:17.533
Now today you have all the local companies
ruling the roost.

01:04:18.853 --> 01:04:21.413
Similarly, you learn here,
five years, six years.

01:04:21.493 --> 01:04:23.973
So, a lot of people ask me,
"Okay, can you do this?

01:04:24.053 --> 01:04:26.333
Can you make a, you know,
very complex phone?"

01:04:26.413 --> 01:04:28.173
We said,
"Yes, we can make a very complex phone.

01:04:28.253 --> 01:04:30.813
But maybe it will take five years,
six years in India to do that.

01:04:31.413 --> 01:04:34.013
But with collaboration,
I can start learning right away.

01:04:34.093 --> 01:04:35.973
And then can do it very, very quickly."

01:04:36.053 --> 01:04:40.173
And how much did this three million phones
a number fall to

01:04:40.253 --> 01:04:41.933
when things went bad at Micromax?

01:04:42.013 --> 01:04:43.133
No, no, it totally started coming.

01:04:43.213 --> 01:04:45.293
Every year it started coming up,
we started losing.

01:04:45.373 --> 01:04:46.413
At that time,

01:04:46.493 --> 01:04:49.453
all the Indian brands were more than 50%
of the Indian market share.

01:04:49.533 --> 01:04:52.293
-Right. Right.
-Which completely got decimated.

01:04:52.373 --> 01:04:54.813
What was the low for Micromax
as a company?

01:04:54.893 --> 01:04:56.493
Which year was the low?

01:04:56.573 --> 01:05:03.133
I think that time in 2019, 2020,
in terms of the brand--

01:05:03.213 --> 01:05:04.733
-Just before COVID.
-Yeah.

01:05:04.813 --> 01:05:07.173
-We said, "Okay, no more..."
-And then COVID could not have been fun.

01:05:07.253 --> 01:05:08.813
[laughter]

01:05:09.853 --> 01:05:11.053
-Right?
-Yeah.

01:05:12.533 --> 01:05:17.573
When you go from a peak to a low,
what is the one lesson that we can learn

01:05:17.653 --> 01:05:20.133
from your experience
that you have learnt already?

01:05:20.213 --> 01:05:22.493
Today, our manufacturing is bigger than,
you know,

01:05:22.573 --> 01:05:25.493
the revenue is way more bigger
than what we used to do in our brand.

01:05:25.573 --> 01:05:28.053
Which probably
not most of the people will know.

01:05:28.133 --> 01:05:31.213
But we are doing way more better
than what we used to do earlier.

01:05:31.293 --> 01:05:32.533
No, I know the Micromax comebacks.

01:05:32.613 --> 01:05:34.333
No, I know. But I am coming.

01:05:34.413 --> 01:05:38.213
So, in between, you know,
you are trying multiple things.

01:05:38.293 --> 01:05:41.573
I think what has worked for us,
you know, we later realised that,

01:05:41.653 --> 01:05:43.093
stick to your core.

01:05:43.173 --> 01:05:44.853
What did you realise is your core?

01:05:44.933 --> 01:05:47.733
So my core was to remain with tech.

01:05:47.813 --> 01:05:49.653
So, for example,
I'll not start a real estate company.

01:05:49.733 --> 01:05:51.373
Real estate is doing good, go there.

01:05:51.453 --> 01:05:52.973
Or something else is doing good, go there.

01:05:53.053 --> 01:05:54.213
Or something.

01:05:54.293 --> 01:05:56.573
So this thing was already there.

01:05:56.653 --> 01:05:58.773
The whole manufacturing,
the factories what we created,

01:05:58.853 --> 01:06:00.373
you know, for Micromax, was already there.

01:06:00.453 --> 01:06:03.013
So why don't we build on that?

01:06:06.253 --> 01:06:07.453
And start doing for others.

01:06:08.413 --> 01:06:09.413
That helped, and that's how we...

01:06:10.173 --> 01:06:11.293
So at Micromax time,

01:06:11.373 --> 01:06:13.493
we were having probably
one or two factories.

01:06:13.573 --> 01:06:18.053
Now, we have four large factories,
fifth coming up, and then--

01:06:18.133 --> 01:06:19.893
You just acquired a new factory as well.

01:06:19.973 --> 01:06:21.853
And now you are scaling.

01:06:22.973 --> 01:06:25.533
Do you feel like you are stronger
the second time around

01:06:25.613 --> 01:06:26.813
than you were in the beginning?

01:06:27.933 --> 01:06:30.093
Less oblivious, more aware.

01:06:31.693 --> 01:06:33.613
Like, I feel like
once somebody is scarred,

01:06:35.013 --> 01:06:39.413
the next time they're a little bit
more differentiated in their approach.

01:06:39.493 --> 01:06:41.813
This weekend I was thinking that.

01:06:41.893 --> 01:06:43.333
-Believe me.
-In Goa?

01:06:43.413 --> 01:06:44.813
Yeah. [chuckles]

01:06:45.533 --> 01:06:46.733
I was thinking about that.

01:06:47.493 --> 01:06:49.893
About something I used to do earlier.

01:06:50.693 --> 01:06:53.893
And then I again thought,
"I am still doing the same thing."

01:06:53.973 --> 01:06:55.053
Which is?

01:06:55.133 --> 01:06:58.413
Taking big bets, going risky, and all.

01:06:58.493 --> 01:07:02.213
Like, you know, once you start doing,
I said, "Okay, no, no, no more, no more.

01:07:03.493 --> 01:07:05.613
Stick, stick to your, you know..."

01:07:05.693 --> 01:07:08.333
-But--
-Risk is intoxicating, no?

01:07:08.413 --> 01:07:09.453
It is.

01:07:09.533 --> 01:07:10.733
While you are taking it?

01:07:10.813 --> 01:07:11.853
Yeah.

01:07:11.933 --> 01:07:13.453
-It gives you a high?
-Yeah.

01:07:14.613 --> 01:07:15.733
And believe that, "Okay, no, no, no,

01:07:15.813 --> 01:07:18.453
this is something I think you can do,
you can crack it."

01:07:19.093 --> 01:07:20.093
And then you go for it.

01:07:21.293 --> 01:07:23.453
And because it has worked earlier,
then you start thinking.

01:07:23.533 --> 01:07:25.133
Then you know every time
it is going to work,

01:07:25.213 --> 01:07:26.213
which is not the case.

01:07:28.693 --> 01:07:31.613
So, yes, while, you know,
we are doing this, I am more aware.

01:07:32.373 --> 01:07:34.693
But the core is that, nah?

01:07:34.773 --> 01:07:39.933
So once your core is that,
you will want to take bigger bets,

01:07:40.013 --> 01:07:42.693
thinking that,
"Okay, nothing happened earlier.

01:07:42.773 --> 01:07:45.053
You know, you came out of it, see?"

01:07:46.413 --> 01:07:47.773
So I think that's the DNA.

01:07:47.853 --> 01:07:51.013
As long as the bets don't go wrong,
they always get bigger,

01:07:51.093 --> 01:07:52.493
-organically.
-Yeah.

01:07:52.573 --> 01:07:56.173
If you had to bet money
on some entrepreneur today,

01:07:57.333 --> 01:07:59.933
wouldn't you pick somebody
who has screwed up a couple of times

01:08:00.013 --> 01:08:02.413
versus somebody
who is doing it for the first time?

01:08:04.173 --> 01:08:06.373
Screwed up a couple of times,
but eventually made it.

01:08:06.453 --> 01:08:08.413
-Yeah, that is important.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

01:08:08.493 --> 01:08:09.813
Yeah.

01:08:09.893 --> 01:08:12.333
If eventually made it,
then, yeah, that's fine.

01:08:12.413 --> 01:08:16.533
I feel like this prophecy is true
for all life.

01:08:16.613 --> 01:08:20.253
I like people
who are a little bit screwed up

01:08:20.333 --> 01:08:21.333
in all domains.

01:08:22.133 --> 01:08:24.933
When I meet a man
and I don't know what his vice is,

01:08:25.013 --> 01:08:26.013
I assume the worst.

01:08:26.813 --> 01:08:29.973
I'd rather know, "Okay, this is my friend,
he is [bleep] up like this, I am aware.

01:08:30.053 --> 01:08:31.893
I am [bleep] up like that, he is aware."

01:08:31.973 --> 01:08:33.013
This friendship is good.

01:08:34.213 --> 01:08:38.133
When somebody comes to me
and projects the idealistic mask,

01:08:38.213 --> 01:08:39.213
then I worry.

01:08:40.253 --> 01:08:42.453
Because we are all the same
at the core of it, you know.

01:08:42.533 --> 01:08:44.813
We are all inherently flawed as people.

01:08:44.893 --> 01:08:46.373
-100%.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

01:08:47.933 --> 01:08:49.253
Yeah.

01:08:49.333 --> 01:08:50.333
But thank you for that.

01:08:50.413 --> 01:08:51.573
[laughter]

01:08:52.253 --> 01:08:54.733
All right, Mr. Amit, you're next.

01:08:55.613 --> 01:08:57.293
-Tell us.
-I think--

01:08:57.373 --> 01:09:00.413
I'm very interested in your story
'cause both of their stories--

01:09:00.493 --> 01:09:01.773
-Him, I know firsthand.
-Yeah.

01:09:01.853 --> 01:09:03.573
And his, I have read a bit.

01:09:03.653 --> 01:09:05.813
But your story is not so much out there.

01:09:06.493 --> 01:09:10.493
So I come from a small town,
Bikaner, Rajasthan.

01:09:10.573 --> 01:09:12.253
And typical middle-class family.

01:09:12.333 --> 01:09:13.653
Father used to work with bank.

01:09:14.733 --> 01:09:15.933
Which bank?

01:09:16.013 --> 01:09:18.373
State Bank of Bikaner &amp; Jaipur,
if you would have heard of.

01:09:18.453 --> 01:09:19.453
SBBJ.

01:09:20.053 --> 01:09:21.653
Later on they got merged with SBI.

01:09:22.453 --> 01:09:24.653
And Grandfather was an advocate.

01:09:24.733 --> 01:09:26.933
So typical middle class.

01:09:27.013 --> 01:09:28.413
And when you're in a small town,

01:09:28.493 --> 01:09:31.813
the only dream is you become a doctor
or an engineer.

01:09:32.573 --> 01:09:35.173
But I think I was not geared up for that.

01:09:35.253 --> 01:09:37.133
I was a very mischievous kid.

01:09:37.893 --> 01:09:39.613
Academically not very strong.

01:09:39.693 --> 01:09:42.053
I mean, 60, 70% scorer at that time...

01:09:42.973 --> 01:09:45.973
where people were, I think, 80, 85, or...

01:09:46.053 --> 01:09:47.653
I was the eldest one in the family.

01:09:50.093 --> 01:09:51.573
No, no. He's fit.

01:09:51.653 --> 01:09:52.773
-[Rahul] Yeah?
-And he went to NIFT.

01:09:56.573 --> 01:09:58.813
-NIFT ones are the cool ones.
-Yeah.

01:09:58.893 --> 01:10:01.173
I have some colleagues who are from there.

01:10:01.253 --> 01:10:02.493
Sometimes, over-smart.

01:10:02.573 --> 01:10:03.573
Right?

01:10:03.653 --> 01:10:05.053
[laughter]

01:10:05.133 --> 01:10:06.333
Fashion college.

01:10:06.413 --> 01:10:08.893
Yeah, it's like
where all the cool kids go.

01:10:08.973 --> 01:10:10.933
So anyways--

01:10:11.013 --> 01:10:13.173
See, his shirt has
a very differentiated colour.

01:10:15.333 --> 01:10:16.373
It's not white, right?

01:10:17.573 --> 01:10:18.573
[chuckles] It's not white.

01:10:18.653 --> 01:10:19.653
[Nikhil] What colour is it?

01:10:19.733 --> 01:10:22.173
Somewhere off-white, beige-ish.

01:10:22.253 --> 01:10:25.173
So I went...

01:10:25.253 --> 01:10:28.213
My parents wanted me to become a doctor.

01:10:28.293 --> 01:10:31.173
And actually,
I was pushed towards that career

01:10:31.253 --> 01:10:34.373
because in small towns,
I think those were the two choice.

01:10:34.453 --> 01:10:38.373
And apparently went to Kota also
for PMT preparation.

01:10:39.173 --> 01:10:41.453
Medical test at that time
for crash course.

01:10:41.533 --> 01:10:44.773
But eventually realised
that I think I can't do that.

01:10:44.853 --> 01:10:46.533
And fortunately what happened that...

01:10:46.613 --> 01:10:51.293
My father was very, you know, bold
that he wanted to get out of Bikaner

01:10:51.373 --> 01:10:52.373
and move to a bigger city.

01:10:52.453 --> 01:10:53.613
And he moved to Kanpur, actually.

01:10:54.253 --> 01:10:56.333
He got posted there.
And when he moved there,

01:10:56.413 --> 01:10:59.093
I realised that it's just not this
as a career.

01:10:59.173 --> 01:11:02.173
There are people who are securing
80%, 85% marks

01:11:02.253 --> 01:11:04.253
and going to Delhi for B.Com.

01:11:04.333 --> 01:11:06.893
So I realised that Mass Com is a course.

01:11:06.973 --> 01:11:08.213
B.Com is a course.

01:11:08.293 --> 01:11:10.093
Arts people are doing because of passion.

01:11:10.173 --> 01:11:13.653
And well-familied, good-educated kids.

01:11:13.733 --> 01:11:15.733
Then I realised that
medical I don't want to do.

01:11:15.813 --> 01:11:17.333
I enjoyed maths, physics,

01:11:17.413 --> 01:11:19.293
those kind of subjects
where I don't need to mug up.

01:11:20.373 --> 01:11:23.253
And definitely a small-town kid
going to a bigger city,

01:11:23.333 --> 01:11:26.613
so you get a little bit buoyed away
by what's happening there.

01:11:27.493 --> 01:11:28.653
I realised that.

01:11:28.733 --> 01:11:30.413
Then parents said, "Do an IIT."

01:11:30.493 --> 01:11:32.853
Then I realised it's too late for me
to do an IIT now.

01:11:32.933 --> 01:11:35.453
Otherwise you'll ask me
to bunk for three years.

01:11:35.533 --> 01:11:38.693
And I think it's '98, '99.

01:11:38.773 --> 01:11:43.493
And eventually, after graduation,
started preparing for competitive exams.

01:11:43.573 --> 01:11:45.133
And formally landed into NIFT.

01:11:45.853 --> 01:11:50.853
So I think NIFT Hyderabad
was a real-life learning for me.

01:11:51.893 --> 01:11:54.253
First time hostel. Getting out of home.

01:11:54.973 --> 01:11:57.693
And I was into fashion management,
not design.

01:11:57.773 --> 01:12:00.773
But maybe all the peers were design guys.

01:12:00.853 --> 01:12:04.853
And again,
Dad took a loan for me to go to college.

01:12:04.933 --> 01:12:08.373
So I had always limitation
that I should not be spending more.

01:12:08.453 --> 01:12:10.413
And then my friends
had higher pocket money.

01:12:10.493 --> 01:12:13.453
So I think my entrepreneurship stint
started from there.

01:12:13.533 --> 01:12:16.533
Tell me things about yourself
that I can't Google.

01:12:17.453 --> 01:12:19.493
Or watch in another interview of yours.

01:12:19.573 --> 01:12:20.973
'Cause that's boring. I don't wanna know.

01:12:22.213 --> 01:12:26.053
I mean... notorious kid, definitely.

01:12:26.133 --> 01:12:31.973
And, I mean, I always had hunger
to do something different.

01:12:32.733 --> 01:12:36.693
And in college, like I said,
I used to look for alternate sources.

01:12:36.773 --> 01:12:39.413
I was again, let's say there was...

01:12:39.493 --> 01:12:41.773
high-tech city was all call centres
if you look into it.

01:12:41.853 --> 01:12:43.493
Hyderabad that time.

01:12:43.573 --> 01:12:45.013
Convergys and all.

01:12:45.093 --> 01:12:47.053
So I thought of maybe doing a job
at a call centre.

01:12:47.133 --> 01:12:49.373
Maybe pick some project at Convergys.

01:12:49.453 --> 01:12:51.093
Not Convergys, maybe, Infosys was there.

01:12:51.173 --> 01:12:53.373
Went to ISP to pitch something.

01:12:53.453 --> 01:12:56.333
And maybe just started picking up
some projects at our college only,

01:12:56.413 --> 01:12:58.213
where, you know,
there was a fest happening,

01:12:58.293 --> 01:12:59.413
"Could you bundle the T-shirts?"

01:12:59.493 --> 01:13:03.973
So I think my first entrepreneurship time
happened from there on.

01:13:04.053 --> 01:13:06.013
I started making
a little bit of pocket money from there.

01:13:07.133 --> 01:13:10.733
But I was always insecure in life
that I'll not get the job.

01:13:10.813 --> 01:13:11.973
Otherwise I was like...

01:13:12.053 --> 01:13:14.493
So you've finished college,
and what did you do first?

01:13:14.573 --> 01:13:16.293
When did you finish college?

01:13:16.373 --> 01:13:18.173
So I finished college in 2004.

01:13:18.813 --> 01:13:21.973
And I got placed
in the manufacturing setup,

01:13:22.053 --> 01:13:23.893
Orient Craft, if you would know.

01:13:23.973 --> 01:13:25.053
Based out of Gurgaon.

01:13:25.133 --> 01:13:29.093
So that is one of the largest export house
out of India.

01:13:29.173 --> 01:13:31.893
I thought I would not get
a better job than this.

01:13:31.973 --> 01:13:33.333
So I stayed there.

01:13:33.413 --> 01:13:35.253
And I worked
for three and a half years there.

01:13:35.333 --> 01:13:36.853
It was typically merchandising.

01:13:37.773 --> 01:13:41.253
And two years I did merchandising,
I found it very boring.

01:13:41.333 --> 01:13:43.733
And I thought of leaving the job
that time because...

01:13:43.813 --> 01:13:45.773
If you would know, merchandising is...

01:13:45.853 --> 01:13:48.173
buyers say you something
and then you copy paste.

01:13:48.253 --> 01:13:50.893
I used to work for Ann Taylor, Gap,
all those brands.

01:13:50.973 --> 01:13:54.253
And then I started giving interviews
actually everywhere outside.

01:13:54.333 --> 01:13:56.853
I went to Barista.
"Can I do job in marketing?"

01:13:56.933 --> 01:13:58.773
Coffee Day was big. There was...

01:13:58.853 --> 01:14:01.533
I went to Air Deccan for an interview
to apply for marketing.

01:14:01.613 --> 01:14:03.973
I was fed up of my career that time.

01:14:04.053 --> 01:14:06.853
Ironically, three people
who have proficiency in marketing

01:14:06.933 --> 01:14:09.053
are running consumer electronic companies.

01:14:10.173 --> 01:14:11.573
So maybe that's a prerequisite.

01:14:11.653 --> 01:14:15.693
We could catch
the market pulse well, actually.

01:14:16.893 --> 01:14:19.013
And maybe I didn't get a job
anywhere outside.

01:14:19.093 --> 01:14:23.213
And I started taking on
all special projects at the company.

01:14:23.293 --> 01:14:25.653
What all the pain problems of the company,
I could take that.

01:14:25.733 --> 01:14:27.973
-And you worked with your brother?
-No, no, no.

01:14:28.053 --> 01:14:29.893
So my brother is ten years younger to me.

01:14:30.733 --> 01:14:34.973
So he came in maybe... ten years ago.

01:14:35.973 --> 01:14:37.333
Twenty-five.

01:14:37.413 --> 01:14:39.373
For 15, 16, he came in.

01:14:39.453 --> 01:14:41.533
-So I was--
-So he's 28.

01:14:41.613 --> 01:14:44.053
So we are talking about 2005 to 2008.

01:14:44.133 --> 01:14:45.373
He is 28 years old.

01:14:45.453 --> 01:14:47.173
No, he's 35. 34, 35.

01:14:47.253 --> 01:14:48.333
You're 38.

01:14:48.413 --> 01:14:49.853
No, I am 43.

01:14:49.933 --> 01:14:51.973
-You're 43.
-Yeah, yeah. I'm 43.

01:14:53.613 --> 01:14:55.733
So anyways, I worked there
for three and a half years

01:14:55.813 --> 01:14:56.813
and then started picking up.

01:14:56.893 --> 01:14:58.533
You look very good, yeah, for 43.

01:14:59.413 --> 01:15:00.413
[Amit] Trying to.

01:15:00.933 --> 01:15:05.373
Working with young founders,
you have to stay true to that.

01:15:06.333 --> 01:15:09.533
Anyways, so I worked
for three and a half years.

01:15:09.613 --> 01:15:11.253
They moved me to...

01:15:11.333 --> 01:15:14.653
I saw a huge gap
in the international product development.

01:15:14.733 --> 01:15:18.053
I picked up that piece,
and that's my journey started.

01:15:18.133 --> 01:15:19.573
I moved to Hong Kong for the first time.

01:15:20.253 --> 01:15:25.573
And I think it was 2007 era
where I saw global brands were there.

01:15:25.653 --> 01:15:27.413
And whenever I used to travel,
people used to ask me,

01:15:27.493 --> 01:15:29.173
"Go and buy this thing for me,
that thing for me."

01:15:29.253 --> 01:15:31.693
I used to import
a lot of BlackBerrys from there.

01:15:31.773 --> 01:15:32.813
I think it was BlackBerry time.

01:15:33.613 --> 01:15:36.213
So I used to buy and trade off
for 1,000, 2,000 bucks

01:15:36.293 --> 01:15:38.413
and sell it in India in my office.

01:15:38.493 --> 01:15:40.733
-It was like jailbreak phones.
-[Rahul] Yeah.

01:15:40.813 --> 01:15:43.813
So every time I used to go buy ten phones
and bring it here.

01:15:43.893 --> 01:15:46.893
And eventually I realised
that I'm solving a bigger problem,

01:15:46.973 --> 01:15:48.853
not electronics, but textile.

01:15:48.933 --> 01:15:49.973
Let me do it myself.

01:15:50.053 --> 01:15:53.773
And I started my first business in 2007,

01:15:53.853 --> 01:15:57.693
which was fashion accessory,
textile merchandising, basically.

01:15:57.773 --> 01:15:59.773
Buying house, quasi concept.

01:15:59.853 --> 01:16:01.653
And I had 60,000 bucks in my pocket.

01:16:02.533 --> 01:16:05.013
And again, how could you do a business
with 60,000 bucks?

01:16:05.093 --> 01:16:07.773
So I started it in '7,
based out of Hong Kong.

01:16:07.853 --> 01:16:12.173
And I think that's where my journey
with H&amp;M started.

01:16:12.253 --> 01:16:13.853
H&amp;M was my first customer.

01:16:13.933 --> 01:16:16.853
I worked with them very closely
with the design team.

01:16:16.933 --> 01:16:19.053
So that's how I realised, man,

01:16:19.973 --> 01:16:22.613
there are brands
which are built at centre.

01:16:22.693 --> 01:16:26.893
So India was, I think, fashion...
Big Bazaar time that time.

01:16:26.973 --> 01:16:29.533
It was Micromax and Big Bazaar
which were at the bottom.

01:16:30.053 --> 01:16:32.013
And H&amp;M was right at the centre.

01:16:32.093 --> 01:16:36.813
Not cheap, not luxury,
but selling to the... to the world.

01:16:36.893 --> 01:16:37.973
Uniqlo, H&amp;M.

01:16:38.053 --> 01:16:42.053
And that's how, I think,
my roots got levelled

01:16:42.133 --> 01:16:44.533
at good-quality product
at an affordable price.

01:16:44.613 --> 01:16:46.573
Not the cheapest, not the expensive.

01:16:46.653 --> 01:16:49.333
I did that business
for seven and a half years,

01:16:49.413 --> 01:16:50.933
eight years, travelling a lot.

01:16:51.013 --> 01:16:53.733
And then Gaurav, my cousin, actually,

01:16:54.333 --> 01:16:57.853
he was 21,
he became commercial pilot, I think,

01:16:57.933 --> 01:17:00.933
Air Deccan time or Kingfisher
or Jet Airways, something tanked.

01:17:01.013 --> 01:17:02.173
No job.

01:17:02.253 --> 01:17:03.933
And he asked me
to get an iPhone that time.

01:17:04.013 --> 01:17:05.013
It was just launched.

01:17:05.093 --> 01:17:06.373
And I said, "Are you mad?"

01:17:06.453 --> 01:17:07.493
[Nikhil] What year?

01:17:07.573 --> 01:17:09.813
I think '14.

01:17:09.893 --> 01:17:11.533
-What time iPhone--
-[Carl] The first one?

01:17:11.613 --> 01:17:13.853
-Yeah.
-2007 or '8?

01:17:13.933 --> 01:17:15.533
-'8.
-2007, '8.

01:17:15.613 --> 01:17:18.053
So I think he asked me to get
the iPhone 3 sometime.

01:17:18.813 --> 01:17:20.693
So I got an iPhone 3 for him,
and I said, "Are you mad?"

01:17:20.773 --> 01:17:22.653
It is 25,000 bucks.

01:17:22.733 --> 01:17:26.773
And I got a jailbreak phone
from Hong Kong for him.

01:17:26.853 --> 01:17:28.813
And I got a phone for him.

01:17:28.893 --> 01:17:31.333
He said,
"Then I need to buy a cover for this."

01:17:31.413 --> 01:17:33.013
And there were no covers for that phone.

01:17:33.613 --> 01:17:35.053
And that's how our journey started.

01:17:35.133 --> 01:17:36.933
He said, "Let me get...

01:17:37.013 --> 01:17:39.653
I have a problem,
can you solve it for me?"

01:17:40.293 --> 01:17:43.253
If I have a problem,
my other friend should have a problem.

01:17:43.333 --> 01:17:44.973
So we started mobile accessories
that time.

01:17:45.053 --> 01:17:46.373
In which year?

01:17:46.453 --> 01:17:48.013
I think 2014, '15.

01:17:48.093 --> 01:17:49.773
I think Xiaomi came to India that time.

01:17:50.813 --> 01:17:52.853
We launched iPhone covers, we flopped.

01:17:52.933 --> 01:17:54.013
All stocks are at home.

01:17:54.093 --> 01:17:56.653
-Under the name Noise?
-Yeah, it's under the name Noise.

01:17:56.733 --> 01:17:58.573
So the company started in 2014.

01:17:58.653 --> 01:18:01.973
'14, '15, we started doing
mobile accessories as a side job.

01:18:02.053 --> 01:18:03.573
He was, as a hobby, doing it.

01:18:03.653 --> 01:18:06.133
I was doing my business, what I was doing.

01:18:06.813 --> 01:18:11.733
And then, iPhone, we had a huge failure,
because the market would be, what, .5%?

01:18:11.813 --> 01:18:14.973
We were the only few customers
buying iPhone.

01:18:15.653 --> 01:18:18.293
And then we flipped to Xiaomi.

01:18:18.373 --> 01:18:20.893
He was doing a side project,
and that's how our journey kicked in.

01:18:21.533 --> 01:18:22.533
And then what happened?

01:18:24.293 --> 01:18:26.453
The business started becoming very big.

01:18:26.533 --> 01:18:28.533
The phone, all Chinese guys came in.

01:18:28.613 --> 01:18:29.773
The business started becoming very big.

01:18:29.853 --> 01:18:32.373
You sold accessories
for the Chinese phones?

01:18:32.453 --> 01:18:33.573
Yeah, we sold accessories.

01:18:33.653 --> 01:18:36.333
Because, see, please understand,
we couldn't do tech.

01:18:36.413 --> 01:18:37.773
I was coming from a fashion background.

01:18:37.853 --> 01:18:39.093
I just knew designs.

01:18:39.773 --> 01:18:42.013
And mobile cover is just an accessory.

01:18:42.093 --> 01:18:43.453
I mean, it's like a T-shirt.

01:18:44.293 --> 01:18:46.253
It's such a simple product.
You get it, you print it.

01:18:46.333 --> 01:18:49.493
We had a small setup also
manufacturing in a factory

01:18:49.573 --> 01:18:52.173
where we used to ship
thousands of cases every day.

01:18:52.733 --> 01:18:56.613
And then we realised that this market
is getting super commoditised.

01:18:56.693 --> 01:18:58.013
And then when did Noise blow up?

01:18:59.213 --> 01:19:00.413
-I think--
-COVID?

01:19:00.493 --> 01:19:01.493
No, no, no, not COVID.

01:19:01.573 --> 01:19:03.293
I think we started picking up in '19.

01:19:03.373 --> 01:19:06.853
I'll tell you the trajectory,
what happened in between.

01:19:06.933 --> 01:19:08.773
So we were doing cases, which was fine.

01:19:09.653 --> 01:19:11.733
And we realised that the pricings
are going down.

01:19:11.813 --> 01:19:15.213
I mean, we started selling for 500 bucks,
and eventually it landed to 150.

01:19:15.893 --> 01:19:19.173
And 150, whatever case you sell,
you can't make a big company.

01:19:19.253 --> 01:19:20.253
So we were growing,

01:19:20.333 --> 01:19:23.173
but we were some 100 crore
revenue company.

01:19:23.893 --> 01:19:26.453
Then we thought of starting doing
different categories.

01:19:26.533 --> 01:19:30.893
We launched, everybody said marketplaces,
Flipkarts of the universe.

01:19:30.973 --> 01:19:34.813
"Why don't you do headphones,
neckbands, or whatever categories?"

01:19:34.893 --> 01:19:35.893
We did that, we failed.

01:19:35.973 --> 01:19:37.293
There was no differentiation.

01:19:38.013 --> 01:19:39.253
There was no differentiation.

01:19:39.333 --> 01:19:42.973
And then, out of interest,
we realised what categories to pick.

01:19:43.053 --> 01:19:45.893
So our thesis was clear,
we'll not fight the big boys.

01:19:45.973 --> 01:19:49.173
Like, Sony was selling wired earphones,
or Philips.

01:19:49.253 --> 01:19:50.493
I said, "Why would somebody buy us?"

01:19:50.573 --> 01:19:52.533
Till that time, we were cheaper,
and you can't be cheaper.

01:19:52.613 --> 01:19:53.813
Till that time, you cut cost.

01:19:55.453 --> 01:19:59.573
And we were searching for smartwatch
for ourselves that time in '19 something.

01:19:59.653 --> 01:20:01.373
I don't remember that time.

01:20:01.453 --> 01:20:03.773
And only Fitbit was available
for 20,000 grands.

01:20:03.853 --> 01:20:04.893
Fitbit Blaze or something.

01:20:04.973 --> 01:20:07.253
We got a refurb watch for 10,000.

01:20:07.333 --> 01:20:09.613
We realised,
"Is this a gap in the market?"

01:20:10.333 --> 01:20:12.573
And that's how we started doing watches.

01:20:12.653 --> 01:20:16.413
The market was two million units
that time.

01:20:16.493 --> 01:20:17.853
Maybe two million in a year.

01:20:18.573 --> 01:20:19.893
Nobody was doing watches.

01:20:19.973 --> 01:20:22.733
We started,
then it picked up in three, four years.

01:20:22.813 --> 01:20:24.053
And COVID, it picked up.

01:20:25.173 --> 01:20:26.693
So I think there was a tipping point of--

01:20:26.773 --> 01:20:28.293
So, watch was the tipping point?

01:20:28.373 --> 01:20:29.893
Watch was the tipping point for us.

01:20:29.973 --> 01:20:33.133
Because you were able
to buy refurbished for cheaper and--

01:20:33.213 --> 01:20:35.613
No, no, no.
We bought refurbished for ourselves.

01:20:35.693 --> 01:20:37.933
But then we realised
that there is a market which exists.

01:20:38.013 --> 01:20:43.453
"Can we do in our brand where we could do
a 5,000, 8,000 rupees watch,

01:20:43.533 --> 01:20:45.813
which is affordable
to a mid-level consumer?"

01:20:45.893 --> 01:20:48.653
Good part, Gaurav was 25 that time.

01:20:48.733 --> 01:20:50.053
So he had that young taste.

01:20:50.133 --> 01:20:51.733
He never wanted to buy cheap.

01:20:51.813 --> 01:20:53.733
And he never wanted to buy
the most expensive one.

01:20:53.813 --> 01:20:55.533
And all India market
was Chinese knockoffs.

01:20:56.773 --> 01:20:58.093
So that was the desire to build.

01:20:58.173 --> 01:21:01.173
Can we use something for ourselves
and gift it to friends, family?

01:21:01.893 --> 01:21:04.053
And today you are more known for earbuds?

01:21:04.133 --> 01:21:05.533
No, no. We are not known for...

01:21:05.613 --> 01:21:06.933
We are less known for earbuds.

01:21:07.013 --> 01:21:10.213
We are dominant share for watches.

01:21:10.293 --> 01:21:11.813
Watches is more tough category.

01:21:11.893 --> 01:21:13.293
How much is your share now?

01:21:13.373 --> 01:21:16.653
We would be north of 25%
for last three, four years.

01:21:16.733 --> 01:21:17.893
So watches are more complicated.

01:21:17.973 --> 01:21:19.013
How big is the market?

01:21:20.213 --> 01:21:24.813
-Close to a billion dollar market revenue.
-Wow.

01:21:24.893 --> 01:21:27.493
So how much are you selling now, Noise,
in terms of revenues?

01:21:28.093 --> 01:21:33.653
We would be... Watches we would have
close to 10, 14% of the revenue share.

01:21:33.733 --> 01:21:35.573
[Nikhil] So about 100, 140 million?

01:21:36.093 --> 01:21:38.253
[Amit] Close to 100 million of revenue.

01:21:38.333 --> 01:21:40.693
[Nikhil] And the rest of the products
in Noise?

01:21:40.773 --> 01:21:42.093
Are audio devices.

01:21:42.173 --> 01:21:45.053
So as of now, we were very clear
that we have limited capital.

01:21:45.133 --> 01:21:47.013
We bootstrapped the business.

01:21:47.093 --> 01:21:49.533
So we couldn't go very widthwise.
We never had the--

01:21:49.613 --> 01:21:50.613
Have you raised money now?

01:21:50.693 --> 01:21:53.373
Last year,
we raised a strategic investment

01:21:53.453 --> 01:21:54.453
from Bose Corporation.

01:21:55.533 --> 01:21:58.253
And now how big is the business,
revenue-wise?

01:21:58.333 --> 01:22:04.213
We would be somewhere sitting...
150, 200 million, that kind of revenue.

01:22:04.293 --> 01:22:08.093
Hundred in watches
and fifty to two hundred in others.

01:22:08.173 --> 01:22:11.133
And we were very clear,
we'll go deeper in the category

01:22:11.213 --> 01:22:14.413
because we never had capital
to experiment multiple ways.

01:22:14.493 --> 01:22:16.333
Crazy, huh? Super impressive.

01:22:17.053 --> 01:22:20.173
To have been able to bootstrap
to that scale, right?

01:22:20.253 --> 01:22:23.093
I didn't know that.
I thought you guys had raised the venture.

01:22:23.173 --> 01:22:26.733
No, we didn't.
I think it became a blessing for us

01:22:26.813 --> 01:22:31.573
because, first, we never had to dress up
our company for any external benefit.

01:22:31.653 --> 01:22:34.573
Like today,
sometimes investors says chase GMV,

01:22:34.653 --> 01:22:38.413
second day they say chase market share,
and sometimes profit.

01:22:38.493 --> 01:22:42.093
So we were in that luxury
of taking our decisions,

01:22:42.173 --> 01:22:43.693
which were right for the business
in long run.

01:22:44.573 --> 01:22:49.133
So having less set of people,
having less products,

01:22:49.213 --> 01:22:51.733
go deeper in the categories
where you are in.

01:22:51.813 --> 01:22:53.573
-Nikhil, this is what the difference is.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

01:22:53.653 --> 01:22:55.253
These are the real businesses,

01:22:55.333 --> 01:22:59.053
because, see, if you see all old,
you know, businesses,

01:22:59.133 --> 01:23:02.053
they were all coming
from their own capital

01:23:02.133 --> 01:23:04.533
or having access only to the banks,
you know,

01:23:04.613 --> 01:23:06.773
and taking the debt from the banks
and doing those things.

01:23:06.853 --> 01:23:10.093
It was not, like,
raising an insane amount of capital

01:23:10.173 --> 01:23:12.453
and say, "Okay, you go
and experiment with somebody else."

01:23:12.533 --> 01:23:14.173
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.
-Right?

01:23:14.253 --> 01:23:15.853
So...

01:23:15.933 --> 01:23:18.293
-I think, yeah, these are the examples.
-No, no, crazy impressive.

01:23:18.373 --> 01:23:20.373
I like pushing people
to see how they defend themselves.

01:23:20.453 --> 01:23:21.493
Yeah. [chuckles]

01:23:21.573 --> 01:23:23.253
I'm trying to figure out how to push Amit.

01:23:23.333 --> 01:23:24.413
-Yeah.
-Okay, so...

01:23:26.213 --> 01:23:27.213
what is today for?

01:23:28.013 --> 01:23:32.253
Today is for any young Indian boy or girl,
under the age of 25,

01:23:32.333 --> 01:23:35.493
who wants to start
a consumer electronic brand.

01:23:36.133 --> 01:23:39.533
It could be cell phone,
it could be TV, it could be speaker,

01:23:39.613 --> 01:23:41.893
it could be earphone,
it could be smartwatch.

01:23:42.773 --> 01:23:47.813
We want to, like, plot a road map
of what they need to look at,

01:23:47.893 --> 01:23:52.213
how to identify the opportunity,
which vendor to go to,

01:23:52.293 --> 01:23:55.493
how to test the product,
and how to finally take it to market.

01:23:55.573 --> 01:23:58.373
We'll go into
do you sell on quick commerce,

01:23:58.453 --> 01:24:02.533
do you sell on Amazon,
do you sell through physical distribution?

01:24:02.613 --> 01:24:06.213
So the first thing we thought we might do
is establish market size.

01:24:07.613 --> 01:24:12.493
How big is the consumer electronic market,

01:24:12.573 --> 01:24:16.253
A, in the world, B, in India?

01:24:16.333 --> 01:24:18.973
How fast is it growing there,
and how fast is it growing here?

01:24:19.053 --> 01:24:20.133
Should I start with smartphones?

01:24:20.213 --> 01:24:21.453
Yeah.

01:24:21.533 --> 01:24:25.253
Smartphones globally
is about 1.2 billion units every year.

01:24:25.333 --> 01:24:31.293
In India it's 120 to 140 million annually,
depending on what number you look at.

01:24:32.293 --> 01:24:37.013
So if you assume that the ASP is $300,
then 1.2 billion,

01:24:37.093 --> 01:24:40.413
that's over $300 billion,
just on the hardware side.

01:24:40.493 --> 01:24:41.813
ASP is...

01:24:41.893 --> 01:24:43.293
-Average selling price.
-Average selling price.

01:24:43.373 --> 01:24:45.693
Very different in India
compared to the rest of the world?

01:24:45.773 --> 01:24:50.653
Yeah. Every country is different
depending on the market dynamics.

01:24:50.733 --> 01:24:52.293
-Per capita as well.
-Yeah.

01:24:52.373 --> 01:24:53.573
Where is the sweet spot?

01:24:53.653 --> 01:24:57.213
If I want to start making
a cell phone today,

01:24:57.293 --> 01:24:58.293
where would I price it?

01:25:00.453 --> 01:25:02.133
Personally, I don't think
there is any more opportunity.

01:25:02.213 --> 01:25:04.253
Oh, man, I wouldn't recommend
any of my friends

01:25:04.333 --> 01:25:06.653
to go into this business right now.

01:25:06.733 --> 01:25:09.733
The market is very, very tough
to compete in.

01:25:09.813 --> 01:25:13.013
But you need to understand
that what exactly,

01:25:13.093 --> 01:25:15.453
if you want to make that,
what exactly are you trying to solve?

01:25:15.533 --> 01:25:17.853
Are you trying to, let's say,
make a luxury brand,

01:25:18.933 --> 01:25:21.053
or are you going to make a mass brand?

01:25:21.693 --> 01:25:25.173
Basis is that you need to figure out
your TAM.

01:25:26.253 --> 01:25:29.413
That what is the market
I'm going to address.

01:25:29.493 --> 01:25:31.693
And basis is that you can define,
"Okay, this is that, you know,"

01:25:31.773 --> 01:25:32.773
then you can find the sweet spot.

01:25:32.853 --> 01:25:35.973
Because otherwise the category is like,

01:25:36.053 --> 01:25:40.213
if you see mobile phones,
iPhone is $1,000.

01:25:41.373 --> 01:25:42.853
And then your, you know,

01:25:43.573 --> 01:25:45.813
the average selling price,
as he said, is right,

01:25:45.893 --> 01:25:50.453
between, you know, $250 to $300 in India.

01:25:50.533 --> 01:25:54.013
So maybe let me break it
for India market perspective

01:25:54.093 --> 01:25:56.693
so that at least viewers
could understand it well.

01:25:56.773 --> 01:25:59.093
In a category like truly wireless,
for an example,

01:25:59.173 --> 01:26:01.653
the India market
would be like 60 million units.

01:26:01.733 --> 01:26:02.733
In a category like?

01:26:02.813 --> 01:26:04.573
Audio devices, for an example, like this.

01:26:04.653 --> 01:26:06.773
This market
would be like 60 million devices,

01:26:06.853 --> 01:26:07.853
which is six crores.

01:26:07.933 --> 01:26:08.933
Yeah.

01:26:09.813 --> 01:26:12.053
-And 90% of this--
-And value-wise?

01:26:12.693 --> 01:26:15.333
Around a billion dollar market value.

01:26:16.493 --> 01:26:20.173
Can you just tell me
for India specifically?

01:26:20.253 --> 01:26:21.533
Yeah. Yeah.

01:26:21.613 --> 01:26:25.373
How much is smartphone, how much is TV,
how much is earphone, how much is watch?

01:26:26.093 --> 01:26:30.173
So, like this...

01:26:30.253 --> 01:26:32.053
Phones would be
about $150 million, phones?

01:26:32.133 --> 01:26:34.133
One-fifty million devices in India,
am I right?

01:26:34.213 --> 01:26:35.453
One-fifty million smartphones,

01:26:35.533 --> 01:26:38.493
and let's say still there are like around
50, 60 million feature phones.

01:26:38.573 --> 01:26:39.573
Feature phones.

01:26:39.653 --> 01:26:41.973
So on a broad level,
India has a penetration

01:26:42.053 --> 01:26:45.413
of 600 million smartphone users
in the country.

01:26:45.493 --> 01:26:46.773
That's the right base to look at it.

01:26:47.853 --> 01:26:49.933
Sixty crore people use smartphones,
is that right?

01:26:51.053 --> 01:26:52.573
-More or less.
-Yeah. More or less.

01:26:52.653 --> 01:26:55.773
I think you gotta look at the annual,
like, 120, 140 number.

01:26:55.853 --> 01:26:57.573
[Nikhil] They broadly say that 72 billion

01:26:57.653 --> 01:27:00.333
is the consumer electronic market
in India.

01:27:01.413 --> 01:27:02.973
-[Carl] How much?
-Seventy-two billion.

01:27:04.053 --> 01:27:05.053
Per year.

01:27:05.853 --> 01:27:07.373
Total consumer electronics?

01:27:09.853 --> 01:27:10.853
USD or INR?

01:27:10.933 --> 01:27:12.533
No, billion dollar he is talking about.

01:27:12.613 --> 01:27:18.253
In that they say cell phones,
smart plus feature is 50 billion.

01:27:19.013 --> 01:27:21.813
Very true. I think large market
would be smartphones only.

01:27:23.173 --> 01:27:24.173
-[Nikhil] Right?
-[Carl] Yeah.

01:27:24.813 --> 01:27:27.253
So in all the consumer electronics
in India,

01:27:27.333 --> 01:27:29.133
because you make TVs and everything else,

01:27:29.213 --> 01:27:32.013
and you make earphones
and watch and all that,

01:27:32.093 --> 01:27:34.253
where is the opportunity?

01:27:34.333 --> 01:27:37.053
For me, say I am a 20-year-old kid

01:27:37.773 --> 01:27:39.773
who has managed to raise some money
from somewhere,

01:27:39.853 --> 01:27:41.613
and I want to compete in this space.

01:27:41.693 --> 01:27:43.613
Where is the opportunity?

01:27:44.613 --> 01:27:47.653
Tell me anything,
tell me wired earphone, tell me...

01:27:47.733 --> 01:27:52.293
No, so first of all,
I think anybody who wanna enter a space,

01:27:52.373 --> 01:27:55.573
first of all, everybody should enter
to a space which is growing

01:27:55.653 --> 01:27:56.693
and has a larger time.

01:27:56.773 --> 01:27:58.173
There is no point to enter to a space

01:27:58.253 --> 01:28:00.813
which doesn't grow
or doesn't have a future.

01:28:00.893 --> 01:28:02.973
For an example,
it's not large enough because--

01:28:03.053 --> 01:28:04.973
You are saying first you make a box of--

01:28:05.053 --> 01:28:08.573
I mean, if the segment is big and growing,
then it's a point to go

01:28:08.653 --> 01:28:11.493
because if you're a 2% player also,
you will be a sizable company.

01:28:11.573 --> 01:28:15.053
Let's say if you go in a market
which is 1,000 crore overall revenue,

01:28:15.133 --> 01:28:17.413
you become 5% also,
you would be a 50 crore company.

01:28:17.493 --> 01:28:18.933
-It doesn't make sense.
-Which one is growing?

01:28:19.773 --> 01:28:20.973
The fastest.

01:28:21.053 --> 01:28:22.773
No, so, okay, in our space,

01:28:22.853 --> 01:28:25.533
let me take you through top-down,
you might understand.

01:28:25.613 --> 01:28:26.613
Let's say in this case,

01:28:26.693 --> 01:28:29.573
this is a 60 million-odd devices
we sell in a year,

01:28:29.653 --> 01:28:31.013
which is six crores.

01:28:31.093 --> 01:28:35.213
And interestingly,
90% devices get sold below $25,

01:28:35.293 --> 01:28:36.933
which is sub 2,000 rupees.

01:28:37.013 --> 01:28:38.573
You're talking about Bluetooth earphones?

01:28:38.653 --> 01:28:40.093
Bluetooth earphones.

01:28:40.173 --> 01:28:43.133
And that is 60% of the market revenue.

01:28:43.213 --> 01:28:49.573
Which is what 5,000 crore is like,
this market.

01:28:50.253 --> 01:28:54.493
And $25 to $75, which is medium segment,
entry-mid premium,

01:28:55.093 --> 01:28:57.333
that is close to 7%...

01:28:58.493 --> 01:29:00.533
and would be 15% of the market.

01:29:01.373 --> 01:29:04.813
And then it is all $150 plus,

01:29:04.893 --> 01:29:08.133
majority Apple,
1% market share, and then...

01:29:09.013 --> 01:29:10.493
[Nikhil] So are you saying
it's a good market?

01:29:10.573 --> 01:29:12.933
If I want to start,
say I have raised one million dollars.

01:29:13.573 --> 01:29:15.893
Should I start a earphone, earpod company?

01:29:15.973 --> 01:29:18.773
So I personally think technology works
in a very different way.

01:29:18.853 --> 01:29:19.933
It's not like fashion,

01:29:20.013 --> 01:29:25.013
where you just create a product
and sell it at any price point.

01:29:25.973 --> 01:29:29.053
Technology you need an access to partners
we were talking about,

01:29:29.133 --> 01:29:31.413
a lot of proprietary things.

01:29:31.493 --> 01:29:33.973
So I think it's a very tough space
for somebody to enter.

01:29:34.053 --> 01:29:37.453
Yes, somebody want to enter into sub $20,
yes, they can.

01:29:37.533 --> 01:29:38.893
But that's the race to bottom.

01:29:38.973 --> 01:29:43.373
And 20 to 50, which is a sweet spot,
like a 1,000 or 1,500 crore market,

01:29:43.453 --> 01:29:45.733
it's tough,
and bigger brands are sitting there.

01:29:45.813 --> 01:29:48.453
And when you say partner,
everybody's partner is China?

01:29:48.533 --> 01:29:49.973
No, no, it's not about those partners.

01:29:50.053 --> 01:29:51.453
We have partners.

01:29:51.533 --> 01:29:55.613
So one is partners
who are giving us chipsets,

01:29:55.693 --> 01:29:58.493
but then you need to have
your own app teams,

01:29:58.573 --> 01:30:01.333
you need to have your own algorithms
we were talking about.

01:30:02.053 --> 01:30:03.893
So those expertise is also needed.

01:30:03.973 --> 01:30:06.133
-Mainly supply chain.
-Supply chain. Yeah.

01:30:06.213 --> 01:30:09.773
For us, we have US partners,
Chinese partners, Japanese, Korean.

01:30:11.173 --> 01:30:12.813
Yes, it's very international.

01:30:12.893 --> 01:30:16.973
So how do I... Say I have an idea
to start an earpod company,

01:30:17.693 --> 01:30:19.653
how do I connect with these partners?

01:30:21.533 --> 01:30:23.573
I'm a newbie, I have no track record.

01:30:23.653 --> 01:30:25.093
You have not worked in this industry?

01:30:25.173 --> 01:30:27.773
-I've not worked in this industry.
-Completely coming from outside?

01:30:27.853 --> 01:30:29.533
I personally think, Nikhil,

01:30:29.613 --> 01:30:33.773
it's really tough until and unless
you're getting to a segment

01:30:33.853 --> 01:30:36.733
which is fairly new
and not being cracked by all of us.

01:30:36.813 --> 01:30:38.573
I mean, a niche space.

01:30:38.653 --> 01:30:40.493
But, see,
you guys started recently, right?

01:30:40.573 --> 01:30:42.213
-You started--
-I'll give you one example.

01:30:42.293 --> 01:30:44.253
So I did OnePlus,

01:30:44.333 --> 01:30:46.053
so I'm relatively known
in the industry, right?

01:30:46.133 --> 01:30:47.493
In the electronics industry.

01:30:48.893 --> 01:30:52.413
And when we started this new company,
Nothing, we wanted to make phones.

01:30:53.133 --> 01:30:54.533
Nobody wanted to make phones for us.

01:30:55.133 --> 01:30:57.333
They said,
"Hey, look at the past ten years.

01:30:57.413 --> 01:31:00.573
So many startups have come and failed,
and why are you different?

01:31:00.653 --> 01:31:02.493
You raise money. They also raise money.

01:31:02.573 --> 01:31:04.533
You have experience.
They also have experience.

01:31:05.213 --> 01:31:06.533
We're not gonna make a phone for you.

01:31:06.613 --> 01:31:08.133
Like, go away."

01:31:08.213 --> 01:31:10.933
And then we're like,
"Okay, we can't make a phone.

01:31:11.573 --> 01:31:13.653
Maybe we can make earbuds first
to prove ourselves,

01:31:13.733 --> 01:31:15.213
to prove the skills of our team."

01:31:15.853 --> 01:31:19.333
We go to the earbud factories,
and they also tell us to go away.

01:31:20.173 --> 01:31:24.613
They're like, "Hey, just go on Amazon.
There's 2,000, 3,000 earbuds brands.

01:31:25.253 --> 01:31:27.173
Who are you? What's your differentiation?

01:31:27.253 --> 01:31:29.653
What's your strategy?
How much money have you raised?

01:31:30.933 --> 01:31:32.613
Go away."

01:31:32.693 --> 01:31:34.333
We were shocked.

01:31:34.413 --> 01:31:37.653
We thought we had some reputation
in the industry

01:31:37.733 --> 01:31:40.253
that some of the factories
wanna work with us.

01:31:40.333 --> 01:31:42.213
So what changed? How did you do it?

01:31:42.973 --> 01:31:44.853
We went to the worst factory.

01:31:45.693 --> 01:31:49.613
Like, the factory,
if they didn't take us on as a client,

01:31:49.693 --> 01:31:50.893
they would go out of business immediately.

01:31:50.973 --> 01:31:51.973
In China?

01:31:52.053 --> 01:31:53.813
In China,
because they were on the blacklist

01:31:53.893 --> 01:31:55.733
of a lot of other people
for quality issues.

01:31:55.813 --> 01:31:57.213
And how did you find this factory?

01:31:59.493 --> 01:32:01.813
One of my co-founders, I think he...

01:32:02.933 --> 01:32:04.893
yeah, he knew some of the salespeople
in the supply chain

01:32:04.973 --> 01:32:06.013
and found this factory.

01:32:06.733 --> 01:32:11.333
But this was a factory
that had been put on the blacklist

01:32:12.333 --> 01:32:13.773
'cause of quality issues.

01:32:13.853 --> 01:32:15.093
But we had no other choice.

01:32:15.173 --> 01:32:16.773
Nobody wanted to work for us.

01:32:16.853 --> 01:32:17.853
That's where we started.

01:32:17.933 --> 01:32:18.933
That's true for all of us.

01:32:19.013 --> 01:32:22.533
We had to start work with factories
which were less known.

01:32:22.613 --> 01:32:23.613
People don't want to work

01:32:23.693 --> 01:32:25.573
because bigger factories
don't want to touch you also.

01:32:25.653 --> 01:32:29.413
They are saying we are happy
making Apple, Boses of the universe,

01:32:29.493 --> 01:32:31.013
and we don't want to--

01:32:31.093 --> 01:32:33.533
But how do, I as a 20-year-old,
find this factory?

01:32:33.613 --> 01:32:34.693
Like, you had somebody.

01:32:34.773 --> 01:32:36.893
I think you can't. Like, they won't--

01:32:36.973 --> 01:32:39.173
What if I just go to China
and look for them?

01:32:39.253 --> 01:32:43.493
There is no reason for them to engage.
Like...

01:32:43.573 --> 01:32:45.053
Nikhil, these are the large businesses,

01:32:45.133 --> 01:32:48.373
for example,
if you see the size in terms of value,

01:32:48.453 --> 01:32:50.373
automobile and mobile phone
will be similar.

01:32:50.453 --> 01:32:52.613
-In terms of value.
-Very right.

01:32:52.693 --> 01:32:55.053
So if I reach out to one of you guys,

01:32:55.133 --> 01:32:59.533
if I happen to know you,
and ask that you connect me to a factory,

01:32:59.613 --> 01:33:01.053
is that the way to do it?

01:33:01.133 --> 01:33:03.413
If we connect also to the factories,

01:33:03.493 --> 01:33:05.653
factories has no motivation
to work with you

01:33:05.733 --> 01:33:10.453
because everybody works with MOQ,
certain processes.

01:33:10.533 --> 01:33:14.013
-[Carl] Yeah.
-They find you working with...

01:33:14.093 --> 01:33:15.773
I would need to pitch who you are.

01:33:15.853 --> 01:33:17.573
I will go to this founder of the factory.

01:33:17.653 --> 01:33:20.573
"Hey, I have a friend
who wants to talk to you.

01:33:20.653 --> 01:33:23.293
This is this person's background
and credentials.

01:33:23.373 --> 01:33:24.853
Can I make the intro or not?"

01:33:25.893 --> 01:33:27.133
So...

01:33:27.213 --> 01:33:29.413
So I have a recent example
going on right now.

01:33:29.493 --> 01:33:34.453
So right now we have this technology
of making connected glasses.

01:33:34.533 --> 01:33:35.893
Right.

01:33:35.973 --> 01:33:38.773
Because we feel that's the future,
that's where buyers are going to move.

01:33:39.493 --> 01:33:41.853
We are trying to find out
who are the right brands

01:33:42.773 --> 01:33:44.053
who can do these glasses

01:33:45.133 --> 01:33:49.333
and established brands
in the glasses space,

01:33:49.413 --> 01:33:52.013
right now who exist,
pitching it to them that, "Hey, look--"

01:33:52.093 --> 01:33:53.253
Like Meta glasses?

01:33:53.333 --> 01:33:54.453
-Exactly same.
-[Nikhil] Right.

01:33:54.533 --> 01:33:55.533
Exactly same.

01:33:55.613 --> 01:33:59.133
Actually, with Meta, along with Meta.

01:33:59.853 --> 01:34:01.173
When you say along with Meta--

01:34:01.253 --> 01:34:05.093
Meta, the operating system,
for example, the whole AI is from Meta.

01:34:05.893 --> 01:34:09.893
So, for example, they have done
the same partnership with Luxottica,

01:34:09.973 --> 01:34:12.253
-Ray-Ban, similar.
-[Nikhil] Right. Right.

01:34:13.973 --> 01:34:15.933
Do you guys think
there is an opportunity there?

01:34:16.013 --> 01:34:17.133
The form is changing,

01:34:17.213 --> 01:34:19.653
and it moves from cell phone
to something else?

01:34:21.293 --> 01:34:25.093
No, I think, interestingly,
our industry is evolving every decade.

01:34:25.173 --> 01:34:29.453
So, like, nobody thought that Nokia
could be disrupted, for an example.

01:34:29.533 --> 01:34:33.413
So any of our devices could be disrupted,
and form factors are definitely changing.

01:34:34.213 --> 01:34:37.453
People are working aggressively
on glasses.

01:34:37.533 --> 01:34:39.773
So that is one form factor to look into.

01:34:39.853 --> 01:34:43.053
But like he said,
it's a game of people who have...

01:34:43.133 --> 01:34:45.093
For glasses,
I think all mobility is working.

01:34:45.613 --> 01:34:48.213
Entire mobile brands in the world
are working towards that.

01:34:48.293 --> 01:34:52.653
So it becomes very difficult
for a young company to still compete.

01:34:52.733 --> 01:34:53.973
Glasses, you can do.

01:34:55.053 --> 01:34:56.493
Glasses, you can do.

01:34:56.573 --> 01:34:58.173
[Amit] You got one...

01:34:59.213 --> 01:35:00.533
one gap.

01:35:00.613 --> 01:35:03.733
No, there is. Because, see,
look at the glasses industry.

01:35:04.573 --> 01:35:08.893
Last year, Meta, with Luxottica,
and these are public numbers,

01:35:08.973 --> 01:35:11.293
they sold two million glasses,
two million.

01:35:12.733 --> 01:35:16.173
And the number what is being projected
in the next four years

01:35:16.253 --> 01:35:17.253
is around 30 million.

01:35:17.333 --> 01:35:24.093
That's a CAGR of, let's say,
more than 43, 45% on an annual basis.

01:35:24.173 --> 01:35:25.173
Right?

01:35:25.253 --> 01:35:30.053
And... since we have been working on that,
so the tech is...

01:35:30.133 --> 01:35:33.453
So earlier the glasses came
with only speaker here.

01:35:33.533 --> 01:35:34.733
-Yeah, yeah.
-Right?

01:35:34.813 --> 01:35:35.893
-Old. Yeah, yeah.
-Yeah?

01:35:37.053 --> 01:35:38.533
Gen 2, there was a camera.

01:35:38.613 --> 01:35:39.613
Yeah.

01:35:41.573 --> 01:35:45.933
And let's say Gen 3
with this whole AI engine coming in there.

01:35:47.093 --> 01:35:48.853
Gen 4, you have a heads-up display.

01:35:48.933 --> 01:35:50.093
Correct.

01:35:50.173 --> 01:35:51.653
Now once you have a heads-up display,

01:35:52.413 --> 01:35:54.653
then whatever, for example,
is going on my cell phone,

01:35:54.733 --> 01:35:56.093
I have a display here.

01:35:56.173 --> 01:35:57.373
On the frame?

01:35:57.453 --> 01:35:58.533
No, no, not on the frame.

01:35:58.613 --> 01:36:00.013
It is a heads-up display
like you have in your cars.

01:36:00.093 --> 01:36:01.173
You are projecting onto a wall.

01:36:01.253 --> 01:36:03.013
No, no, not on the wall.

01:36:03.093 --> 01:36:05.453
-Just like in a car speedometer.
-Yeah, yeah.

01:36:05.533 --> 01:36:07.413
It is a heads-up display. You can see.

01:36:07.493 --> 01:36:08.493
So here I can see.

01:36:09.373 --> 01:36:13.973
So today, for example, if it is in,
let's say, black and white,

01:36:14.053 --> 01:36:15.653
tomorrow it will be all coloured.

01:36:15.733 --> 01:36:16.733
It will evolve.

01:36:17.573 --> 01:36:20.493
And then, for example,
if you are watching your Instagram Reels,

01:36:20.573 --> 01:36:22.773
you are just flicking it.

01:36:22.853 --> 01:36:24.453
Just sitting,
and then you are not taking out your phone

01:36:24.533 --> 01:36:25.573
because rest of...

01:36:25.653 --> 01:36:30.573
See, in your phone, you have a display,
you have speaker, mic, and a camera.

01:36:31.813 --> 01:36:32.893
All things are solved.

01:36:34.133 --> 01:36:36.053
Then why do you need
to take out your phone?

01:36:36.133 --> 01:36:38.493
Do you think that will be the future
of form?

01:36:38.573 --> 01:36:40.373
Cell phone will move to glasses?

01:36:40.453 --> 01:36:43.333
See, nobody can just firmly say that,
"Okay, this is..."

01:36:43.413 --> 01:36:46.413
Although, for example, Zuckerberg has said
that this is going to be.

01:36:46.493 --> 01:36:48.973
But he said the Oculus
and all of those things

01:36:49.053 --> 01:36:51.573
were the form as well for a long time,
which didn't play out, right?

01:36:51.653 --> 01:36:52.653
[Rahul] You're correct.

01:36:53.413 --> 01:36:56.613
So, as I said, see, it is nothing right,
nothing wrong.

01:36:56.693 --> 01:36:58.453
You have to go out in the market
and test it out.

01:36:58.533 --> 01:37:00.013
-Hmm.
-[Rahul] Right?

01:37:00.093 --> 01:37:04.813
But looking at the tech right now,
what exactly is it going to solve?

01:37:04.893 --> 01:37:07.293
I think I've seen
all the new glasses coming up.

01:37:07.893 --> 01:37:12.173
I seriously feel that this will be
the form factor to watch out for.

01:37:12.253 --> 01:37:13.853
-[Nikhil] Right.
-[Rahul] Yes.

01:37:13.933 --> 01:37:17.013
So if somebody new watching this
wants to get into the industry,

01:37:17.093 --> 01:37:18.413
this is the industry.

01:37:19.173 --> 01:37:22.253
-Right.
-I have a different approach.

01:37:22.333 --> 01:37:24.293
If somebody was young and watching this

01:37:24.373 --> 01:37:26.133
and wanting to get
into consumer electronics,

01:37:27.333 --> 01:37:29.733
I would urge them
to first become a content creator.

01:37:30.813 --> 01:37:31.813
Bang on!

01:37:31.893 --> 01:37:34.853
-Marketing.
-Because the barrier to entry is very low.

01:37:34.933 --> 01:37:35.933
Everybody can do it.

01:37:36.693 --> 01:37:38.613
And that is the arbitrage opportunity now.

01:37:38.693 --> 01:37:41.613
Like, the millennials
and the older people,

01:37:41.693 --> 01:37:45.173
they're gonna have a harder time to learn
the latest algorithms, latest trends.

01:37:45.253 --> 01:37:46.373
100%.

01:37:47.653 --> 01:37:51.253
If you do the content well, like MrBeast,
now you can do anything.

01:37:51.333 --> 01:37:54.133
You can make chocolates,
you can make a TV show on Amazon.

01:37:55.133 --> 01:37:58.973
When you have the traffic,
you have leverage to sell any product.

01:37:59.773 --> 01:38:02.973
Then when I do the intro to the factory,
they will, "That's MrBeast, of course."

01:38:03.773 --> 01:38:06.093
He's just some random kid,
it's impossible.

01:38:06.173 --> 01:38:10.573
But I feel there are very niche spaces
which are coming up

01:38:10.653 --> 01:38:13.893
which none of us are solving
as bigger companies.

01:38:13.973 --> 01:38:16.293
When you look at our space,
this product...

01:38:17.773 --> 01:38:19.573
hearing aids, is a decent space.

01:38:19.653 --> 01:38:25.133
But right now it's like 150,000,
1,50,000 rupees or $2,000,

01:38:25.213 --> 01:38:27.573
there is a hearing aid, it looks ugly.

01:38:28.653 --> 01:38:33.413
I see industry working in a space
which is over-the-counter hearing aids,

01:38:33.493 --> 01:38:35.973
way affordable, looking better.

01:38:36.053 --> 01:38:37.053
That is one market.

01:38:37.893 --> 01:38:39.813
And when you look at our category,
wearables,

01:38:39.893 --> 01:38:42.413
I see now penetration has happened
in wearables.

01:38:42.493 --> 01:38:44.853
Like, as parents, we have used, Rahul.

01:38:44.933 --> 01:38:47.253
Now the problem is we have aging parents.

01:38:47.333 --> 01:38:49.533
We need a device for them
which could monitor their health.

01:38:49.613 --> 01:38:54.013
And more importantly,
we live in urban cities, we have kids.

01:38:54.893 --> 01:38:58.173
And you won't believe, I get a message
from five people every day,

01:38:58.253 --> 01:38:59.613
"Do you have a kid's watch?"

01:38:59.693 --> 01:39:01.493
Because none of us
are looking at this space,

01:39:01.573 --> 01:39:03.093
the space stands at zero.

01:39:03.173 --> 01:39:05.293
You're saying for kids
and senior monitoring?

01:39:05.373 --> 01:39:07.893
I mean, we have two spaces,
because, see, first market--

01:39:07.973 --> 01:39:09.893
But can't an Apple Watch do that?

01:39:10.613 --> 01:39:13.573
Apple Watch does it,
but it's 50,000 rupees.

01:39:13.653 --> 01:39:16.733
Will India price point get solved
with 50,000 bucks?

01:39:16.813 --> 01:39:21.573
India would need a watch for a parent,
maybe at eight to ten thousand rupees.

01:39:21.653 --> 01:39:24.133
Not a 50,000, 100%.

01:39:24.213 --> 01:39:28.213
So coming up to his point of hearing aids.

01:39:29.013 --> 01:39:31.933
Again, anybody watching,
there's a space to disrupt.

01:39:32.573 --> 01:39:33.733
Because all the hearing aids, if you see,

01:39:33.813 --> 01:39:36.813
are, like, one lakh rupees,
two lakh rupees,

01:39:36.893 --> 01:39:39.093
-close to three lakh rupees.
-Two lakh rupees.

01:39:39.173 --> 01:39:41.853
I, you know,
went to buy for my dad to a doctor.

01:39:42.853 --> 01:39:46.053
It's 1.5 lakh rupees, hearing aid.

01:39:46.133 --> 01:39:47.813
And I said, "You have a better one?"

01:39:47.893 --> 01:39:49.533
He said, "Yeah, it's two lakh rupees."

01:39:49.613 --> 01:39:51.973
I said, "What is the difference?"
"Software difference."

01:39:52.053 --> 01:39:53.493
On phone.

01:39:53.573 --> 01:39:55.973
With this, we give you three more
extra features which you can unlock.

01:39:56.533 --> 01:39:58.453
-It's very uncompetitive market.
-Yeah.

01:39:58.533 --> 01:39:59.533
I said, "Why?"

01:40:00.453 --> 01:40:04.133
He said, "No, no, with these features,
you'll be able to understand

01:40:04.213 --> 01:40:06.973
if the voice is coming
from behind or front, all these things."

01:40:07.053 --> 01:40:10.373
Then I went into
why these hearing aids are expensive.

01:40:11.733 --> 01:40:13.373
Because back then,

01:40:13.453 --> 01:40:17.013
putting something in a small form factor
was expensive.

01:40:18.173 --> 01:40:19.653
Was expensive at that time.

01:40:19.733 --> 01:40:20.733
But not today.

01:40:20.813 --> 01:40:23.533
I think, no,
it's not about this also, Rahul.

01:40:23.613 --> 01:40:26.293
So cost would be cheaper for
the manufacturer who is selling it brand.

01:40:26.373 --> 01:40:29.533
But it's just about only one or two brands
doing that business,

01:40:29.613 --> 01:40:31.933
selling at maybe 80%, 90% gross margin.

01:40:32.013 --> 01:40:34.413
-There is one company I'm just forgetting.
-They have the majority market share.

01:40:34.493 --> 01:40:35.573
They have all the three big brands

01:40:35.653 --> 01:40:37.253
-in the world.
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:40:37.333 --> 01:40:38.573
-Hearing aids?
-Yeah.

01:40:38.653 --> 01:40:40.453
There is one company
who has bought out all others.

01:40:40.533 --> 01:40:41.973
Three to four big brands in the world.

01:40:42.053 --> 01:40:43.453
Is it a big market?

01:40:43.533 --> 01:40:45.013
It's a narrow, not big.

01:40:45.893 --> 01:40:48.173
-But--
-Is there another advice?

01:40:48.253 --> 01:40:49.253
Pick narrow markets

01:40:49.333 --> 01:40:51.533
where the large incumbents
are not going after?

01:40:52.533 --> 01:40:55.293
-Yes, if you're passionate about it.
-[Amit] Yeah.

01:40:55.373 --> 01:40:56.773
Passion has to keep you going.

01:40:56.853 --> 01:40:59.173
Explain, like, why would I be passionate
about hearing aids?

01:40:59.253 --> 01:41:00.253
That's what I mean.

01:41:00.333 --> 01:41:02.773
If you are not passionate
about a business you're starting,

01:41:02.853 --> 01:41:04.293
like, businesses are tough.

01:41:04.373 --> 01:41:07.133
There are some good days
and a lot of terrible days.

01:41:07.213 --> 01:41:09.293
So if you are not really in love
with what you are doing,

01:41:09.373 --> 01:41:13.133
it's hard to persevere
when it gets really difficult.

01:41:13.213 --> 01:41:14.693
But can I be passionate
about hearing aids?

01:41:14.773 --> 01:41:16.213
Some people are passionate about it.

01:41:16.293 --> 01:41:18.733
Some people are, by the way.
They are trying to solve real problems.

01:41:18.813 --> 01:41:20.453
No, we are.

01:41:20.533 --> 01:41:24.573
If somebody wants to do it, you know,
crack the code, go out of it.

01:41:25.933 --> 01:41:29.333
So, for example, you are saying
you want to introduce someone and all.

01:41:29.413 --> 01:41:31.733
I mean, we can introduce to them
all the chipset players,

01:41:31.813 --> 01:41:32.853
you know, all whatever.

01:41:32.933 --> 01:41:36.213
Because nobody is there in that space
that's available for somebody to take on.

01:41:36.293 --> 01:41:37.453
And we are ready to fund them.

01:41:38.093 --> 01:41:39.093
100%.

01:41:39.173 --> 01:41:42.173
Think I am not interviewing you guys.

01:41:42.253 --> 01:41:45.533
Think I am a 20-year-old boy
sitting in a room.

01:41:45.613 --> 01:41:48.573
I have had the great opportunity
of sitting with three of you.

01:41:48.653 --> 01:41:49.933
I have a million dollars.

01:41:50.013 --> 01:41:52.333
I want to build something
in consumer electronics.

01:41:52.413 --> 01:41:54.413
I live in Bangalore, in India.

01:41:54.973 --> 01:41:58.453
So you three have a conversation,
and I will try and learn along the way.

01:41:59.213 --> 01:42:00.573
And intervene once in a while.

01:42:00.653 --> 01:42:01.653
What else?

01:42:01.733 --> 01:42:03.893
We have already given the cards,
for example.

01:42:03.973 --> 01:42:06.573
You know, the glasses, hearing aids.

01:42:07.853 --> 01:42:09.893
-[Nikhil] What else?
-What not-- I'll be very clear.

01:42:09.973 --> 01:42:13.973
If somebody is trying to go
to a commodity market, it's no-go.

01:42:14.053 --> 01:42:15.653
It's a race to bottom.
There is no winning there.

01:42:15.733 --> 01:42:17.173
What is a commodity?

01:42:17.253 --> 01:42:18.253
I mean, let's say somebody says,

01:42:18.333 --> 01:42:20.813
"I want to do a earbud
which is 1,500 bucks."

01:42:21.693 --> 01:42:22.693
No go.

01:42:22.773 --> 01:42:23.773
How will you win?

01:42:23.853 --> 01:42:26.893
I mean, what's your right to win
when there's overcrowded market?

01:42:26.973 --> 01:42:28.653
And when large players are there.

01:42:28.733 --> 01:42:30.253
I am a content creator.
I have distribution.

01:42:30.333 --> 01:42:31.333
Let's add that.

01:42:31.413 --> 01:42:35.213
I'll tell you, content creator
also has a shelf threshold of,

01:42:35.293 --> 01:42:37.333
let's say,
whatever million followers they have.

01:42:37.413 --> 01:42:40.733
They could reach to 5,000 units,
10,000 units, not beyond that.

01:42:41.453 --> 01:42:45.653
Did somebody, a content creator,
recently sell a watch, and he sold a lot?

01:42:45.733 --> 01:42:47.093
-Yeah.
-What was his name?

01:42:47.893 --> 01:42:49.253
Shlok, nah?

01:42:49.333 --> 01:42:50.773
Anarc. Layers.

01:42:50.853 --> 01:42:51.933
-Yeah.
-Shlok.

01:42:52.013 --> 01:42:53.413
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.
-Tech Burner.

01:42:54.253 --> 01:42:56.573
So they did it, but if you look into it--

01:42:56.653 --> 01:43:02.173
What if the kid is ten times
or hundred times bigger than Tech Burner?

01:43:03.093 --> 01:43:04.093
MrBeast has done that.

01:43:04.173 --> 01:43:06.133
But I'm just saying.
Tech is very different.

01:43:06.213 --> 01:43:09.293
Tech, they failed because the product
was not up to the mark.

01:43:10.733 --> 01:43:12.173
They were new in the town.

01:43:12.253 --> 01:43:13.373
See, it's not like selling T-shirt.

01:43:13.453 --> 01:43:14.893
You can just stitch it and sell it.

01:43:14.973 --> 01:43:16.853
And there is no tech to it.

01:43:16.933 --> 01:43:20.653
A same factory makes a 300-rupees T-shirt
and a 30,000-rupees T-shirt also.

01:43:20.733 --> 01:43:21.733
Tech is not like that.

01:43:21.813 --> 01:43:24.413
But if you're outsourcing the tech,
the production,

01:43:24.493 --> 01:43:26.173
if you're going to a co-packer almost--

01:43:26.253 --> 01:43:27.813
No, it's not like this business.

01:43:29.173 --> 01:43:33.413
So, like all of us,
we choose what components to get into.

01:43:33.493 --> 01:43:36.053
That will get into it.
It's a super customised business.

01:43:36.653 --> 01:43:38.653
Some of the software layers
are being customised

01:43:38.733 --> 01:43:40.773
at our level in our teams.

01:43:40.853 --> 01:43:41.853
Some are outsourced.

01:43:41.933 --> 01:43:43.213
-Am I right, Carl?
-Yes.

01:43:43.293 --> 01:43:45.973
And then we design a product,
and then it comes out.

01:43:46.053 --> 01:43:47.493
It's like a CPU.

01:43:47.573 --> 01:43:49.053
It's just not you buy from it.

01:43:49.133 --> 01:43:54.013
You choose specific components,
run software on it, develop software.

01:43:54.093 --> 01:43:55.813
It's not that easy.
That's why companies are failing.

01:43:55.893 --> 01:44:00.493
So I had the same idea
before trying this business.

01:44:00.573 --> 01:44:02.333
There's a bunch of factories.
They all know how to make it.

01:44:02.413 --> 01:44:04.813
We just go and order and then pay them.

01:44:04.893 --> 01:44:05.933
It shows up. Done.

01:44:07.133 --> 01:44:08.973
That can't be further away from the truth.

01:44:09.973 --> 01:44:12.293
Like, these factories, sure,
they have the common models

01:44:12.373 --> 01:44:13.493
that you can buy off the shelf.

01:44:13.573 --> 01:44:15.573
-But everybody can buy those.
-[Amit] Yeah.

01:44:15.653 --> 01:44:17.093
And they don't have the best engineers.

01:44:17.173 --> 01:44:19.533
Like, the best engineers,
they're not gonna work for a factory.

01:44:19.613 --> 01:44:22.253
They're gonna work for Apple
or Samsung or, like, a brand, right?

01:44:22.333 --> 01:44:23.973
So they don't have good engineering.

01:44:24.053 --> 01:44:26.133
So what is happening in China,
and what is happening at Apple?

01:44:26.213 --> 01:44:28.333
Explain the engineering process.

01:44:28.413 --> 01:44:30.933
We just were discussing
when we went on a break.

01:44:31.013 --> 01:44:32.013
About the camera.

01:44:32.093 --> 01:44:33.093
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

01:44:33.173 --> 01:44:34.733
Yeah, camera is a great example.

01:44:35.733 --> 01:44:38.253
Like, if you wanna create...

01:44:39.093 --> 01:44:40.653
There are so many fields
within these products, right?

01:44:40.733 --> 01:44:43.133
There is a radio antenna,
there is industrial design,

01:44:43.213 --> 01:44:44.813
there is camera, there is software.

01:44:44.893 --> 01:44:46.213
It's like so many different things.

01:44:46.293 --> 01:44:50.453
Everything requires a lot of investment
and time and energy to do it well.

01:44:50.533 --> 01:44:53.493
So I think maybe taking a step back.

01:44:53.573 --> 01:44:55.813
One piece of advice
is to really also respect

01:44:56.773 --> 01:44:58.053
whatever new thing you're doing.

01:44:58.653 --> 01:45:00.813
Like, "Okay, now we are making earbuds.

01:45:00.893 --> 01:45:03.893
Let's learn about how to make earbuds,
how everything works.

01:45:03.973 --> 01:45:07.493
Well, now we're doing camera tuning.
Let's really learn about how that works."

01:45:07.573 --> 01:45:10.693
So we just have a very simplistic view
and outsource it to other people.

01:45:11.333 --> 01:45:14.893
If we don't even know
what the underlying principles are,

01:45:14.973 --> 01:45:16.173
it's gonna be very bad.

01:45:16.253 --> 01:45:20.413
So just for camera,
we've been struggling with camera.

01:45:21.133 --> 01:45:22.573
This year, it got a lot better.

01:45:23.973 --> 01:45:25.693
It's not that we are not smart enough.

01:45:25.773 --> 01:45:29.093
But the camera
is a very hardcore resource investment.

01:45:29.693 --> 01:45:32.733
The way it works is you make the phone
recognise the scene.

01:45:32.813 --> 01:45:34.653
The scene could be
two people sitting here.

01:45:34.733 --> 01:45:36.973
It could be nighttime. It could be city.

01:45:37.053 --> 01:45:38.293
Fruits.

01:45:38.373 --> 01:45:42.013
Fruits. The more scenes you can define,
the better your pictures will be.

01:45:42.093 --> 01:45:45.813
The more you can define,
then each scene will have its own tuning.

01:45:46.373 --> 01:45:48.213
The team will tune it differently
depending on the scene

01:45:48.293 --> 01:45:51.333
to make it as beautiful as possible
for this specific scene.

01:45:52.053 --> 01:45:54.933
So if I have a big team,
I can define a lot of different scenes.

01:45:55.653 --> 01:45:57.933
So then there's a very high likelihood

01:45:58.013 --> 01:46:00.773
that the phone will tune it
in a way that's nice.

01:46:00.853 --> 01:46:03.933
If I have a small team,
I can only define a few scenes.

01:46:04.013 --> 01:46:05.093
So if I only have a few scenes,

01:46:05.173 --> 01:46:08.813
then I'll miss a lot of the long-tail
potential use cases for the camera.

01:46:09.333 --> 01:46:10.733
And customers are not gonna be happy.

01:46:10.813 --> 01:46:15.133
Yeah, I think identifying gaps,
and as I said,

01:46:15.213 --> 01:46:17.293
you know, in terms of passion,
you were saying.

01:46:17.373 --> 01:46:19.893
So still so many categories are there.

01:46:19.973 --> 01:46:21.213
Example.

01:46:21.293 --> 01:46:22.733
Let's take example of Dyson.

01:46:22.813 --> 01:46:23.813
Can you disrupt?

01:46:23.893 --> 01:46:25.173
Bang on.

01:46:25.253 --> 01:46:27.653
So if you look at India as a market,
there is no Dyson.

01:46:27.733 --> 01:46:29.973
It's just Dyson,
which is like 40,000 bucks,

01:46:30.053 --> 01:46:31.133
and there is Bajaj to buy.

01:46:31.213 --> 01:46:33.453
No. So there is a company
called SharkNinja.

01:46:34.293 --> 01:46:35.373
The number one in USA.

01:46:36.133 --> 01:46:37.693
-[Amit] There.
-Disrupted as in completely.

01:46:37.773 --> 01:46:40.573
By Dyson, do you mean vacuum cleaner,
hair blower--

01:46:40.653 --> 01:46:42.453
Home. Home. Home.

01:46:42.533 --> 01:46:45.013
You see, if you look at it,
there is no young brand in home.

01:46:45.093 --> 01:46:46.093
Look at the customer.

01:46:47.093 --> 01:46:49.453
Our parents grew up buying Bajaj.

01:46:49.533 --> 01:46:52.293
We aspire to buy Dyson,
but Dyson is too expensive.

01:46:52.373 --> 01:46:56.173
So look at that 25 to 35 age group,
what they would buy.

01:46:56.253 --> 01:46:58.773
So, for example,
if I have to use an analogy,

01:46:58.853 --> 01:47:02.173
-if Dyson is the Mercedes-Benz...
-[Amit] Yeah. No, Toyota is there.

01:47:02.253 --> 01:47:05.653
Yeah, a Toyota, a Honda, or a Hyundai.

01:47:05.733 --> 01:47:06.733
We have Maruti.

01:47:07.613 --> 01:47:09.413
So Maruti is Bajaj?

01:47:09.493 --> 01:47:11.013
I mean, those kind of companies, yeah.

01:47:12.293 --> 01:47:14.133
So, you know, these are the segments.

01:47:14.213 --> 01:47:18.893
So you have to really identify those gaps
and say, "Yes. Is there a market?"

01:47:19.853 --> 01:47:21.693
And I think, go for it.

01:47:21.773 --> 01:47:24.333
And if you have a passion and all,
you will figure out a way,

01:47:24.413 --> 01:47:25.933
you know, find out the right people.

01:47:26.733 --> 01:47:28.733
Maybe take a step-by-step approach.

01:47:28.813 --> 01:47:32.293
Instead of starting your own company,
work for somebody else,

01:47:32.373 --> 01:47:33.853
-like me.
-Learn it.

01:47:36.013 --> 01:47:40.813
If there are so many mistakes you can make
in our industry,

01:47:40.893 --> 01:47:42.733
if I did not do it, like, once before,

01:47:43.413 --> 01:47:46.053
the chances of failure
would have been way higher.

01:47:46.133 --> 01:47:49.173
It's, like, eight to nine months
of a cycle when you're committed.

01:47:49.253 --> 01:47:50.253
And when you're committed,

01:47:50.333 --> 01:47:52.093
you are committed
with few million dollars.

01:47:52.173 --> 01:47:53.413
You cannot get out.

01:47:55.013 --> 01:47:58.973
Carl, you have said the easiest way
to differentiate is design.

01:48:00.333 --> 01:48:01.333
In a bunch of interviews.

01:48:02.253 --> 01:48:07.453
Can't I look at the same devices,
but relook design altogether?

01:48:07.533 --> 01:48:08.933
And do what design?

01:48:09.013 --> 01:48:12.133
Like, relook
my design philosophy altogether.

01:48:12.213 --> 01:48:14.333
Why do earbuds have to look like this?

01:48:14.413 --> 01:48:16.693
What if I change
the form factor completely?

01:48:16.773 --> 01:48:18.773
Then there is PMF risk.

01:48:18.853 --> 01:48:20.133
What is PMF risk?

01:48:20.213 --> 01:48:22.053
Product-market fit risk.

01:48:22.813 --> 01:48:26.013
So if you look at our products,
that product and this product,

01:48:27.053 --> 01:48:30.053
design is different,
but actually there is very low PMF risk

01:48:30.133 --> 01:48:34.613
because these are products
that consumers already know how to use,

01:48:34.693 --> 01:48:35.693
what to use it for.

01:48:36.213 --> 01:48:37.973
They already buy a lot of them
every single year.

01:48:38.653 --> 01:48:41.773
If you deviate too much
from the current product definition,

01:48:41.853 --> 01:48:45.213
then you have to take care of the risk.

01:48:45.293 --> 01:48:49.053
And then it's a question
of whether the risk versus the reward

01:48:49.133 --> 01:48:50.373
could potentially be worth it.

01:48:50.453 --> 01:48:52.053
But there's no way to test it?

01:48:52.813 --> 01:48:55.413
You can test it, you can do a mock-up,

01:48:55.493 --> 01:48:59.973
you can even use AI to generate a picture
and then go and speak to people.

01:49:00.053 --> 01:49:04.373
But I think besides mock-up,
it is all about functionality, usage,

01:49:04.453 --> 01:49:05.933
so that also plays a bigger role.

01:49:06.013 --> 01:49:10.213
So I think we don't want to change
people behaviours the way they are doing.

01:49:10.293 --> 01:49:11.293
Little changes--

01:49:11.373 --> 01:49:12.973
It is a different business strategy.

01:49:13.053 --> 01:49:15.973
I think we're
in the fast follower strategy

01:49:16.053 --> 01:49:17.213
or late mover strategy.

01:49:17.293 --> 01:49:18.293
Explain.

01:49:19.213 --> 01:49:23.773
So we're coming into an industry
that already got created by other people,

01:49:23.853 --> 01:49:27.253
and we're just trying to carve out
our space within a big industry,

01:49:27.333 --> 01:49:30.733
a billion-units-a-year industry
that was created by other people.

01:49:30.813 --> 01:49:32.973
So then we do not take the risk.

01:49:33.613 --> 01:49:36.093
We come into a very mature category,

01:49:36.173 --> 01:49:37.773
and then we can differentiate
through design.

01:49:38.733 --> 01:49:42.453
But if you're creating something new,
like, back in the day, drones were new,

01:49:42.533 --> 01:49:45.093
or now electric vehicles are new,
or robotics,

01:49:46.013 --> 01:49:48.293
then you do not have to differentiate
on the product

01:49:48.373 --> 01:49:51.813
because the technology is fresh enough
as a differentiator.

01:49:51.893 --> 01:49:57.173
But then you have the execution risk
on the technology and also the PMF risk

01:49:57.253 --> 01:50:00.893
on whether consumers will wanna adopt
this product or not.

01:50:01.773 --> 01:50:06.093
I personally think late mover
is easier for me.

01:50:06.733 --> 01:50:10.893
That requires a different way of thinking,
more survival-focused,

01:50:10.973 --> 01:50:13.333
more capability-building,
more long-term thinking.

01:50:14.133 --> 01:50:18.013
Whereas the technology approach
is more like, you have one shot.

01:50:18.093 --> 01:50:19.093
If it works, it works.

01:50:19.173 --> 01:50:21.893
If it does not work,
you gotta start over again.

01:50:24.893 --> 01:50:26.853
-So just asking Carl on...
-[Nikhil] Yeah, yeah.

01:50:26.933 --> 01:50:29.613
So, Carl, on the phones, for example,

01:50:29.693 --> 01:50:33.213
where do you think...
some disruption can happen?

01:50:34.533 --> 01:50:37.453
I think the disruption can happen
on the OS side.

01:50:37.533 --> 01:50:41.573
I think the hardware side is very hard
to differentiate on

01:50:41.653 --> 01:50:44.853
because all these suppliers that we have,

01:50:44.933 --> 01:50:47.733
they're all very concentrated,
and they're very strong,

01:50:47.813 --> 01:50:50.573
and they're investing
in their product road map,

01:50:50.653 --> 01:50:54.413
upgrading their batteries and processors
incrementally every year.

01:50:54.493 --> 01:50:56.573
Like, we cannot really differentiate.

01:50:57.413 --> 01:50:59.333
And as a supplier,
you wanna sell to everybody, right?

01:51:00.253 --> 01:51:05.173
But if the form factors are changing now,
foldable phones are coming in,

01:51:05.253 --> 01:51:09.773
don't you think if we can bring the cost
by innovation of the foldable phones down,

01:51:10.533 --> 01:51:11.613
it will have a mass adoption?

01:51:11.693 --> 01:51:14.653
Because relatively,
it's a game-changing thing

01:51:14.733 --> 01:51:17.413
because from a single screen,
you're going to a bigger screen.

01:51:18.053 --> 01:51:19.373
-Yeah.
-Or maybe a triple screen.

01:51:19.453 --> 01:51:21.253
That's also not up to us, right?

01:51:21.333 --> 01:51:23.253
'Cause the screen manufacturer

01:51:23.333 --> 01:51:26.693
is the real decision maker
for that product.

01:51:27.213 --> 01:51:28.653
It's not us.

01:51:28.733 --> 01:51:31.733
Also, just to add onto it,
the screen manufacturer is also booked,

01:51:31.813 --> 01:51:34.933
and he also wants to take advantage of it
because he knows after three years,

01:51:35.013 --> 01:51:37.493
there's gonna be the same price
as a normal screen.

01:51:37.573 --> 01:51:39.053
So he will also not reduce the price.

01:51:39.133 --> 01:51:42.573
And you wanna go with the biggest vendor
instead of a startup like us.

01:51:42.653 --> 01:51:43.933
So I think for us,

01:51:44.013 --> 01:51:47.133
our biggest opportunity to differentiate
in our next phase

01:51:47.813 --> 01:51:49.813
-is through the OS.
-OS.

01:51:50.893 --> 01:51:53.493
I think the next differentiation
for all of us

01:51:53.573 --> 01:51:55.253
would be through software only.

01:51:55.893 --> 01:52:00.133
But aren't you using one of two softwares
which are in the market

01:52:00.213 --> 01:52:03.093
and operating your devices on that?

01:52:03.173 --> 01:52:04.933
[Amit] So we...

01:52:05.013 --> 01:52:07.133
So phones is a different universe.

01:52:07.213 --> 01:52:09.573
They're Android or iOS.

01:52:09.653 --> 01:52:13.653
But in our case,
we work on open RTOS operating system,

01:52:13.733 --> 01:52:17.613
where we build our operating system there.

01:52:17.693 --> 01:52:19.653
-Right.
-And what I mean is,

01:52:19.733 --> 01:52:21.533
more softwares would come in like,

01:52:22.173 --> 01:52:25.013
"Could I fine-tune my audio

01:52:25.613 --> 01:52:27.653
based on my hearing capabilities
of my ear?"

01:52:27.733 --> 01:52:29.973
Like, Apple is doing it now.
It's pure software.

01:52:30.853 --> 01:52:34.813
"Or could I have AI capabilities in this
so that I could interact it?"

01:52:34.893 --> 01:52:37.733
A lot of companies are working
on a friend kind of a concept.

01:52:37.813 --> 01:52:39.453
So it's all software,
what I see is happening.

01:52:39.533 --> 01:52:41.373
And the same is gonna happen on the...

01:52:42.413 --> 01:52:43.773
Today we're based on Android,

01:52:43.853 --> 01:52:48.493
but I see some disruption opportunities
to become the next Android.

01:52:48.573 --> 01:52:49.573
Like?

01:52:50.253 --> 01:52:52.813
I think there's a couple of trends, right?

01:52:54.973 --> 01:52:56.253
The one trend is...

01:52:57.773 --> 01:53:01.373
if you look at the current big OSes,
iOS and Android,

01:53:01.453 --> 01:53:03.213
they're very successful already.

01:53:03.293 --> 01:53:05.693
Android has three billion-plus users.

01:53:05.773 --> 01:53:07.453
iOS has one billion-plus users.

01:53:08.133 --> 01:53:09.933
So they can't really
change the product that much.

01:53:10.013 --> 01:53:13.013
If you change the product,
a lot of people are gonna be confused.

01:53:13.093 --> 01:53:14.453
They have too many users.

01:53:14.533 --> 01:53:15.693
And it's very profitable.

01:53:15.773 --> 01:53:18.053
They're making a lot of money
on the software and the services.

01:53:18.733 --> 01:53:21.053
I don't know the number for India,
but in the US,

01:53:21.133 --> 01:53:23.813
Apple makes $100 per year
on each iPhone user,

01:53:23.893 --> 01:53:26.213
just on non-hardware stuff.

01:53:26.293 --> 01:53:27.293
It's a very high margin.

01:53:29.413 --> 01:53:31.853
It's very profitable. Very big.

01:53:31.933 --> 01:53:34.373
Now the disruption moment is with GenAI

01:53:34.453 --> 01:53:36.293
-and large language models.
-[Amit] Correct.

01:53:36.373 --> 01:53:38.293
If you look at the recent news
around Apple,

01:53:38.373 --> 01:53:41.173
they announced Apple Intelligence at WWDC.

01:53:42.173 --> 01:53:45.573
And still today, almost a year later,

01:53:45.653 --> 01:53:47.053
-there's nothing...
-Still the same.

01:53:47.133 --> 01:53:48.653
...nothing there to use.

01:53:48.733 --> 01:53:50.133
Now they are reshuffling
their management team.

01:53:50.213 --> 01:53:53.013
And this is like four years after ChatGPT.

01:53:54.093 --> 01:53:58.093
It took a long time to implement this.

01:53:58.173 --> 01:54:01.253
So I think, one,
they're too big and too successful.

01:54:02.053 --> 01:54:04.413
So then the question is, like,
how do you disrupt?

01:54:04.493 --> 01:54:06.653
Like, what is their biggest moat?

01:54:07.573 --> 01:54:09.133
I think, at least for smartphones,

01:54:09.213 --> 01:54:12.133
their biggest moat
is their developer ecosystem, right?

01:54:12.213 --> 01:54:18.053
If today we launch our own OS
based on Android or a fork of Android,

01:54:19.133 --> 01:54:22.053
we don't have any apps on the phone,
no app store, no apps,

01:54:22.853 --> 01:54:24.613
nobody is gonna buy the product.

01:54:24.693 --> 01:54:26.173
Like, I wanna use my apps.

01:54:27.453 --> 01:54:28.653
But again, if you look at AI,

01:54:28.733 --> 01:54:30.613
there's a disruption moment
for app development

01:54:30.693 --> 01:54:33.853
because now with AI coding tools,

01:54:33.933 --> 01:54:37.653
you just need to write what app you want,
and then it shows up.

01:54:38.293 --> 01:54:40.693
In the future, you can just speak
what app you want into the phone,

01:54:40.773 --> 01:54:41.933
and that app shows up.

01:54:42.013 --> 01:54:44.453
So then that gives
a smaller company like us

01:54:44.533 --> 01:54:47.253
the ability to compete with iOS,

01:54:47.333 --> 01:54:49.653
which has, I don't know,
a million, two million apps already.

01:54:50.293 --> 01:54:54.053
But we can empower every normal person
to also be an app developer.

01:54:54.133 --> 01:54:57.013
If you have an idea,
you just speak your idea into the product.

01:54:57.573 --> 01:55:03.493
Therefore, we can also quickly develop
our ecosystem of developers and apps.

01:55:03.573 --> 01:55:06.413
So I think that's the main opportunity
that I see,

01:55:06.493 --> 01:55:13.133
that a younger, more nimble company
can navigate a changing world way quicker.

01:55:13.213 --> 01:55:17.933
And the big moment that's enabling
all of this is the advancements in AI.

01:55:18.653 --> 01:55:22.653
How else can AI present opportunities

01:55:22.733 --> 01:55:28.013
if I were to want to build something
in consumer electronics as a 25-year-old?

01:55:28.093 --> 01:55:31.813
It's kind of like the personal computer.

01:55:31.893 --> 01:55:37.733
The example of it enables you
to manifest your creativity into reality.

01:55:38.493 --> 01:55:43.133
The personal computer allows you to go
to Photoshop, GarageBand, iMovie.

01:55:43.893 --> 01:55:46.573
Now, creating stuff is easier than ever.

01:55:46.653 --> 01:55:47.933
Like, we talked about creating apps.

01:55:48.773 --> 01:55:50.853
You can create graphics,
create advertising,

01:55:50.933 --> 01:55:54.053
create content,
create product design, code.

01:55:54.853 --> 01:56:00.053
It's really, in one way, lowering the bar
to creativity being manifested.

01:56:00.133 --> 01:56:01.533
[Rahul] I think that is one segment
which will...

01:56:01.613 --> 01:56:05.453
Again, a great idea,
you know, for all the youngsters.

01:56:05.533 --> 01:56:09.093
For AI, in terms of training the models,
you know,

01:56:09.173 --> 01:56:12.293
we all see that you will need
these many GPUs,

01:56:12.373 --> 01:56:14.533
you know, hundreds of GPUs,
thousands of GPUs,

01:56:14.613 --> 01:56:15.653
to train all your models and all.

01:56:15.733 --> 01:56:18.573
I think all those things,
you know, will change.

01:56:20.053 --> 01:56:22.213
There will be a time
where you will be able to train

01:56:22.293 --> 01:56:24.813
the largest of the models
using one single server.

01:56:24.893 --> 01:56:27.013
You will not need a farm of servers.

01:56:27.813 --> 01:56:31.693
We have seen a trailer
in form of DeepSeek already.

01:56:32.493 --> 01:56:35.973
And I think very soon we'll...

01:56:36.053 --> 01:56:40.973
What, you know, it implies
is that how it is going to change.

01:56:41.053 --> 01:56:45.413
This means that the access to technology
will be massified.

01:56:46.733 --> 01:56:49.853
Right now, it is with only a few people
who are working on these LLMs.

01:56:49.933 --> 01:56:52.493
For example, running 405 billion tokens,

01:56:52.573 --> 01:56:55.973
or now the new model
is 788 billion tokens,

01:56:56.613 --> 01:56:58.453
which only big server farms can do.

01:56:59.213 --> 01:57:02.973
But, once there is a technology

01:57:03.053 --> 01:57:05.133
wherein within a single server
you'll be able to--

01:57:05.213 --> 01:57:06.773
You can run your models.

01:57:07.893 --> 01:57:12.893
I think, then all the youngsters,
and they are way more creative,

01:57:12.973 --> 01:57:15.493
they will be able to come up with,
for example, an operating system.

01:57:15.573 --> 01:57:19.213
They can just come up with an OS
and then...

01:57:19.293 --> 01:57:20.493
and figure it out.

01:57:20.573 --> 01:57:24.333
Maybe then find a MrBeast and say,
"Okay, hey, I have this."

01:57:24.413 --> 01:57:26.413
And then, so...

01:57:26.493 --> 01:57:30.813
But, there will be numerous opportunities
coming out of that once it is massified.

01:57:30.893 --> 01:57:33.333
One trend that I see in the market

01:57:33.413 --> 01:57:39.293
is the youth of today does not want to buy
from the corporations of yesterday.

01:57:39.373 --> 01:57:45.133
I feel like things like Louis Vuitton,
Gucci are not cool today

01:57:45.213 --> 01:57:47.173
like they might have been ten years ago.

01:57:47.253 --> 01:57:51.573
Everybody wants streetwear,
the new independent brand--

01:57:51.653 --> 01:57:53.333
Look at how you are dressed, for example.

01:57:54.773 --> 01:57:56.093
Do you think there is a play there?

01:57:56.173 --> 01:58:00.253
If I start a consumer electronic company

01:58:00.333 --> 01:58:07.173
where I will use the narrative
of not a corporation?

01:58:08.173 --> 01:58:09.933
[Carl] I think there is an opportunity,

01:58:10.013 --> 01:58:13.613
but I think you would first need to start
in a different category.

01:58:13.693 --> 01:58:16.413
Like, make a fashion brand,
make that successful.

01:58:16.493 --> 01:58:17.933
Then you have the credibility

01:58:18.013 --> 01:58:20.893
to go to the consumer
electronics suppliers

01:58:20.973 --> 01:58:22.853
to get them to want to work with you.

01:58:22.933 --> 01:58:24.733
'Cause they have seen so many...

01:58:24.813 --> 01:58:27.253
These guys have seen so many failures
and so many pitches.

01:58:27.333 --> 01:58:29.693
They are very pragmatic.

01:58:29.773 --> 01:58:31.133
That is an interesting idea.

01:58:31.213 --> 01:58:33.213
So, you are saying

01:58:33.293 --> 01:58:38.733
start an independent design-themed brand,

01:58:38.813 --> 01:58:41.933
start elsewhere,
succeed and then transition into this?

01:58:42.013 --> 01:58:43.453
You have to have volume.

01:58:43.533 --> 01:58:46.253
That is the core of the consumer
electronics industry.

01:58:46.333 --> 01:58:48.413
To be able to work with these suppliers

01:58:48.493 --> 01:58:51.573
you need to show the numbers
that they can believe in.

01:58:51.653 --> 01:58:53.493
So, look at our case.

01:58:53.573 --> 01:58:57.173
We did not come from electronics
or consumer electronics background.

01:58:57.253 --> 01:59:01.493
So, in my wildest dream
I could have never thought of

01:59:01.573 --> 01:59:05.413
working in a space which is led by
mobility brands or other brands.

01:59:05.493 --> 01:59:07.893
So, we started with mobile accessories.

01:59:07.973 --> 01:59:10.133
It's like...
I still say it is a T-shirt business.

01:59:10.213 --> 01:59:11.773
It is just simple cases.

01:59:11.853 --> 01:59:14.893
You just print designs
and designs are a character.

01:59:14.973 --> 01:59:18.173
And we started understanding the user,
consumer pattern,

01:59:18.253 --> 01:59:20.613
and knowing and started building volumes.

01:59:20.693 --> 01:59:23.293
Our partners saw a confidence in us, like,

01:59:23.373 --> 01:59:26.453
"They are doing good volumes.
We could test something with them."

01:59:26.533 --> 01:59:29.013
So, maybe our entry also
was not on day one here.

01:59:29.093 --> 01:59:31.653
We learnt consumer from a basic business.

01:59:33.693 --> 01:59:35.973
But, by the way,
I have a very fundamental question

01:59:36.053 --> 01:59:39.053
which I have realised as a founder.

01:59:39.133 --> 01:59:41.853
What is the segment of the market
you want to chase?

01:59:42.853 --> 01:59:44.973
Like, what customer you want to...

01:59:45.053 --> 01:59:46.653
I am asking you that question.

01:59:46.733 --> 01:59:48.413
I don't have data like you have.

01:59:48.493 --> 01:59:52.813
No, it is not about what I want.

01:59:52.893 --> 01:59:54.293
It is about what you want to build.

01:59:54.373 --> 01:59:56.213
I'll tell you for an example,
the game what he is doing.

01:59:56.293 --> 01:59:58.373
He is saying,
I'll not fight the cheapest in the market,

01:59:58.453 --> 02:00:00.533
like, he is not doing the Xiaomi play.

02:00:01.293 --> 02:00:02.373
But what he is doing,

02:00:02.453 --> 02:00:05.293
he is in the mid segment,
which is super painful,

02:00:06.333 --> 02:00:07.333
which needs time.

02:00:07.933 --> 02:00:11.453
His gestation would be...
Success will not be short term.

02:00:11.533 --> 02:00:15.133
He would have a patience of
three-to-four-year capital to build it.

02:00:15.213 --> 02:00:16.573
And then he--

02:00:16.653 --> 02:00:19.093
There are chances he might see
and might not see success.

02:00:19.173 --> 02:00:23.013
So, as founders or whosoever,
young people want to start,

02:00:23.093 --> 02:00:26.373
they need to be very clear
what segment they are trying to build.

02:00:26.453 --> 02:00:28.653
Because different segment--
When you talk about design--

02:00:28.733 --> 02:00:30.653
What, if I come to you with a blank slate,

02:00:30.733 --> 02:00:32.413
what segment
would you recommend I build in?

02:00:32.493 --> 02:00:35.573
No, if you ask me,
I would say don't go for the mass.

02:00:35.653 --> 02:00:38.213
Mass is important,
but have some brand aspiration,

02:00:38.293 --> 02:00:40.973
have your identity,
have your brand uniqueness.

02:00:41.053 --> 02:00:43.813
No point to fight for a commodity,
that's a race to bottom.

02:00:43.893 --> 02:00:46.093
You sell for $20,

02:00:46.173 --> 02:00:49.253
somebody else will sell for 15, 12, 11.

02:00:49.333 --> 02:00:50.853
Have your own community,

02:00:50.933 --> 02:00:53.293
one narrow cohort of users
who you are selling,

02:00:53.373 --> 02:00:56.253
and that community should be
your evangelist there.

02:00:57.213 --> 02:01:01.293
And that always happens at
somewhere little above, not to the basics.

02:01:01.373 --> 02:01:03.493
You are not solving basics
of anyone right now.

02:01:03.573 --> 02:01:05.453
How does India build the supply chain?

02:01:05.533 --> 02:01:06.933
Great.

02:01:07.813 --> 02:01:08.973
So, it's a process.

02:01:10.013 --> 02:01:13.733
So, the process is that
you start with initially...

02:01:13.813 --> 02:01:15.013
to start with EMS.

02:01:15.093 --> 02:01:16.253
EMS is?

02:01:16.333 --> 02:01:21.613
EMS is the electronic manufacturing
services that you start the EMS process.

02:01:22.413 --> 02:01:27.133
Then you start getting the design
out there in country.

02:01:28.133 --> 02:01:32.573
Then after design, you start working on
the supply chain, the component ecosystem.

02:01:33.493 --> 02:01:37.693
Right? So, this is...
This all is a process one-by-one.

02:01:37.773 --> 02:01:41.373
If I am 25 and I want to start
a component company,

02:01:42.133 --> 02:01:45.213
I've raised a little bit of money,
put up a factory.

02:01:45.893 --> 02:01:48.093
How will I ever compete
with somebody in China

02:01:48.173 --> 02:01:50.133
who's manufacturing millions of units?

02:01:50.213 --> 02:01:52.093
So, you can do that.

02:01:52.173 --> 02:01:54.973
So, there is so much of material
which goes inside.

02:01:55.053 --> 02:02:00.253
For example, a glue on a glue machine,
on SMT, it's a glue.

02:02:00.933 --> 02:02:01.973
That glue--

02:02:02.053 --> 02:02:03.573
So, I just found out that that glue,

02:02:03.653 --> 02:02:05.693
the particular glue
is still coming from China.

02:02:05.773 --> 02:02:08.133
We can-- Why can't we make that here?

02:02:08.213 --> 02:02:11.533
And I studied, I said why the chemical
companies can make that glue out there.

02:02:11.613 --> 02:02:12.613
You can do that.

02:02:13.493 --> 02:02:14.493
Probably there is--

02:02:14.573 --> 02:02:18.053
Maybe somebody has to find out
and get into that.

02:02:19.773 --> 02:02:21.733
I know someone, you know, who said, "Okay,

02:02:21.813 --> 02:02:24.653
after finishing my engineering,
what should I do and all?"

02:02:24.733 --> 02:02:28.253
And then went on search
that what India is importing a lot

02:02:28.333 --> 02:02:30.333
and he found out
all the coin's material...

02:02:31.973 --> 02:02:35.493
Right? For the coins, currency coins,
the material, we still import.

02:02:35.573 --> 02:02:38.013
He started making that,
he started supplying that.

02:02:38.093 --> 02:02:39.173
So, you just...

02:02:39.253 --> 02:02:40.653
Is that an opportunity for me?

02:02:40.733 --> 02:02:45.253
I think US will, in the tariff world,
not buy from China like they once did.

02:02:45.333 --> 02:02:47.013
Components is a huge opportunity.

02:02:47.093 --> 02:02:51.493
So, for example, now India is projecting
a market of 500 billion dollars by 2030.

02:02:51.573 --> 02:02:52.733
It's a huge market.

02:02:53.533 --> 02:02:55.253
60% of that is components.

02:02:55.333 --> 02:02:59.453
And we are also incentivised to use
the locally manufactured components.

02:02:59.533 --> 02:03:00.853
If manufacturing is coming here,

02:03:00.933 --> 02:03:03.733
100% components will come here,
like batteries...

02:03:03.813 --> 02:03:05.653
-That's an opportunity, too.
-100%.

02:03:05.733 --> 02:03:08.173
Like, I want to make money,
I'm 25, in this industry.

02:03:08.253 --> 02:03:09.733
-Component is part of--
-EMS is a...

02:03:09.813 --> 02:03:13.173
I think next ten years is EMS. So...

02:03:13.253 --> 02:03:14.813
And the component PLI scheme is coming.

02:03:14.893 --> 02:03:17.413
Maybe by the time this podcast is out,
the scheme will be announced.

02:03:17.493 --> 02:03:18.933
How do I go about starting that?

02:03:19.013 --> 02:03:22.213
Let's say an EMS company,
an EMS manufacturer.

02:03:22.293 --> 02:03:26.093
Great. So, take a mobile phone,
get into each and every component.

02:03:26.173 --> 02:03:27.773
There are so many. There are--

02:03:27.853 --> 02:03:30.933
So, in a mobile phone, there are,
let's say, 700-800 components.

02:03:31.013 --> 02:03:32.613
Maybe in his phone, maybe it will be more.

02:03:32.693 --> 02:03:34.773
iPhone will be way more, right?

02:03:34.853 --> 02:03:35.853
Get into that.

02:03:35.933 --> 02:03:38.333
How do I find that out?
Like, I want to know...

02:03:39.653 --> 02:03:41.573
I'm assuming US, China
are going to hate each other

02:03:41.653 --> 02:03:42.653
for some time more.

02:03:43.813 --> 02:03:45.533
Apple phones are made in the US.

02:03:45.613 --> 02:03:49.853
They can't buy that particular product
that they have been, from China anymore.

02:03:50.533 --> 02:03:54.253
How do I figure out what that component is
and then how to build it?

02:03:54.333 --> 02:03:56.213
Just tear it down.

02:03:56.293 --> 02:03:58.133
Nikhil, these days,
it is actually simpler.

02:03:58.213 --> 02:03:59.453
You know, you go on ChatGPT.

02:04:00.493 --> 02:04:01.933
There are so many sites on the Internet

02:04:02.013 --> 02:04:03.733
where you could just see
tear down of every phone.

02:04:03.813 --> 02:04:05.733
Tear down, you can find out
what are the components

02:04:05.813 --> 02:04:07.933
and then you find out, okay,
how many components are there in India.

02:04:08.013 --> 02:04:11.573
Go on the export list, import list
that what all are getting in the country.

02:04:12.333 --> 02:04:14.333
Right? What is the volume? What is the--

02:04:14.413 --> 02:04:16.693
These days, you can get access
to all the customs data easily.

02:04:16.773 --> 02:04:17.773
[Amit] Yeah.

02:04:17.853 --> 02:04:20.613
So, huge opportunity.

02:04:20.693 --> 02:04:24.453
You should also work at EMS to get some...
industry knowledge.

02:04:24.533 --> 02:04:26.413
-Experience. Yeah.
-[Carl] Experience.

02:04:26.493 --> 02:04:28.533
There is somebody working with him
for a year.

02:04:28.613 --> 02:04:31.213
He would know everything
where this opportunity lies.

02:04:32.013 --> 02:04:33.973
How big is the incentive
for someone like Carl?

02:04:34.053 --> 02:04:35.893
Say, you are selling Nothing phones
in India.

02:04:36.453 --> 02:04:38.533
You source from me in Bangalore

02:04:38.613 --> 02:04:41.413
versus a Chinese component manufacturer.

02:04:42.173 --> 02:04:46.973
Is the incentive enough
to warrant the change in price?

02:04:48.093 --> 02:04:51.733
So, right now, we have to pay
duties on components

02:04:51.813 --> 02:04:54.213
that are sourced
from other countries like China.

02:04:54.293 --> 02:04:55.573
So the more we can source locally,

02:04:55.653 --> 02:04:58.453
the more we can lower
the prices of our product

02:04:58.533 --> 02:05:00.533
to then be more competitive on the market.

02:05:00.613 --> 02:05:02.453
So, we are very incentivised.

02:05:02.533 --> 02:05:04.653
And if we are able to tap into PLI,

02:05:04.733 --> 02:05:06.293
and I think the PLI regulation

02:05:06.373 --> 02:05:11.413
will also be more and more requiring
of the brands to source locally.

02:05:12.093 --> 02:05:14.453
And they will raise the bar
every single year.

02:05:16.333 --> 02:05:18.733
We are very incentivised
to source locally.

02:05:18.813 --> 02:05:22.453
As a business, we just need to make
the best decision for our shareholders.

02:05:22.533 --> 02:05:26.173
So, till now you have told me,
go to ChatGPT, figure out...

02:05:26.253 --> 02:05:27.933
No, no, just...

02:05:28.013 --> 02:05:31.133
Just as I said, these days,
there are a lot of avenues

02:05:31.213 --> 02:05:34.213
where you can go and find out
multiple sort of information.

02:05:34.293 --> 02:05:36.173
Right. So, I figure out one component

02:05:36.253 --> 02:05:38.893
which is going into
US cell phone manufacturer

02:05:38.973 --> 02:05:40.213
which is coming from China.

02:05:41.133 --> 02:05:46.013
And then I go about figuring if that
raw material is available in India.

02:05:46.093 --> 02:05:48.053
I identify that there is.

02:05:48.133 --> 02:05:52.213
What do I do next
to set up a factory which makes it?

02:05:52.293 --> 02:05:54.133
Okay, let's take an example.

02:05:55.173 --> 02:05:56.453
Carl, can I use your phone?

02:06:00.533 --> 02:06:02.253
Let's say this is a USB socket.

02:06:02.333 --> 02:06:03.333
[Nikhil] Yeah.

02:06:03.413 --> 02:06:09.253
This USB socket is
the most abused component here

02:06:09.333 --> 02:06:12.053
because, let's say a million times
you are going to...

02:06:13.213 --> 02:06:15.293
Right? So, this means to say that

02:06:15.373 --> 02:06:17.133
this will require
a special sort of material.

02:06:17.773 --> 02:06:19.053
Study that material.

02:06:19.133 --> 02:06:20.533
Where that material is available?

02:06:21.333 --> 02:06:22.973
Who is manufacturing it?

02:06:23.053 --> 02:06:24.173
At what cost?

02:06:25.133 --> 02:06:29.293
And absolutely go to the root of that.

02:06:30.213 --> 02:06:31.933
And then see what are the...

02:06:33.333 --> 02:06:36.493
If you can go and visit these factories

02:06:36.573 --> 02:06:40.373
by tapping someone,
getting into a network--

02:06:40.453 --> 02:06:41.573
These factories in China?

02:06:42.373 --> 02:06:45.333
Wherever. Wherever. If possible.

02:06:45.413 --> 02:06:48.333
See, and then understand the standards.

02:06:48.413 --> 02:06:49.613
See, why this is not happening?

02:06:49.693 --> 02:06:50.853
Why I gave you a glue example?

02:06:50.933 --> 02:06:52.573
Because people said,
"No, India can't make that."

02:06:52.653 --> 02:06:53.653
Why can't we make that?

02:06:53.733 --> 02:06:55.373
We are fantastic in chemical--

02:06:55.453 --> 02:06:57.053
Our chemical industry,
our pharmaceutical industry,

02:06:57.133 --> 02:06:58.213
they are doing brilliantly well.

02:06:59.453 --> 02:07:02.093
Probably there is maybe,
there is not awareness of that,

02:07:02.173 --> 02:07:03.773
or the volumes and everything,

02:07:03.853 --> 02:07:05.853
but I think if we are going to go,

02:07:05.933 --> 02:07:09.053
let's say from 100 billion
to 500 billion dollars,

02:07:09.133 --> 02:07:10.533
it's a massive opportunity.

02:07:10.613 --> 02:07:11.613
Similarly here.

02:07:12.413 --> 02:07:13.853
What else can be done?

02:07:13.933 --> 02:07:17.333
Like, see, the outcome of this is we want,

02:07:17.413 --> 02:07:20.853
even if it's five kids who start...

02:07:22.213 --> 02:07:27.213
solving for the supply chain problem
dependency that we are talking about,

02:07:27.293 --> 02:07:31.653
if that is the go-to action that happens
because of the time we have spent today,

02:07:31.733 --> 02:07:33.933
I think we can all say today was worth it.

02:07:34.773 --> 02:07:37.053
Also, like, we spoke--

02:07:37.133 --> 02:07:38.853
And I think we will need
5,000 of those kids

02:07:38.933 --> 02:07:42.173
because it's a huge universe.

02:07:42.253 --> 02:07:43.573
And we don't have it here.

02:07:43.653 --> 02:07:45.173
We have to bring it in.

02:07:45.253 --> 02:07:46.453
[Nikhil] Yeah.

02:07:46.533 --> 02:07:48.413
And, by the way, brands like us

02:07:48.493 --> 02:07:51.533
are desperately looking for people
to do it for us.

02:07:51.613 --> 02:07:52.773
I mean, it's our need also.

02:07:52.853 --> 02:07:55.333
What is the biggest need?
Say two things that you want me--

02:07:55.413 --> 02:07:57.373
Let's say for us, for an example,

02:07:57.453 --> 02:07:59.973
in watches we do,
the largest component is the screen.

02:08:00.053 --> 02:08:02.493
The screen is like $5 or something.

02:08:02.573 --> 02:08:05.853
And if I import, there is a 15% duty,

02:08:05.933 --> 02:08:08.333
which means every screen
I am paying, what?

02:08:08.413 --> 02:08:10.493
One and a half-- Close to $1.

02:08:11.253 --> 02:08:14.253
If you say, make it in India,
it's a huge volume.

02:08:14.333 --> 02:08:16.613
It's maybe half a million,
one million screens a month.

02:08:16.693 --> 02:08:18.573
What is the margin in screen business?

02:08:19.173 --> 02:08:21.693
I'm sure if we cost arbitrage,
if you look at it,

02:08:21.773 --> 02:08:24.773
it still makes 10% or 7%.

02:08:24.853 --> 02:08:27.213
It's just one SKU,
you have to keep producing.

02:08:27.293 --> 02:08:30.293
Oh, you know the smartphone screens
from China,

02:08:31.253 --> 02:08:34.213
those companies are losing money
to sell the screens.

02:08:34.293 --> 02:08:38.573
Because they have policies that subsidise
the creation of that industry.

02:08:38.653 --> 02:08:41.693
So, at least for the smartphone screens,
it's very hard for...

02:08:41.773 --> 02:08:47.453
So you're saying our import duty has to be
higher than their subsidy, at the least?

02:08:47.533 --> 02:08:50.413
At the least, if-- Yeah. Yeah.

02:08:50.493 --> 02:08:52.053
So, one is import duty,

02:08:52.133 --> 02:08:55.133
and second, of course,
the PLI schemes coming on components

02:08:55.213 --> 02:08:57.613
will incentivise
to use more Make In India.

02:08:57.693 --> 02:08:58.973
Any advice to the government,

02:08:59.053 --> 02:09:00.813
because I'm sure
somebody will be watching.

02:09:00.893 --> 02:09:04.133
How should the PLI scheme be structured
for components?

02:09:04.213 --> 02:09:05.213
It's already structured.

02:09:05.293 --> 02:09:06.693
It's just going to be announced
in two-three days.

02:09:06.773 --> 02:09:08.613
-He would be a part of it.
-[Rahul] So...

02:09:09.773 --> 02:09:10.773
It's a good scheme.

02:09:11.413 --> 02:09:12.573
Yes, it's a good scheme.

02:09:13.853 --> 02:09:15.093
It's a good scheme.

02:09:15.973 --> 02:09:17.813
But see, the larger point here is...

02:09:19.493 --> 02:09:23.893
that you have to ensure
that locally-made products

02:09:23.973 --> 02:09:26.373
make more sense for anybody who wants to,

02:09:26.453 --> 02:09:28.533
you know, who's selling,
let's say, in India.

02:09:28.613 --> 02:09:29.973
I'm not even talking about export.

02:09:30.613 --> 02:09:35.853
If Carl wants to buy a,
let's say, a middle frame,

02:09:35.933 --> 02:09:39.853
he should be able to source it locally
and it should be cheaper for him,

02:09:39.933 --> 02:09:43.533
not because he's forced
because of a regulation.

02:09:43.613 --> 02:09:47.093
It should also make sense economically
for him to do that.

02:09:47.173 --> 02:09:49.333
And that, in today's world,
because of scale,

02:09:49.413 --> 02:09:52.973
it can only happen with custom duty
or the tariff.

02:09:54.773 --> 02:09:55.773
So, tariff-- No--

02:09:55.853 --> 02:09:57.253
-Depending on the component.
-Yes.

02:09:57.333 --> 02:09:59.173
I think plastic
should be very easy, right?

02:09:59.933 --> 02:10:01.773
-To replicate here.
-Yes.

02:10:02.293 --> 02:10:06.733
Plastic, and second, as I said,
the government incentive schemes.

02:10:06.813 --> 02:10:08.853
Because, you know,
if you see how China was built,

02:10:08.933 --> 02:10:10.933
because of
all the government schemes only.

02:10:11.933 --> 02:10:13.213
And why their exports went up

02:10:13.293 --> 02:10:15.133
because their export schemes are,
like, massive.

02:10:15.213 --> 02:10:16.653
You three continue talking.

02:10:16.733 --> 02:10:18.053
Like, I'm a 25-year-old.

02:10:18.133 --> 02:10:22.973
I'm trying to learn from three stalwarts
of our consumer electronic industry.

02:10:24.213 --> 02:10:26.613
I want to make money. End goal.

02:10:27.893 --> 02:10:29.893
The biggest moneymaker is, like...

02:10:30.653 --> 02:10:34.453
The industries with fewer competitors,
right? Like NVIDIA.

02:10:35.213 --> 02:10:37.653
If you look at the NVIDIA share price,
it's insane.

02:10:37.733 --> 02:10:38.733
Taking a huge example.

02:10:38.813 --> 02:10:42.373
But even for our industry, like,
I think the chipset makers,

02:10:42.453 --> 02:10:46.213
their margins are way higher
than the EMS factories, right?

02:10:46.293 --> 02:10:48.693
NVIDIA, I don't know, is it 40--

02:10:48.773 --> 02:10:49.973
Qualcomm is 40, 60--

02:10:50.053 --> 02:10:52.013
They're 45%, I think,
they just declared, yeah.

02:10:52.093 --> 02:10:53.293
[Carl] 45% gross margin.

02:10:53.373 --> 02:10:57.453
But Foxconn is, I think, 10%. So...

02:10:57.533 --> 02:11:00.013
Like, eventually we also have to move
upmarket, right,

02:11:00.093 --> 02:11:04.133
into, like, more and more difficult,
lower competition areas of the stack.

02:11:06.053 --> 02:11:07.893
Yes, but, Carl, again,

02:11:08.773 --> 02:11:12.973
Nikhil's point is that how do we inspire
the young generation out here

02:11:13.053 --> 02:11:14.373
to start doing something?

02:11:14.453 --> 02:11:16.013
You know, how do they spot opportunities?

02:11:16.093 --> 02:11:17.093
Yeah.

02:11:17.173 --> 02:11:22.413
So, as I said, if you tear down the phone,
what are the easiest five things,

02:11:22.493 --> 02:11:25.173
ten things you can just pick up and say,
"Hey, this I can do.

02:11:25.893 --> 02:11:29.613
That is a little-- Is not that complex."

02:11:30.373 --> 02:11:33.333
By the way, you know, he's right.

02:11:33.413 --> 02:11:37.573
You know, so making these mechanics,

02:11:37.653 --> 02:11:41.013
for example,
precision mechanics is not that easy.

02:11:41.653 --> 02:11:43.693
We still, you know, a lot of things
are getting imported,

02:11:43.773 --> 02:11:44.853
even on precision mechanics.

02:11:44.933 --> 02:11:46.213
-Yeah?
-[Rahul] Yeah.

02:11:47.413 --> 02:11:49.253
But once there are
a lot of incentives and all,

02:11:49.333 --> 02:11:53.773
we have ample people here
who can take a shot at that.

02:11:53.853 --> 02:11:58.293
I'm curious to hear, like,
how does the next Qualcomm...

02:11:59.173 --> 02:12:03.773
Like, if a kid is watching this,
like, say, 30 years later,

02:12:03.853 --> 02:12:05.733
they've created Qualcomm,
the next Qualcomm.

02:12:05.813 --> 02:12:07.933
Like, how does that path happen?

02:12:08.013 --> 02:12:13.133
So, you know, Carl, you just straight away
talking about a moonshot.

02:12:13.213 --> 02:12:16.133
But instead of a Qualcomm, one Qualcomm,

02:12:17.053 --> 02:12:21.573
I'm saying, can we make, for example,

02:12:21.653 --> 02:12:24.053
if I have to take an example
of automobile,

02:12:24.133 --> 02:12:25.253
let's say, in terms of components,

02:12:25.333 --> 02:12:29.533
can we make 300 or 500 Mindas here?

02:12:30.453 --> 02:12:31.733
Minda is a good example, you know.

02:12:32.453 --> 02:12:34.173
-Auto is all making money.
-[Rahul] Yeah.

02:12:37.733 --> 02:12:38.733
-Makes sense.
-Yeah.

02:12:38.813 --> 02:12:42.293
I think that's a very large opportunity,
knocking on our door.

02:12:42.373 --> 02:12:46.933
How much money would I need to start
a factory around, say, the USB port?

02:12:47.013 --> 02:12:48.973
I think it will be very less, right?

02:12:49.693 --> 02:12:50.693
[Amit] For USB port.

02:12:50.773 --> 02:12:52.373
It's not easy.

02:12:53.093 --> 02:12:55.293
-You would know it the best.
-[Rahul] Yeah, it's a...

02:12:57.693 --> 02:12:58.773
You know, Molly and all,

02:12:58.853 --> 02:13:02.133
they are like specialised Europeans
who are working on this.

02:13:04.333 --> 02:13:07.333
But again, it was just an example.

02:13:07.413 --> 02:13:11.613
But once you go inside, Nikhil,
as I said, you can find out...

02:13:12.653 --> 02:13:14.893
For example, inside there is a...

02:13:15.693 --> 02:13:18.653
You have battery.
On battery to dissipate the heat,

02:13:19.773 --> 02:13:21.493
you need some mechanism
to dissipate the heat.

02:13:22.533 --> 02:13:24.573
You need a graphene,
small film of graphene,

02:13:24.653 --> 02:13:26.173
which you can put,
which can dissipate the heat.

02:13:26.253 --> 02:13:27.253
You can make it here.

02:13:28.893 --> 02:13:30.333
It will go in every phone.

02:13:31.933 --> 02:13:33.413
So, I am not saying straight away
you go and target,

02:13:33.493 --> 02:13:36.293
okay, I am going to make the next
Sony camera or something like that.

02:13:36.373 --> 02:13:38.773
And the PLI scheme
will incentivise all of this?

02:13:40.413 --> 02:13:42.773
So, as of now,
they have structured it for,

02:13:42.853 --> 02:13:45.693
let's say,
components which are high in value,

02:13:45.773 --> 02:13:49.573
let's say, which cover 70% to 75%
of the mobile phone.

02:13:50.573 --> 02:13:52.293
These are all B2B businesses then.

02:13:52.373 --> 02:13:54.733
I mean, everybody has
a different inclination

02:13:54.813 --> 02:13:57.253
towards what they want to build.

02:13:57.333 --> 02:13:58.733
No, anything is fine.

02:13:58.813 --> 02:14:00.973
I just want to build something
in this space

02:14:01.053 --> 02:14:02.893
where I can actually make money.

02:14:04.133 --> 02:14:05.453
Is there financing available?

02:14:05.533 --> 02:14:12.093
Let's say, I figure out a certain product
which is under PLI that I start building.

02:14:13.533 --> 02:14:15.373
But I don't have too much initial capital.

02:14:16.133 --> 02:14:18.773
How does one go around
getting that initial funding?

02:14:19.773 --> 02:14:21.133
If I come up with a business plan

02:14:21.213 --> 02:14:23.253
and come to somebody like Rahul,
will you give it?

02:14:23.333 --> 02:14:26.413
Yes, if I see that your product works,

02:14:28.253 --> 02:14:30.853
working as per the standards, and then...

02:14:30.933 --> 02:14:32.413
Would a bank give it?

02:14:32.493 --> 02:14:34.813
I think yes.
But, of course, banks work on collaterals.

02:14:34.893 --> 02:14:35.933
I don't have collateral.

02:14:36.013 --> 02:14:37.613
There are a few banks who might,
you know...

02:14:37.693 --> 02:14:41.133
Is there some startup scheme,
some government subsidy,

02:14:41.213 --> 02:14:42.333
where I can get the initial capital?

02:14:42.413 --> 02:14:44.053
Yes, you can. There are multiple schemes.

02:14:44.133 --> 02:14:45.533
Again, yeah. Very good point.

02:14:45.613 --> 02:14:48.333
There are so many schemes
which people are not even aware of.

02:14:48.413 --> 02:14:51.133
For example, for MSME sector,

02:14:51.213 --> 02:14:54.173
you know,
from Invest India, from Startup India,

02:14:54.253 --> 02:14:57.973
there are multiple schemes going on
which people are not even aware of.

02:14:58.053 --> 02:14:59.653
I am not aware. How do I find out?

02:15:00.333 --> 02:15:02.053
You will have to make this much effort.

02:15:02.133 --> 02:15:03.733
Then you need to go after that

02:15:03.813 --> 02:15:05.413
and find out
how many schemes are available

02:15:05.493 --> 02:15:06.853
and then one by one...

02:15:06.933 --> 02:15:08.213
Which one applies to me.

02:15:08.293 --> 02:15:11.213
Yes. For example,
there is a PLI everybody knows,

02:15:11.293 --> 02:15:14.013
but there is a DLI,
which is design-led incentive

02:15:14.093 --> 02:15:15.373
for the chipsets and all.

02:15:16.373 --> 02:15:17.373
You should know that.

02:15:18.693 --> 02:15:19.773
There is a grant for that.

02:15:20.493 --> 02:15:21.613
You need to show your designs.

02:15:21.693 --> 02:15:25.293
Government, you know, they will come,
inspect and see what you are doing

02:15:25.373 --> 02:15:26.373
and then you can do that.

02:15:27.693 --> 02:15:33.493
For a right idea, you will knock on
100 doors, one door will open.

02:15:34.893 --> 02:15:37.333
But you need-- You need to knock.

02:15:38.733 --> 02:15:40.013
You just can't say, okay...

02:15:41.053 --> 02:15:43.133
As you also said,
either a bank will come up

02:15:43.213 --> 02:15:46.373
or a VC will come up
or a government scheme will come up.

02:15:46.453 --> 02:15:48.413
Something will come up for a right idea.

02:15:48.493 --> 02:15:49.893
I was reading this thing.

02:15:49.973 --> 02:15:52.573
Somebody had sent me an email
saying semiconductors,

02:15:52.653 --> 02:15:54.373
something drastic is happening in India.

02:15:55.173 --> 02:15:56.493
Is that a possibility?

02:15:57.773 --> 02:15:58.933
"Drastic" means?

02:15:59.013 --> 02:16:03.373
Like, so the backstory goes
that at one point,

02:16:03.453 --> 02:16:05.813
India was really focused
on semiconductors.

02:16:05.893 --> 02:16:08.173
There was one particular factory
which burned down.

02:16:08.973 --> 02:16:10.653
But in the last 20 years,

02:16:10.733 --> 02:16:13.133
we have been left behind
or 30 years we have been left behind,

02:16:13.213 --> 02:16:14.893
and they are restarting the effort...

02:16:16.133 --> 02:16:19.013
to manufacture
more semiconductors in India.

02:16:19.093 --> 02:16:20.413
Is that possible?

02:16:21.413 --> 02:16:23.093
With TSMC and all of that?

02:16:23.173 --> 02:16:25.013
The whole world is relying on them, right?

02:16:25.093 --> 02:16:28.173
You mean like start a new TSMC
or get TSMC to...

02:16:28.253 --> 02:16:31.413
Like both semiconductor design
and manufacturing. Can I--

02:16:31.493 --> 02:16:33.733
-So you can't create a TSMC...
-[Nikhil] Can you compete?

02:16:33.813 --> 02:16:36.893
I think it comes down to, like,
the depth of the thing, right?

02:16:36.973 --> 02:16:38.533
Like how many millimetre...

02:16:38.613 --> 02:16:40.773
So we are working in one of the companies
on semiconductors.

02:16:40.853 --> 02:16:45.213
And what you're referring is,
there was one fab in India,

02:16:45.293 --> 02:16:48.533
only one fab which was in Mohali,
government owned, long back...

02:16:48.613 --> 02:16:49.613
[Nikhil] Yes.

02:16:49.693 --> 02:16:52.293
Doing probably, you know,

02:16:54.173 --> 02:16:55.813
100 nanometres or something like that.

02:16:55.893 --> 02:16:57.733
Today TSMC is doing two nanometres.

02:16:58.613 --> 02:16:59.893
Two-three, correct.

02:16:59.973 --> 02:17:02.653
So, of course, I mean,
you can't catch up with two nanometre.

02:17:02.733 --> 02:17:05.613
Even, see, China started their
semiconductor programme 20 years back.

02:17:06.413 --> 02:17:08.213
They are still not able
to compete on that.

02:17:08.293 --> 02:17:10.693
But it is very, very important.

02:17:10.773 --> 02:17:15.573
All four of us, like, 15 years back or so,

02:17:15.653 --> 02:17:19.413
have you ever thought that
semiconductor will be more valuable

02:17:19.493 --> 02:17:20.773
or important than oil?

02:17:20.853 --> 02:17:22.853
Not even a thought came across to my mind.

02:17:23.973 --> 02:17:25.093
Back then.

02:17:25.173 --> 02:17:26.853
But if you see today, it is.

02:17:27.853 --> 02:17:31.573
And I am assuming the same thing.
I am assuming US, China continue to fight.

02:17:32.293 --> 02:17:33.853
And Taiwan becomes...

02:17:35.973 --> 02:17:37.733
I don't know,
maybe our friend in that fight

02:17:37.813 --> 02:17:39.253
or maybe not our friend.

02:17:39.333 --> 02:17:41.573
If our supply chain gets disrupted

02:17:41.653 --> 02:17:44.613
where we can't get those
2mm semiconductors,

02:17:44.693 --> 02:17:45.773
what does India do then?

02:17:46.413 --> 02:17:49.373
It is a tough question because,
you know, it is divided in multiple parts.

02:17:50.333 --> 02:17:51.573
So it is not only about two nanometres.

02:17:51.653 --> 02:17:53.853
Two nanometre is only one segment.
Then you have--

02:17:53.933 --> 02:17:55.733
So, government is saying, you start with,

02:17:55.813 --> 02:17:58.973
let's say 35 nanometres right now,
is good enough.

02:17:59.053 --> 02:18:02.853
Because you have to start coming slowly
one by one. Right?

02:18:02.933 --> 02:18:06.693
So even that, you know,
if we can start at 35,

02:18:08.373 --> 02:18:13.093
because those are larger components,
which can go into you know, other things.

02:18:13.773 --> 02:18:20.013
You know, refrigerators, TVs,
vacuums, cars and all.

02:18:20.093 --> 02:18:24.533
And then slowly, slowly you start coming
in for the ITs and the mobile phones.

02:18:25.333 --> 02:18:30.493
But at least we start attacking the,
you know, the 35, 40 nanometres,

02:18:30.573 --> 02:18:32.253
25 nanometres, start attacking that.

02:18:33.813 --> 02:18:34.893
So that is the opportunity.

02:18:34.973 --> 02:18:36.933
I mean, straight away, you know,
you can't leapfrog.

02:18:37.533 --> 02:18:40.413
As I said, China has put
billions and billions of dollars

02:18:40.493 --> 02:18:41.973
and still they are not able
to achieve that.

02:18:42.053 --> 02:18:44.773
And there are--
Again, it's a country play.

02:18:45.453 --> 02:18:47.173
A company can't build something like this.

02:18:48.533 --> 02:18:50.493
Country, you know, has to come into it.

02:18:51.253 --> 02:18:54.333
For example, to do a,

02:18:54.413 --> 02:18:56.253
let's say,
anything less than 10 nanometres,

02:18:56.333 --> 02:18:57.613
you need to have lithography.

02:18:57.693 --> 02:18:58.773
What is that?

02:18:58.853 --> 02:19:00.293
It's a machine. It's a technology.

02:19:01.213 --> 02:19:07.853
That technology is right now
with Holland, Netherlands.

02:19:07.933 --> 02:19:12.093
There is a company...
This company name is...

02:19:12.173 --> 02:19:13.213
-ASML.
-ASML.

02:19:13.293 --> 02:19:14.293
No competitors.

02:19:14.373 --> 02:19:15.773
So, ASML has those machines.

02:19:15.853 --> 02:19:17.613
You need to have access to that.

02:19:18.693 --> 02:19:21.493
In those machines, the software
actually is coming from the United States.

02:19:21.573 --> 02:19:23.493
So it's a-- It's all a--

02:19:23.573 --> 02:19:27.213
Because it's a game where you need to
work on this technology

02:19:27.293 --> 02:19:28.653
and need to stabilise the technology.

02:19:28.733 --> 02:19:30.933
So the government has to come
and play into that.

02:19:31.013 --> 02:19:34.813
So, it's way more deeper
than what we feel. Because, you know--

02:19:35.813 --> 02:19:38.693
But, you know,
semiconductor is a vast range.

02:19:38.773 --> 02:19:41.013
It's not only that, only doing a TSMC,

02:19:41.093 --> 02:19:45.093
because when we talk about semiconductors,
you know, we always talk about TSMC.

02:19:46.293 --> 02:19:47.293
Memory.

02:19:47.373 --> 02:19:49.453
Why can't India have its own memory?

02:19:49.533 --> 02:19:51.973
Can we design our own?

02:19:52.053 --> 02:19:53.893
Let's, for example, in your IT,

02:19:53.973 --> 02:19:57.533
there is Gen 4, there is Gen 5,
now there is Gen 6.

02:19:58.453 --> 02:19:59.773
Why can't India come up with,

02:19:59.853 --> 02:20:01.973
I'm talking about, let's say,
Gen 8 or Gen 9?

02:20:02.653 --> 02:20:04.253
End of the day, you have to have that.

02:20:05.973 --> 02:20:07.893
So these are all opportunities--

02:20:07.973 --> 02:20:09.813
I'll ask you a question
on top of your question only.

02:20:09.893 --> 02:20:11.413
Why is it not happening?

02:20:11.493 --> 02:20:14.133
Because in India,
we were good in services.

02:20:14.213 --> 02:20:16.413
So we were--
Our services sector was doing good.

02:20:16.493 --> 02:20:18.773
So people said, okay,
let's build on the services business.

02:20:19.613 --> 02:20:22.413
So if you see all these Gen 4, 5,

02:20:22.493 --> 02:20:25.653
half of their manpower
will be sitting in Bangalore and Hyderabad

02:20:25.733 --> 02:20:28.373
and designing for the other bigger brands

02:20:28.453 --> 02:20:31.573
who are somewhere in US
or other countries.

02:20:33.853 --> 02:20:35.373
But not for us.

02:20:35.453 --> 02:20:38.573
Because A, we were not having
those government programmes earlier.

02:20:38.653 --> 02:20:41.173
They were not, right--

02:20:41.253 --> 02:20:43.373
Not focused on creating
something like that.

02:20:44.493 --> 02:20:46.773
So, where the buck was going was,

02:20:46.853 --> 02:20:48.733
okay, services is an easy business,
let's go there.

02:20:50.733 --> 02:20:53.853
Half of the people working on those
technologies will be from India.

02:20:54.853 --> 02:20:59.213
He was talking about Qualcomm or MTK,
their biggest R&amp;D centres are in India.

02:20:59.293 --> 02:21:00.613
-Mm?
-Yes.

02:21:02.213 --> 02:21:03.733
So the focus--

02:21:03.813 --> 02:21:06.653
But now we have, you know,
with the current government,

02:21:06.733 --> 02:21:08.253
all the new schemes coming in,

02:21:10.133 --> 02:21:11.813
people are becoming more aware of that.

02:21:13.573 --> 02:21:15.573
See, today we are discussing
about semiconductors.

02:21:16.453 --> 02:21:19.693
Otherwise, if it was a consumer brand
or electronics and that,

02:21:19.773 --> 02:21:21.253
why will we be discussing
about semiconductors?

02:21:22.133 --> 02:21:24.813
Because now, all of us,
because of the policies and everything,

02:21:24.893 --> 02:21:27.133
and whatever happened,
we are more aware of that.

02:21:28.813 --> 02:21:31.693
You are doing a bunch of
very new things, right?

02:21:31.773 --> 02:21:34.173
Like with television, operating software.

02:21:34.773 --> 02:21:37.693
There is one company
that we are both part of.

02:21:38.533 --> 02:21:39.973
-Around television, as well.
-Yeah.

02:21:40.053 --> 02:21:42.453
What's happening in that world?
Would you like to tell us?

02:21:42.533 --> 02:21:44.933
No, that's more on the aggregation,

02:21:45.013 --> 02:21:47.733
because the way we consume content
is completely changing.

02:21:48.613 --> 02:21:50.373
Can you tell us your thesis around that?

02:21:51.253 --> 02:21:53.773
Thesis is that, you know,
you buy a product,

02:21:53.853 --> 02:21:56.853
and then you start getting multiple apps,

02:21:56.933 --> 02:22:00.373
and then you start paying different apps.

02:22:02.933 --> 02:22:05.573
Then your user experience is then,

02:22:05.653 --> 02:22:08.133
that whatever recommendation
one is showing something else,

02:22:08.213 --> 02:22:10.693
the other is showing us
some different recommendation,

02:22:10.773 --> 02:22:12.293
third is showing something else.

02:22:12.373 --> 02:22:16.333
Why can't I have an experience
wherein I switch on my TV,

02:22:17.013 --> 02:22:19.213
and then I don't have to go in any app?

02:22:19.293 --> 02:22:23.853
There is one user interface,
and all the apps are stitched into that.

02:22:23.933 --> 02:22:27.933
You just type in your,
let's say, username.

02:22:28.013 --> 02:22:30.413
Let's say nikhil@gmail.com,

02:22:31.093 --> 02:22:35.533
and then everything from your Netflix
to your Zee to your Sony,

02:22:36.653 --> 02:22:39.853
as per your choice and recommendation,
everything starts coming on one screen.

02:22:39.933 --> 02:22:41.093
You're not going in an app.

02:22:43.133 --> 02:22:46.573
That's one area-- Because again,
it's an evolving space.

02:22:47.933 --> 02:22:50.133
And then you bundle it
along with the hardware piece,

02:22:50.213 --> 02:22:53.213
wherein you move on a SaaS model.

02:22:53.293 --> 02:22:54.293
How do you...

02:22:55.453 --> 02:22:56.853
I'm pretty interested
in this business model,

02:22:56.933 --> 02:23:00.813
because as a content platform,
you don't want to be unbundled, right?

02:23:00.893 --> 02:23:03.213
You want your own app,
your own user experience.

02:23:03.293 --> 02:23:04.293
Yes.

02:23:04.373 --> 02:23:06.053
How do you get their stuff?

02:23:06.133 --> 02:23:10.173
Like, it's not in their incentive
to unbundle their content.

02:23:10.253 --> 02:23:12.653
Like, you're saying,
how do you get access to that content?

02:23:12.733 --> 02:23:13.733
Yeah, for instance, Netflix.

02:23:13.813 --> 02:23:16.413
If I'm Netflix, and you say,
you just want to take the content...

02:23:16.493 --> 02:23:18.373
Apart from Netflix,
you take some other example,

02:23:18.453 --> 02:23:20.213
because that's
a different animal altogether.

02:23:20.293 --> 02:23:22.213
-Hotstar.
-Let's say Hotstar, yeah.

02:23:22.813 --> 02:23:25.613
So, I have my own app,
I have my own users,

02:23:25.693 --> 02:23:26.973
I don't want to give you my content,

02:23:27.053 --> 02:23:29.493
because then I lose
my competitive advantage.

02:23:30.173 --> 02:23:32.333
Then my content becomes a commodity
on your platform.

02:23:33.333 --> 02:23:36.693
So, I mean, the platform,
the content, the platforms,

02:23:36.773 --> 02:23:39.573
they will try and hedge
against this, right?

02:23:40.613 --> 02:23:42.613
So, if there are like, say, 25 apps,

02:23:42.693 --> 02:23:45.933
which are the most widely used apps
out there,

02:23:46.013 --> 02:23:49.293
and out of 25, 90% of the apps,

02:23:49.373 --> 02:23:52.493
you're able to get inside the app

02:23:52.573 --> 02:23:56.133
and get the permission for recommendation
and everything.

02:23:57.493 --> 02:24:01.213
And then, you know,
put it on your screen for the user.

02:24:01.293 --> 02:24:03.693
I think it's acceptable.

02:24:03.773 --> 02:24:06.253
-So, for them, it's like incremental.
-Yes.

02:24:06.333 --> 02:24:08.453
If I don't work with you,
I won't make this money.

02:24:08.533 --> 02:24:09.573
Might as well make the money.

02:24:09.653 --> 02:24:11.373
-Because they also need distribution.
-Yeah.

02:24:13.013 --> 02:24:16.653
So, then you have a few big ones
that are harder to negotiate with.

02:24:16.733 --> 02:24:18.373
They will come with scale.

02:24:18.453 --> 02:24:20.733
So, once you achieve scale,
they will say, "All right."

02:24:20.813 --> 02:24:22.813
-"We also want this."
-I get it.

02:24:22.893 --> 02:24:25.693
It's a bit like
cell phone and app store, right?

02:24:25.773 --> 02:24:26.773
Yeah.

02:24:27.893 --> 02:24:30.853
So, when there's a new OS
on the cell phone,

02:24:30.933 --> 02:24:33.973
the big app makers
are not going to adopt, right?

02:24:34.053 --> 02:24:36.173
They're going to wait for the distribution
to come first.

02:24:37.413 --> 02:24:39.213
So, I think it's about that adoption.

02:24:39.293 --> 02:24:40.613
Yeah.

02:24:40.693 --> 02:24:42.693
But when you bundle,
I think it gets cheaper.

02:24:42.773 --> 02:24:43.773
Yeah.

02:24:45.093 --> 02:24:46.973
Why don't you guys speak
like I'm not in the room

02:24:47.053 --> 02:24:48.173
and there are no cameras?

02:24:49.373 --> 02:24:51.093
Yeah, isn't... We're trying to.

02:24:51.173 --> 02:24:52.173
[laughter]

02:24:52.253 --> 02:24:56.693
Carl, what opportunity exists
in the consumer market besides phones?

02:24:56.773 --> 02:24:58.373
What do I want to have exist?

02:24:58.453 --> 02:25:00.773
No. I mean,
what are the opportunities which--

02:25:00.853 --> 02:25:02.053
Oh, what opportunities exist?

02:25:02.133 --> 02:25:03.773
Not for the large players.

02:25:04.493 --> 02:25:07.493
I'm only thinking about, like,
very big categories all the time.

02:25:08.733 --> 02:25:12.133
I'm thinking about, like,
EVs and robotics stuff.

02:25:14.173 --> 02:25:15.813
But I agree, like, if you're young,

02:25:15.893 --> 02:25:18.333
you have to start with something
more simple.

02:25:19.453 --> 02:25:20.533
[Nikhil] What is China like?

02:25:20.613 --> 02:25:23.333
What else do you think we can learn
as a country from them?

02:25:25.533 --> 02:25:27.733
I don't spend a lot of time
thinking about policy.

02:25:27.813 --> 02:25:29.733
But I do think the PLI is set up...

02:25:29.813 --> 02:25:32.293
You probably know more
about PLI than me, but...

02:25:34.333 --> 02:25:38.893
We are very keen to be a part
of the next generation PLI scheme.

02:25:41.413 --> 02:25:45.373
I think if India wants to develop
its own smartphone ecosystem,

02:25:45.453 --> 02:25:48.173
starting from the factory,
EMS side is very good.

02:25:48.253 --> 02:25:49.933
That's already happening.

02:25:50.013 --> 02:25:53.973
Incentivising foreign and domestic players
to build here.

02:25:54.053 --> 02:25:55.093
It's already happening.

02:25:55.933 --> 02:25:57.533
I think to reach the next stage,

02:25:57.613 --> 02:26:00.973
it can't just be
manufacturing and exports.

02:26:01.533 --> 02:26:03.653
Because ultimately,
that's not the highest value add.

02:26:04.453 --> 02:26:07.733
The next stage will be to design
and engineer here as well.

02:26:07.813 --> 02:26:10.013
So, what is the next stage policy

02:26:10.093 --> 02:26:13.853
after the goal of PLI
has been accomplished?

02:26:13.933 --> 02:26:15.853
What is the next stage plan? I'm not sure.

02:26:15.933 --> 02:26:19.893
I'm just starting to spend more time
and learn more about this.

02:26:19.973 --> 02:26:23.213
So, I think, to your question that,
what can we do?

02:26:23.293 --> 02:26:26.573
If you see what they have done
in last 25 years,

02:26:26.653 --> 02:26:30.253
in terms of
all the government policies, so...

02:26:31.253 --> 02:26:33.813
We are discussing about incentivising,
that is one.

02:26:33.893 --> 02:26:35.573
That is one incentive.

02:26:35.653 --> 02:26:37.093
But rest of the other enablers,

02:26:37.173 --> 02:26:42.413
for example, the whole supply chain
in terms of materials and everything,

02:26:42.493 --> 02:26:44.853
they have worked
a lot deeper on that segment.

02:26:45.693 --> 02:26:46.853
In terms of logistics,

02:26:48.133 --> 02:26:50.893
they have created logistics parks
to enable that.

02:26:51.773 --> 02:26:56.493
Today, if we are talking about,
for example, now we have,

02:26:56.573 --> 02:27:00.453
let's say, iPhones going and exporting
and doing all this sort of things.

02:27:01.693 --> 02:27:07.573
The way we are expanding,
you will need two full, bigger, you know,

02:27:07.653 --> 02:27:11.893
large aircrafts every week
to ferry the product from here to Chicago.

02:27:13.893 --> 02:27:14.933
We need to have that.

02:27:15.893 --> 02:27:18.053
We need to, you know, build bigger ports,

02:27:19.173 --> 02:27:20.533
wherein you can reduce the time.

02:27:21.213 --> 02:27:24.293
Because they have taken all that measures,
not only in one segment,

02:27:24.373 --> 02:27:25.613
because we talk only about this,

02:27:25.693 --> 02:27:29.413
but every segment,
they have done with all those policies.

02:27:30.613 --> 02:27:34.973
I think consumer electronics
is a very expensive

02:27:35.653 --> 02:27:38.373
and difficult thing
for somebody without experience.

02:27:38.453 --> 02:27:41.053
-All of a sudden going--
-Experience is key, I believe.

02:27:41.133 --> 02:27:42.253
Without that you can't do.

02:27:43.173 --> 02:27:45.253
In fact, you can't do also,
I personally think.

02:27:45.333 --> 02:27:46.413
[Nikhil] You're making dessert?

02:27:47.253 --> 02:27:49.333
-Yeah--
-[Amit] Doing is expensive only.

02:27:49.413 --> 02:27:51.373
I mean, you will 100% make mistakes.

02:27:52.133 --> 02:27:55.653
I think we found a couple of themes,
you know, where people could start.

02:27:55.733 --> 02:27:58.293
Something more focused,
something more niche,

02:27:58.373 --> 02:28:00.173
lower risk, lower capex.

02:28:00.853 --> 02:28:02.613
Start from there, evolve from there.

02:28:02.693 --> 02:28:06.813
It could be on the consumer side,
with clothing or accessories.

02:28:07.373 --> 02:28:09.053
It could be on the supply chain side

02:28:09.133 --> 02:28:13.573
with parts of the stack
that are easier to make.

02:28:14.133 --> 02:28:15.893
And then just evolve from there.

02:28:15.973 --> 02:28:17.773
It could be on the distribution side

02:28:17.853 --> 02:28:21.893
with content creation
as a means of distributing information.

02:28:22.613 --> 02:28:24.493
But, Rahul, what is your thought?

02:28:24.573 --> 02:28:31.293
We have seen all brands across the globe
coming to India in consumer electronics.

02:28:31.373 --> 02:28:33.093
Hardly there are brands who have gone out.

02:28:33.173 --> 02:28:35.933
-To have gone?
-To have gone outside India.

02:28:36.013 --> 02:28:38.573
-Indian brands?
-Yeah, Indian brands.

02:28:38.653 --> 02:28:41.653
Forget Southeast Asian countries
for a while.

02:28:41.733 --> 02:28:45.533
But none of the brands have gone outside
our home turf and played a game there.

02:28:46.653 --> 02:28:50.093
Do you think world needs
some new age brands?

02:28:50.893 --> 02:28:52.693
I have solid thesis for that.

02:28:54.373 --> 02:28:57.653
So, I personally think
India as a country...

02:28:57.733 --> 02:28:59.733
I mean we all work with scarcity mindset.

02:28:59.813 --> 02:29:01.173
So, what has happened that,

02:29:01.253 --> 02:29:03.573
what a US or an European entrepreneur

02:29:03.653 --> 02:29:07.333
would try to solve a problem
by throwing a dollar.

02:29:07.413 --> 02:29:09.133
A dollar is 90 rupees for us.

02:29:09.653 --> 02:29:11.933
So, what I'm trying to say,
for us every penny counts.

02:29:12.533 --> 02:29:15.053
And for something
what they are producing for $100,

02:29:16.053 --> 02:29:17.893
a similar great quality product,

02:29:17.973 --> 02:29:24.493
Indian entrepreneur could build for,
let's say 30-40% cheaper than them.

02:29:25.333 --> 02:29:27.573
We have captive consumption.

02:29:28.933 --> 02:29:30.453
Entrepreneurs now are very smart,

02:29:30.533 --> 02:29:33.493
they are very evolved,
travelled, done across.

02:29:34.093 --> 02:29:38.013
Why can't we take that arbitrage
and take these brands to the globe?

02:29:38.733 --> 02:29:41.213
I mean, we are good at marketing
by the way, Indian entrepreneur.

02:29:41.293 --> 02:29:42.413
Software, we are good at.

02:29:43.253 --> 02:29:44.773
Hardware, we can learn from our peers.

02:29:46.573 --> 02:29:47.893
Why can't Indian brands--

02:29:47.973 --> 02:29:52.293
Why can't we build brands
who are based out of India

02:29:52.373 --> 02:29:54.173
and move to global scale?

02:29:55.133 --> 02:29:59.053
There are no brands existing everywhere,
there are old traditional brands.

02:29:59.133 --> 02:30:01.213
-It's starting now, right?
-Yeah.

02:30:01.293 --> 02:30:02.293
With you guys.

02:30:02.373 --> 02:30:04.733
[Amit] So,
that's what we are trying to do.

02:30:04.813 --> 02:30:08.013
We believe that
it is a right platform for us.

02:30:08.093 --> 02:30:10.773
We have gained decent experience

02:30:10.853 --> 02:30:14.173
and international markets
we could do justice.

02:30:14.253 --> 02:30:15.573
But I'm generally talking.

02:30:16.133 --> 02:30:18.293
We need more brands. One brand can't do.

02:30:18.373 --> 02:30:21.093
I mean, I have seen we all buying
international brands.

02:30:21.173 --> 02:30:23.773
Are you talking about-- You want me
to answer in consumer electronics?

02:30:23.853 --> 02:30:26.453
I am talking about consumer electronics,
specifically, yeah.

02:30:26.533 --> 02:30:27.973
In consumer electronics,

02:30:28.053 --> 02:30:32.693
you can go into those markets
where your products are relevant.

02:30:33.493 --> 02:30:34.973
-Bang on.
-[Rahul] Okay?

02:30:35.053 --> 02:30:38.693
So, for example, in Indian demographics,
whatever products you are making,

02:30:38.773 --> 02:30:42.453
you are going to take the same product
because you have scale and you go there.

02:30:42.533 --> 02:30:44.293
So, that's what I am saying. So, when...

02:30:45.733 --> 02:30:49.493
I mean, I want to cater to a market
which is, let's say, mid.

02:30:50.293 --> 02:30:52.173
Because I don't want a cheapest product.

02:30:52.253 --> 02:30:54.453
-Which is fine. So--
-[Amit] Indian demographic.

02:30:54.533 --> 02:30:59.213
So, those products you have taken into
those similar categories and similar...

02:31:00.053 --> 02:31:01.693
-you know, geographies.
-[Amit] Yeah.

02:31:01.773 --> 02:31:03.213
-That you can do.
-[Amit] Yeah.

02:31:03.933 --> 02:31:08.053
Southeast Asia, all other, you know,
so, for example, all the SAARC countries,

02:31:08.133 --> 02:31:10.813
then this side, Russia, Eastern Europe.

02:31:10.893 --> 02:31:12.253
These are fantastic markets.

02:31:12.333 --> 02:31:13.373
-[Amit] Yeah.
-Right?

02:31:14.133 --> 02:31:19.533
Then second, if you are saying
that you want to hit the upper deck.

02:31:19.613 --> 02:31:21.093
I am just staying middle.

02:31:21.173 --> 02:31:22.893
See, upper, I am very clear.

02:31:22.973 --> 02:31:26.293
Let Sony, Samsung play the game
what they are playing, or Apple.

02:31:26.373 --> 02:31:27.533
We don't want to touch them.

02:31:27.613 --> 02:31:29.933
The consumers are very loyal.
They have an ecosystem.

02:31:30.013 --> 02:31:33.173
They have advantages
of whatever they could, so...

02:31:33.253 --> 02:31:35.373
You already have a scale in India.

02:31:36.573 --> 02:31:39.373
And then when you are going outside,
you know, you go with that.

02:31:40.253 --> 02:31:42.493
Same scale and cater to that.

02:31:42.573 --> 02:31:45.573
Create one or two more brands.

02:31:46.733 --> 02:31:50.213
And use--
Leverage the scale what you have.

02:31:51.573 --> 02:31:53.213
And, you know,
you can attack the markets--

02:31:53.293 --> 02:31:54.973
No, that's what I am saying, we can do it.

02:31:55.053 --> 02:31:57.013
-India need those brands.
-Yes.

02:31:57.613 --> 02:32:00.373
We are just no more
about basic necessity brand,

02:32:00.453 --> 02:32:02.773
where we are just solving for features.

02:32:03.693 --> 02:32:05.853
And you'll be surprised, I'll tell you,
Rahul, where I'm coming from,

02:32:05.933 --> 02:32:09.493
When we-- We just launched in Dubai
in Virgin stores.

02:32:10.173 --> 02:32:13.133
Traditionally, Indian brands would have
gone and launched a $20 product.

02:32:13.213 --> 02:32:15.813
We launched ourselves
at $75 to $100 pricing.

02:32:16.453 --> 02:32:18.133
And we're getting a great response.

02:32:18.213 --> 02:32:20.373
I mean, look at the kind of response
people are giving

02:32:20.453 --> 02:32:22.893
for a decent-price-point products.

02:32:22.973 --> 02:32:25.213
-Again, innovation is one.
-100%.

02:32:25.293 --> 02:32:28.293
Innovation is needed.
You can't enter a commodity space.

02:32:28.373 --> 02:32:30.053
Innovation and then you can have--

02:32:30.133 --> 02:32:36.293
Create different brands for,
you know, different needs.

02:32:36.373 --> 02:32:38.133
One brand can't serve all, that's true.

02:32:38.213 --> 02:32:39.453
[Rahul] Look at...

02:32:39.533 --> 02:32:43.133
Here you have OPPO, then you have OnePlus,
then you have Realme.

02:32:43.213 --> 02:32:44.253
Under one umbrella only.

02:32:44.333 --> 02:32:45.493
-We have two brands.
-[Rahul] Yeah.

02:32:46.653 --> 02:32:48.373
He has to come up with CMF because...

02:32:48.453 --> 02:32:50.293
-We need the scale.
-Yeah.

02:32:50.373 --> 02:32:51.893
The scale, 100% is needed.

02:32:51.973 --> 02:32:55.053
I think you can build mid-market
with the scale.

02:32:55.133 --> 02:32:57.053
-Yeah.
-Otherwise, nobody gonna support you.

02:32:58.053 --> 02:32:59.053
Yeah.

02:32:59.133 --> 02:33:01.053
But I think it's--

02:33:01.133 --> 02:33:03.293
The Indian economy
has got into a point in time

02:33:03.373 --> 02:33:06.053
where there's entrepreneurs
with a skill-set to go global.

02:33:06.133 --> 02:33:10.253
And it's already the language advantage,
the language and culture advantage.

02:33:10.333 --> 02:33:12.013
-It's easier to do marketing.
-[Amit] Yeah.

02:33:12.093 --> 02:33:14.573
Right? It's easier to do US or Europe.

02:33:16.493 --> 02:33:17.973
But on the product definition side,

02:33:18.053 --> 02:33:21.573
it's easier to go to
more similar markets first.

02:33:21.653 --> 02:33:23.413
There will be more risk going into...

02:33:23.493 --> 02:33:25.533
You need product market fit,
which I am aligned.

02:33:25.613 --> 02:33:28.093
You go to-- Like, we also are going
to similar markets,

02:33:28.173 --> 02:33:29.493
which are easy acceptance.

02:33:29.573 --> 02:33:32.893
And then try to go in territory--
I respect all territories.

02:33:32.973 --> 02:33:35.373
So, I mean, let's say US,
these are all tough markets.

02:33:35.453 --> 02:33:36.973
It's easy to go and break there.

02:33:37.053 --> 02:33:41.493
So, I would like to go small there,
do little trials, fail, and then take on.

02:33:42.693 --> 02:33:45.133
Yeah. So, they are, as I said,
going to SAARC countries,

02:33:45.213 --> 02:33:49.253
going to, you know,
Russia, Eastern Europe,

02:33:49.333 --> 02:33:53.093
which are all, you know, great markets
for you to do your trials and all.

02:33:53.173 --> 02:33:54.933
And then also tweak.

02:33:55.013 --> 02:33:56.973
We should start, like, a hub.

02:33:58.493 --> 02:34:01.533
Like, start a place
where we fund young entrepreneurs

02:34:01.613 --> 02:34:03.573
to build some of the stuff we spoke about.

02:34:04.173 --> 02:34:05.173
100%

02:34:06.653 --> 02:34:10.613
Right? Like, get some land,
give them the resources.

02:34:11.573 --> 02:34:13.053
You guys all have the know-how.

02:34:14.893 --> 02:34:17.453
Like, start one place where people can--

02:34:17.533 --> 02:34:20.453
Like, an incubator of sorts,
with real estate.

02:34:20.533 --> 02:34:24.453
And it's easier to do. On...

02:34:24.533 --> 02:34:26.013
And it could be anything.

02:34:26.093 --> 02:34:27.493
You know, you can--

02:34:27.573 --> 02:34:31.013
If somebody comes up with an idea
with a diaper,

02:34:31.093 --> 02:34:32.973
which will have some connectivity,

02:34:33.053 --> 02:34:35.133
which tells that it is wet or not
or whatever.

02:34:36.533 --> 02:34:39.013
Same tech you could be using,
let's say, in the ring.

02:34:39.093 --> 02:34:43.053
I just found out a tech
where my daughter--

02:34:43.133 --> 02:34:46.373
My wife wanted to monitor
my daughter about fever.

02:34:46.453 --> 02:34:48.093
And you can't measure
every time for a kid.

02:34:48.173 --> 02:34:52.333
So, there was a socks she could wear
when she was six months or a year.

02:34:52.413 --> 02:34:56.773
It could track the sleep,
the temperature and everything. So...

02:34:57.653 --> 02:35:00.533
These are micro-niche markets,
but yeah, innovations are there.

02:35:00.613 --> 02:35:02.893
What's the deal with these rings
that you are wearing?

02:35:02.973 --> 02:35:05.093
Why are they growing so much?
Why is everybody buying them?

02:35:05.893 --> 02:35:11.653
So, I think market moves
in different form factors.

02:35:12.493 --> 02:35:15.653
And market need newness.

02:35:16.933 --> 02:35:20.733
This form factor, like watches,
are maybe mass-adoption phase,

02:35:20.813 --> 02:35:22.413
whatever phase you want to call.

02:35:23.693 --> 02:35:26.573
Rings are a new category, early adopters.

02:35:27.533 --> 02:35:30.053
And people are getting
more health conscious, also.

02:35:30.973 --> 02:35:33.933
So, they are pairing it
with their watches, by the way.

02:35:34.013 --> 02:35:35.653
They are not a replacement for a watch.

02:35:35.733 --> 02:35:38.773
Is that an opportunity,
health-related consumer electronics?

02:35:40.253 --> 02:35:41.813
You guys seeing any trends there?

02:35:41.893 --> 02:35:44.813
So, I wear a WHOOP on my feet.

02:35:46.373 --> 02:35:50.493
So, what I have realised,
I am into, I mean...

02:35:50.573 --> 02:35:52.933
I am little bit into this space,
so I understand it.

02:35:53.773 --> 02:35:56.773
So, consumer is saying it's good to have.

02:35:57.373 --> 02:36:00.733
Meaning, I want a fitness device,
but I will not track fitness.

02:36:00.813 --> 02:36:04.053
I mean, you would see a guy
wearing a WHOOP-- I was talking--

02:36:04.133 --> 02:36:08.813
and eating a McDonald's burger
and a cola and a 100 kilos.

02:36:09.693 --> 02:36:13.013
So, it's just visual cues to tell people

02:36:13.093 --> 02:36:15.533
that I belong to this universe
where I know.

02:36:16.493 --> 02:36:19.493
I want to know what I am,
but they are not cautious.

02:36:19.573 --> 02:36:23.653
I think they are little bit aware of it,
but not that--

02:36:23.733 --> 02:36:25.453
India is a market, internationally, yes.

02:36:25.533 --> 02:36:28.533
People are more and more health conscious.

02:36:28.613 --> 02:36:30.133
Preventive healthcare is...

02:36:30.213 --> 02:36:33.413
-You know that patch which measures--
-CGM.

02:36:33.493 --> 02:36:35.373
-Insulin spikes.
-Yeah.

02:36:35.453 --> 02:36:37.653
I have always been thinking
that at some point

02:36:37.733 --> 02:36:39.173
an Apple Watch can start doing that.

02:36:39.253 --> 02:36:43.533
Do you think that's an opportunity,
if your watch has a CGM monitor in it?

02:36:43.613 --> 02:36:47.573
So, if you look at use cases,
so I think these devices--

02:36:47.653 --> 02:36:52.573
Okay, diabetic is a very big used case,
this problem.

02:36:52.653 --> 02:36:55.853
And this doesn't work, by the way.
Nobody uses it.

02:36:55.933 --> 02:36:59.533
For us, we have used for wellness,
but diabetic patient also doesn't use it.

02:36:59.613 --> 02:37:01.253
It is 5,000 bucks, it's too expensive.

02:37:01.333 --> 02:37:02.813
And nobody wants to break it every time.

02:37:04.253 --> 02:37:06.653
So, we feel wearable gonna divert
towards health side,

02:37:06.733 --> 02:37:08.013
like we were talking about.

02:37:08.093 --> 02:37:09.453
Health is a segment.

02:37:09.533 --> 02:37:11.693
Thirty-five plus,
you start getting those problems.

02:37:11.773 --> 02:37:13.973
Apple is 100% working on it.

02:37:14.053 --> 02:37:20.253
But Apple will only come when it becomes
really solid, mainstream, proven,

02:37:20.333 --> 02:37:21.653
because it's health.

02:37:21.733 --> 02:37:24.053
Is there no opportunity unique to India?

02:37:24.133 --> 02:37:26.773
What do we want in health
that other people don't want?

02:37:26.853 --> 02:37:28.173
No, I think, no.

02:37:28.253 --> 02:37:30.253
This is a good space
if somebody is working on it.

02:37:30.973 --> 02:37:32.493
Honestly,
I would like to invest in a space

02:37:32.573 --> 02:37:34.173
where people are working on CGM.

02:37:34.253 --> 02:37:35.373
So, Apple is working.

02:37:35.453 --> 02:37:37.693
Samsung has a huge R&amp;D centre
in Bangalore,

02:37:37.773 --> 02:37:43.013
where they are working on
blood pressure and CGM on device,

02:37:43.093 --> 02:37:44.413
where it's non-invasive.

02:37:44.493 --> 02:37:46.653
So, I think in two-three years time
we will see it there.

02:37:47.973 --> 02:37:52.013
I believe in health.
Health has PMF in consumer electronics.

02:37:52.093 --> 02:37:56.173
And another field that has PMF
is children's education.

02:37:56.253 --> 02:37:59.693
Parents are always willing to invest
in the future of their kids.

02:38:00.653 --> 02:38:02.293
What would that look like?

02:38:02.373 --> 02:38:04.733
We have a common friend
who is building this company

02:38:04.813 --> 02:38:09.573
called SuperLearn, where--

02:38:10.373 --> 02:38:15.813
He is trying to build a tablet
which costs $150,

02:38:15.893 --> 02:38:18.853
where you can't, like,
really browse the net

02:38:18.933 --> 02:38:20.973
and go to YouTube and Netflix,

02:38:21.773 --> 02:38:24.133
but replace your school bag
with that device.

02:38:24.213 --> 02:38:26.653
You mean learning like that? Do you think
something like that could work?

02:38:26.733 --> 02:38:27.733
That could work.

02:38:27.813 --> 02:38:31.253
It could also be, like,
some form of smartwatch for kids,

02:38:31.333 --> 02:38:33.573
for learning, maybe with an AI companion.

02:38:33.653 --> 02:38:35.093
It could also just be a teddy bear.

02:38:35.853 --> 02:38:37.773
That's there, no? The toy is there.

02:38:37.853 --> 02:38:40.013
Miko-- Miko is doing good.

02:38:40.893 --> 02:38:44.533
I just know that it's a space
where people want to spend money

02:38:44.613 --> 02:38:45.853
and are not price sensitive.

02:38:46.733 --> 02:38:48.733
So, you-- Wherever you are spending,

02:38:48.813 --> 02:38:50.733
you will spend for your parents,
you will spend for your kids.

02:38:50.813 --> 02:38:51.813
And your health.

02:38:52.773 --> 02:38:53.893
And health.

02:38:53.973 --> 02:38:56.093
What do you guys think of Elon Musk
in Neuralink?

02:38:56.173 --> 02:38:57.733
I like the thesis.

02:38:57.813 --> 02:39:01.413
It's trying to make the communication
more efficient.

02:39:02.773 --> 02:39:06.733
Efficiency is always beneficial
to humanity.

02:39:06.813 --> 02:39:09.213
But maybe there are other ways
to get to higher efficiency.

02:39:09.293 --> 02:39:13.933
I don't know how long it will take
for that to really work for mass market.

02:39:14.573 --> 02:39:16.173
Do you think people will be willing
to do that?

02:39:16.853 --> 02:39:19.373
Like, put something in your body,
not on your body?

02:39:20.773 --> 02:39:22.613
If the benefits are there, I think so.

02:39:22.693 --> 02:39:26.573
But currently...
I don't think the benefits are there.

02:39:26.653 --> 02:39:29.053
Just dovetailing into his question.

02:39:29.133 --> 02:39:31.733
Wherein, these days,
people are talking more about organic.

02:39:32.293 --> 02:39:35.533
They don't want to take
unnecessary medicines and...

02:39:37.333 --> 02:39:39.893
I mean, for somebody who is disabled,

02:39:39.973 --> 02:39:42.773
then they get a lot of benefit
from using that product today.

02:39:43.373 --> 02:39:45.413
But at what point
does it become beneficial

02:39:45.493 --> 02:39:48.333
for a normal person to use that? And why?

02:39:48.413 --> 02:39:51.013
I think there is still some time to go.

02:39:51.893 --> 02:39:53.773
Wouldn't you suddenly become
so much smarter

02:39:53.853 --> 02:39:56.693
if you have something in your head
which is telling you everything?

02:39:57.973 --> 02:40:01.933
You can almost have that already now
if you have earbuds with ChatGPT.

02:40:02.013 --> 02:40:03.693
You can speak to ChatGPT voice.

02:40:03.773 --> 02:40:05.493
-With the AI glass also coming.
-[Carl] Yeah.

02:40:05.573 --> 02:40:07.893
You are sitting in front of this.
This is the setup. This is happening--

02:40:07.973 --> 02:40:12.453
That's way easier to adopt
than operating something into your body.

02:40:12.533 --> 02:40:14.493
What happens to the world? Like...

02:40:14.573 --> 02:40:16.533
If intelligence is on call,

02:40:17.213 --> 02:40:20.613
traditional intelligence is on call
or information is on call,

02:40:22.293 --> 02:40:23.653
we still have to differentiate.

02:40:24.293 --> 02:40:25.293
How do we do that?

02:40:26.093 --> 02:40:27.773
I think most people are going to...

02:40:28.453 --> 02:40:30.733
I think 80% of the population
will just chill

02:40:30.813 --> 02:40:32.533
and receive income from the government.

02:40:33.293 --> 02:40:36.013
And a small group of people
will leverage the new technologies

02:40:36.093 --> 02:40:38.653
to push society and humanity forward.

02:40:38.733 --> 02:40:40.213
Like universal basic income.

02:40:40.293 --> 02:40:42.413
Yeah. I think that will happen for sure.

02:40:42.493 --> 02:40:43.733
Yeah?

02:40:43.813 --> 02:40:47.173
I think you can't replace, you know,
emotional quotient out of that.

02:40:47.253 --> 02:40:49.853
You know, that's what makes
all of us unique.

02:40:50.493 --> 02:40:51.493
All of us--

02:40:51.573 --> 02:40:54.253
You give us the same piece of information
to all four of us,

02:40:54.333 --> 02:40:56.693
all four of us will behave differently

02:40:56.773 --> 02:40:58.613
and will have different actions.

02:40:58.693 --> 02:41:00.053
I think that is something which...

02:41:02.813 --> 02:41:03.973
you can't take away.

02:41:06.453 --> 02:41:07.453
Do you think?

02:41:08.213 --> 02:41:10.893
A little bit agree on this.

02:41:10.973 --> 02:41:13.333
Basic, I think 80% of the jobs
will be done,

02:41:13.413 --> 02:41:17.013
for 20% you would still need human...

02:41:17.093 --> 02:41:19.293
The productivity will increase so much.

02:41:19.373 --> 02:41:22.093
But I think he is also right
that we all will become more lazy.

02:41:22.173 --> 02:41:24.053
Like, kids today
don't need to use their brain.

02:41:24.133 --> 02:41:26.173
They will be doing everything on...

02:41:26.853 --> 02:41:28.573
You need to be very self-motivated,

02:41:28.653 --> 02:41:30.693
but those people
can really leverage the technology

02:41:30.773 --> 02:41:33.013
to create so much more productivity.

02:41:33.093 --> 02:41:34.853
I wonder if a kid will think tomorrow

02:41:34.933 --> 02:41:38.533
if I can just regurgitate a book
from my device at any point,

02:41:38.613 --> 02:41:39.733
then why read the book?

02:41:40.373 --> 02:41:42.293
That's how I was thinking
when I was in school.

02:41:42.373 --> 02:41:44.133
-Like, I can just Google the information.
-[Amit] Yeah.

02:41:44.213 --> 02:41:45.573
Why should I memorise this?

02:41:45.653 --> 02:41:48.213
Okay. Last part.

02:41:48.293 --> 02:41:51.573
I want each of you guys to give one advice

02:41:51.653 --> 02:41:56.293
to me, the 25-year-old,
having watched this today.

02:41:56.973 --> 02:41:59.413
Tomorrow morning I want to wake up
and figure out what to build.

02:41:59.493 --> 02:42:00.773
One piece of advice.

02:42:01.653 --> 02:42:02.733
Would you like to go first?

02:42:06.213 --> 02:42:11.853
I think if somebody needs to
plan something in this space

02:42:11.933 --> 02:42:13.853
or whatever space, I think,

02:42:14.573 --> 02:42:17.453
definitely a thorough research is needed.

02:42:17.533 --> 02:42:19.853
I mean, why you're going in, and--

02:42:19.933 --> 02:42:22.453
I think you need to have that fuel
or patience also to build it.

02:42:22.533 --> 02:42:25.253
That passion we are talking about

02:42:25.333 --> 02:42:29.853
and do pick up a narrow niche
instead of going too broad.

02:42:30.413 --> 02:42:34.693
I mean, pick up a smaller subset
of whatever problem you want to solve.

02:42:34.773 --> 02:42:36.453
Go double down and then move on.

02:42:37.373 --> 02:42:39.573
Definitely there are going to be
failures, learnings--

02:42:39.653 --> 02:42:43.613
But I would term them as learnings
and you keep pivoting with that.

02:42:43.693 --> 02:42:44.733
So that would be one thing.

02:42:45.853 --> 02:42:49.133
I would say be really sure
that you want to do something.

02:42:50.133 --> 02:42:51.493
It's not always fun.

02:42:52.893 --> 02:42:55.173
I think most people
should not be entrepreneurs.

02:42:55.253 --> 02:42:59.333
Most people have a much higher
quality of life doing other things,

02:42:59.413 --> 02:43:03.773
specialising in a tech field
or working for somebody else.

02:43:04.693 --> 02:43:06.613
Very inspiring advice

02:43:06.693 --> 02:43:09.213
to wannabe entrepreneurs, Carl,
I must say.

02:43:10.453 --> 02:43:14.373
It's better to say it now, right,
rather than finding out down the line?

02:43:14.453 --> 02:43:15.813
[Rahul] He is scaring us.

02:43:15.893 --> 02:43:16.893
Just be really sure.

02:43:16.973 --> 02:43:21.893
I think, like, it needs to come from
a deep passion around something

02:43:21.973 --> 02:43:23.373
because it's going to be hard.

02:43:23.453 --> 02:43:27.653
There will be euphoric days,
but there will also be terrible days.

02:43:27.733 --> 02:43:30.613
Like, lack of sleep for weeks. Like--

02:43:30.693 --> 02:43:32.973
I mean, we've all
been through that probably.

02:43:33.973 --> 02:43:37.373
Why are you going to keep pushing forward
when you face those difficulties?

02:43:37.453 --> 02:43:41.253
I think you've got to be sure
that this is what you really want to do,

02:43:41.333 --> 02:43:42.453
that you're passionate about it.

02:43:43.773 --> 02:43:46.173
I believe in the potential
of every individual person.

02:43:46.253 --> 02:43:49.373
Like, if you really want to
accomplish something, you can.

02:43:49.453 --> 02:43:52.613
But there's a cost associated with it.

02:43:53.253 --> 02:43:56.773
And I think for most people,
the cost is not worth it.

02:43:58.133 --> 02:43:59.133
Rahul?

02:44:00.173 --> 02:44:04.213
My only advice will be
show me your five friends.

02:44:06.213 --> 02:44:07.333
Because...

02:44:10.493 --> 02:44:14.813
if you have to build a successful company,
then you have to keep a good company.

02:44:15.773 --> 02:44:18.013
So, if you have--
And you will become like that.

02:44:19.853 --> 02:44:24.813
So, if you have a good company
of people, who are like-minded,

02:44:27.133 --> 02:44:30.933
then even if you have, you know,
there's certain qualities

02:44:31.013 --> 02:44:33.653
and things which you don't possess,
you can, you know...

02:44:35.213 --> 02:44:38.413
A, rely, learn, and do,

02:44:39.133 --> 02:44:40.933
and, you know, come up with...

02:44:42.533 --> 02:44:44.053
come out of various difficulties.

02:44:44.133 --> 02:44:49.653
So, basically you will become, like,
whatever your company is.

02:44:49.733 --> 02:44:51.693
So, if your company is, like,

02:44:51.773 --> 02:44:56.013
there are guys who are doing other things,

02:44:56.093 --> 02:44:59.333
you will eventually, you will go that way.

02:45:00.173 --> 02:45:04.213
But if you have
five people reading biology,

02:45:06.813 --> 02:45:08.413
you will certainly go down that path.

02:45:08.493 --> 02:45:11.093
Even if you are not--
You don't want to learn,

02:45:11.173 --> 02:45:14.133
you say, "No, I am not a bio person,
I am a physics person."

02:45:14.213 --> 02:45:15.973
But, at least, you are doing physics.

02:45:17.173 --> 02:45:19.493
You are not just doing anything else.

02:45:20.373 --> 02:45:24.253
So, just keep a cohort of those people...

02:45:26.853 --> 02:45:28.093
and I think you will--

02:45:29.093 --> 02:45:30.653
A lot of things will get resolved.

02:45:30.733 --> 02:45:32.133
Fair.

02:45:32.213 --> 02:45:33.613
My fleeting thought,

02:45:34.333 --> 02:45:37.533
I am quite excited
about this component incubator.

02:45:38.213 --> 02:45:42.173
I would say let's each of us
put in a little bit of money,

02:45:42.253 --> 02:45:44.293
not care too much about the upside,

02:45:45.013 --> 02:45:47.013
and try and get not too many.

02:45:47.093 --> 02:45:48.973
I think we should find four kids,

02:45:49.053 --> 02:45:51.613
support them in building
a component company

02:45:51.693 --> 02:45:53.493
with time, money and all of that.

02:45:54.373 --> 02:45:58.333
And maybe other people can learn
from what we have done and replicate.

02:45:58.413 --> 02:45:59.613
And I hope we are successful.

02:46:00.533 --> 02:46:02.773
But, thank you to each one of you

02:46:02.853 --> 02:46:06.093
for flying into my home and doing this.

02:46:06.693 --> 02:46:09.453
Very kind and I will reach out to you

02:46:09.533 --> 02:46:13.813
for different kinds of advice
at different points of time,

02:46:13.893 --> 02:46:16.853
and also to help all the young
wannabe entrepreneurs in India.

02:46:16.933 --> 02:46:18.333
But, thank you.

02:46:18.413 --> 02:46:21.013
No, no. Thank you so much.
Thanks for the great food.

02:46:21.093 --> 02:46:22.213
-[Amit] Good food.
-[Rahul] Loved it.

02:46:22.293 --> 02:46:23.333
Thank you guys.

02:46:26.653 --> 02:46:28.133
Like a high protein...

02:46:28.213 --> 02:46:31.013
It's protein powder,
yoghurt, and dark chocolate.

02:46:31.093 --> 02:46:34.453
-Very nice.
-Yeah. It's all, like, really clean food.

02:46:35.293 --> 02:46:36.933
Did you guys have fun? Was that okay?

02:46:37.013 --> 02:46:38.253
-[Amit] Yeah, yeah.
-It was superb.

